</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CLEAN AIR AND EMERGING ALTERNATIVE FUEL VEHICLES:
Executive Summary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">July 1996<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">CLEAN AIR AND EMERGING ALTERNATIVE
FUEL VEHICLES:</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">A Time for Environmental Innovation
Areas<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">By Bruce Yandle, Andy H. Barnett and Mark
Brandly<B><SUP><a href="end.html">*</a></SUP> <BR>
<BR>
</B></FONT></B>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Advances in technology are perhaps the single
most important ingredient of further progress in providing a cleaner
environment for America and the world.  New clean-up technologies,
more efficient production processes - and simply the transition
from a smokestack-laden industrial economy to a digital economy
- provide the opportunity for today's Americans to live in a dramatically
cleaner world than the one their parents left them.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Unhappily, current environmental policies often
lock obsolete technologies in place, or fail to provide appropriate
incentives for the development and adoption of new technologies
that are both cleaner and less costly than those currently in
use.  Even where our current policies work to encourage the adoption
of new technologies, they do so in ways that are often ineffective,
typically through the use of top-down, command-and-control mandates.
<p> 
Current policies also fail, in many cases, to recognize that
while our commitment to a cleaner environment is national in scope,
the problem is often local or regional in nature - and hence not
easily addressed through national, one-size-fits-all standards.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">America's current policies with respect to
air pollution are a case in point.  Since the 1970s, we achieved
significant progress in reducing emissions, but never enough to
meet clean air standards nationwide.  In response, the 1990 Clean
Air Act Amendments set different rules for the most polluted regions
and called for the development and deployment of new technologies
- including alternative fuel (nonpetroleum-based) vehicles (AFVs).
Yet in implementing a complex patchwork of programs to promote
AFVs, the Executive Branch is utilizing top-down mandates that
attempt to impose a uniform regime on an environmental problem
that varies dramatically by region.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The clean air benefits of AFVs vary widely
by region for two reasons.  First, the types of air pollution
AFVs address are limited mainly to 22 cities, the state of California
and a 12-state region in the Northeast.  Second, the best way
of addressing these pollution problems also varies - in some cases,
AFVs may be the better approach; in other cases, different options
will be more effective.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">At the same time, the national security benefits
of AFVs (i.e., the reduction in American dependence on imported
petroleum) know no regional boundaries and hence call for a national
approach to encourage AFVs.  Achieving national promotion of AFVs
while maintaining regional flexibility in their use to reduce
air pollution is a complex challenge.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Among different alternative fuel technologies
being developed, compressed natural gas and liquefied natural
gas offer the best prospects for AFV expansion.  And while the
infrastructure problem associated with refueling and delivery
of alternative fuels is a challenge, the hurdles for serving important
markets have been reduced significantly in recent years.  In fact,
in some important niche markets, conversion to alternative fuels
is justified on differences in fuel costs alone.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The current government approach to providing
incentives for AFV use is neither efficient nor effective.  For
example, our examination of current policies shows that:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The peculiar atmospheric traits of different
urban areas are not recognized by federal standards designed to
reduce urban smog.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Efforts by the Department of Energy to
encourage AFV use and federal mandates for the expansion of AFVs
in the federal fleet are not coordinated with EPA's efforts to
improve air quality in metropolitan regions.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal fuel tax policies are not well
geared to provide larger incentives for cleaner-burning fuels.
(State fuel tax incentives are more closely tied to emission characteristics.)</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The mandated purchase of AFVs by operators
of public and private fleets for the purpose of providing national
security benefits is not accompanied by financial incentives for
covering incremental costs.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Heavy-duty trucks and other large vehicles,
which offer bright prospects for AFV use, are not covered by federal
statutes designed to encourage AFV use.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">America needs a new, more effective and efficient
approach to promoting AFVs.  Among its main features should be:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">A program of Environmental Innovation Areas
(EIAs) that recognize the peculiar environmental challenges of
U.S. cities and regions.  These newly created EIAs should be given
complete flexibility in choosing the means for meeting baseline
environmental standards and should serve as coordinating units
for federal efforts to expand AFV use.   </FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal fuel taxes that no longer favor
or discriminate against alternative fuels used in the search for
cleaner air.  Instead, tax policy should be designed to provide
incentives for the use of cleaner fuels that address emission
problems reaching far beyond the limits of cities and multi-state
regions.  States and regions should be encouraged to design fuel
taxes that encourage the appropriate use of cleaner burning fuels
in their areas.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Furthermore,</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal funds to cover the full incremental
cost of AFVs should accompany federal mandates that require nonfederal
fleet AFV purchases.  Based on past legislative goals considered
by Congress, funding for light AFVs could amount to as much as
$326 million annually.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are a variety of existing tax subsidy
and expenditure programs that could be redeployed to at least
partly offset this cost.</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Because AFVs both pollute less and reduce
American reliance on imported petroleum, incentives for AFV use
are a lower-cost way to improve automobile fuel efficiency than
Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> By removing barriers to expanded AFV use and
deployment of other improved technologies, implementation of these
proposals would reduce the cost of achieving environmental and
national energy security goals.  This plan would expand AFV use
and concentrate environmental benefits in the most appropriate
geographical areas.  Among other benefits of such a program would
be:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Multiple Environmental Innovation Areas
(EIAs) that will provide a national laboratory for discovering
lower cost institutions for improving all dimensions of environmental
quality.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The more logical expansion of AFV infrastructure
due to the creative and expanded use of EIAs and federally provided
funds to assist with the expansion of the AFV fleet.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Minimized costs in producing cleaner air
through the encouragement of tradeoffs between AFVs and other
approaches for reducing air pollution.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Improved technological innovation through
the adoption of new technology.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There is no magic bullet or one best approach
for reducing air pollution in the United States.  A successful
policy for the 21st century will rely on a multitude of solutions
that emerge from those closest to the problem.  AFVs are a proven
technology that offer meaningful environmental benefits.  With
appropriate incentives and flexible institutions for accomplishing
environmental goals, AFVs can become an even more important part
of the environmental arsenal.</FONT>

<p><br>
<a href="sect1.html">Next Section: Introduction</a><p>
<a href="end.html">End Notes</a>
<HR>
<P>
<font size=2>Future Insight, <I>a series of occasional papers
issued by PFF, offer replacement models for current regulatory
agencies, departments and laws designed at the height of the Industrial
Era with organizations better suited to meeting the needs of citizens
in the Digital Age.  A private, non-profit, non-partisan idea
center established in 1993, The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation
aims to create a positive vision of the future founded in the
historic principles of the American Idea.  It brings together
a diverse group of thinkers and policy experts and shares their
work with the American people through seminars, conferences, publications
and electronic media of all forms.  Supported by tax deductible
donations from corporations, foundations and individuals, PFF
does not engage in lobbying activities or take positions on legislation.
 The views expressed here are solely those of the author(s) and
do not necessarily represent the views of the Board, Officers
or Staff of The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation.</I></FONT>

<P>
<CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=2>Permission granted to reproduce as long
as acknowledgment is made.<BR>
</FONT></I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=2>Richard F. O'Donnell, Editor<BR>
</FONT></I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=2>The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation
<I> 1301 K Street, N.W., Suite 650 West  Washington, DC 20005</I></FONT></I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=2>voice: 202/289-8928 <I> fax: 202/289-6079
 e-mail: <a href="mailto:mail@pff.org">mail@pff.org</a>  internet: 
<a href="http://www.pff.org">www.pff.org</a></I></FONT></I></CENTER>
