<html><head><title>From Virtuality to Reality -- PFF</title></head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h1>From Virtuality to Reality</h1>

<b>by Newt Gingrich</b>
<P><br>

Since the mid-1960s people have been talking about computers and the
information revolution. Drucker's The Age of Discontinuities, Boulding's,
The Meaning of the 20th Century and Bell's Beyond Post-Industrial Society
were all precursors to the first popularizer of this notion, which was
Future Shock by Heidi and Alvin Toffler -- and that was written basically a
quarter of a century ago.
<P>
Now, those four books described everything we're living through for all
practical purposes, except the details, and nothing has changed for a
quarter century. That leaves us with an interesting question: Since this is
all intellectually obvious, why can't we break through? Why, given this
potential of information, have we been so slow and so timid to embrace the
Third Wave?
<P>
I think the essence of this occurs at two levels.
<P>
The first was put forward by C.P. Snow in a 1959 BBC lectures series called
"The Two Cultures." Snow, who is a novelist, politician and a Ph.D. in
physics, argued that over the last century, and particularly the last 60
years, Western Civilization had broken into two cultures: a scientific
engineering culture that largely spoke the language of math, and an arts
and literary culture that largely spoke the language of literary allusion.
These two cultures had grown further and further apart, with the result, if
I can summarize in the modern era, that those who know are inarticulate,
and those who are articulate don't know. If you're capable of being glib
and verbal, the odds are you have no idea what you're talking about but it
sounds good; whereas if you know a great deal of what you're saying, the
odds are you can't get on a talk show because nobody can understand you.
<P>
You end up with more and more politicians and more and more reporters who
cover things they don't have a clue about, while people who understand the
potential literally cannot express that potential in a common language in a
way that people understand.
<P>
Two major facts compound the problem. One is that most entrepreneurs who
make breakthroughs are almost by definition psychologically uninterested in
working in dull, slow processes in which most of your time is spent
listening to people who don't know as much as you. The other is that the
science and engineering communities' are against being politically active
in any kind of practical sense. Thus with entrepreneurs and scientists not
engaged in governing, you end up with a society in which lawyers dominate,
so we get more laws to sue the few engineers who are left.
<P>
There is a second failure as to why we haven't broken through into the
Third Wave yet, and it's largely a failure of the imagination. If you ask
me intellectually where we are -- and this is directly out of the Toffler's
work, so it won't surprise most of you -- I would argue that the most
accurate analogy for where we are right now is not 1933, it's the 1770s to
1800. Just as the English-speaking world went through the transition from
the end of the medieval agrarian society to the rise of the commercial and
ultimately manufacturing society and out of that came waves of change that
were very traumatic and very profound, so the transition from the
industrial era into the information age is very similar in forcing us to
ask the most profound questions about relationships.
<P>
The greatest single works of that earlier period were intellectually both
by the same man, and it's interesting that the one we seldom talk about,
The Theory of Moral Sentiments by Adam Smith, which proceeds and frames The
Wealth of Nations, is an inherently philosophical and moral work, seeking
to understand how it is that human beings function and what it is that
drives them in concluding, as he put it, that there is a man in the mirror
and that each of us internally in some way seek to justify ourselves to
what we would call a conscience.
<P>
Later he wrote what was largely, much like Alexis de Tocqueville, a book of
reporting. That is, if you read The Wealth of Nations as the description by
a political philosopher of the changes he was literally living through as
Britain began to shift out of the medieval guild society into the
commercial world market society, it is almost the economic parable to de
Tocqueville, who later does the same thing for an American society making
the transition from republican virtue to democratic commercialism. Now, in
that setting, the Founding Fathers, the Federalist Papers, the Constitution
are in a sense all driven by this larger world view, this wrestling with
the nature of freedom and the nature of human beings, their relationship to
their creator and where they're going.
<P>
It's from this that you then begin to get radical change. Now, in the
United States it's easy and obvious. We have a revolution, the Articles of
Confederation fail, we have a second try. And this is why I keep telling
people don't worry about occasional failures. The second try is the
Constitution. It's worked reasonably well now for over 200 years. But it
wasn't their first product.
<P>
Now, I gave you that background because I think what we're missing in part
is: A) the ability to get people who are willing to think broadly enough
about basic issues and then draw conclusions from their thought, and B) the
willingness by politicians to take those ideas and begin to apply them
directly to the modern world and to begin to say, okay, if these principles
are true, what, then, should we do? For instance, I recently got some
excitement because I said we need to transform Medicare, which was, by the
way, promptly denounced by some people who say Gingrich wants to abolish
Medicare, which is not what the word "transform" means at all.
<P>
But my argument's very simple. Everywhere on the planet, we are saying that
the information age means more decentralization, more market orientation,
more freedom for individuals, more opportunity for choice, more capacity to
be productive without controls by the state. So we go to Poland, Hungary,
Russia, you name it, China, and then you look at the Health Care Financing
Administration, a mid-1960s effort to apply European centralized
bureaucracy to health care for the elderly, and which is having, by the
way, precisely the long-term results you'd expect. It is gradually cheating
doctors and hospitals and will presently cheat the elderly. And it is
producing a very expensive, very bureaucratic product which is not allowing
the citizen themselves to have any choice about the expenditure of their
funds for their lives.
<P>
Now it seems to me you could make a pretty good argument -- and given
everything we're saying to everybody else on the planet this ought to be a
no-brainer -- we can offer better health care with greater choices at
higher quality for more senior citizens by transforming Medicare than we
can by the next 200 task forces on paperwork at the Health Care Financing
Administration. Now, what makes that possible?
<P>
Well, one of the challenges I've made to doctors is to tell them we can
either go to Canada or to Walmart. You can either go to a nationally
controlled bureaucratic structure or you can go to the marketplace, but
you're not going to stay in a guild status where you have all the knowledge
but share none of it. And I'll give you a simple example: My wife had a
thyroid problem a couple of years ago, she called three different
specialists and said, "What do you charge?" None of them would tell her.
That's nuts.
<P>
And you should be able to access easily the database that says, "Here are
the doctors in the area; here's what they charge; here's what their
outcomes are like" before you walk in. And, by the way, "Here's where they
studied and here's what therapies they believe in."
<P>
It's not a lack of potential to do this. It's not a lack of ability to put
it on-line. It's not a lack of ability to teach people. Many of you will
remember when people didn't pump gas because, it was said, if everyday
citizens pumped gas, they'd set their cars on fire; you can't really let
people go out and put their own gas in their car; I mean, who knows what
they'll do; they'll be making molatov cocktails and throwing them at each
other; bad things will happen. How many of you remember this debate? This
was a serious debate in the 1970s all across the country.
<P>
Now, in that framework, let me give you a way of thinking about this. First
of all, I believe that the central issues of our time are cultural; they
are not political. What drove me to this belief was an analogy. The
questions I was trying to figure out was why do Americans do bureaucracy
badly. Why is it that bureaucratic models objectively, outside the military
and very small elite groups like the National Parks Service or the FBI, do
not work well?
<P>
As a general principal, create a bureaucracy in America and watch the decay
set in. And yet that's not automatically true about bureaucracy as a
system.
<P>
One can argue that much of Chinese history was remarkably bureaucratic and
pretty good. You can argue that German bureaucracy is a very impressive
model. Thus the conclusion was that Americans' problem with bureaucracy is
cultural. I don't know how many of you have been in Germany. As you know,
in Germany, on the Autobahn, there's no speed limit. You can go literally
any speed you want. Many Americans rent a car, they're doing 100, they're
excited and a Mercedes goes by at 160, they pull over and cry and they
never fully recover from the experience.
<P>
If tomorrow morning the Bundestag adopted 100-kilometer or 62- mile-an-hour
speed limit, virtually every German would obey it the next day, and at the
next election they would massacre the current generation of politicians and
they would elect The No Speed Limit Party.
<P>
Now, I'm always cautious about this because I don't want to offend anybody,
but my understanding is that the American cultural response to the
challenge of speed limits is substantially different from the German
cultural response.
<P>
In most of America, a speed limit is a benchmark of opportunity. Let me
just ask you a question. How many of you find that as a norm you look at
the posted number and add five or 10?
<P>
This, to me, was one of the two moments I became a revolutionary. A country
in which virtually every citizen drives over the speed limit it is
impossible to lead by bureaucratic regulation. By definition. And this is
why the Clinton health plan last year was so crazy. By definition, a nation
driven by incentives will wake up every morning and say, how do I get
around the rule; what can my lawyer find for me; is there a consultant who
knows the loopholes? And because the incentive for the individual always
beats the incentive for the system, the bureaucracy will always be one
layer behind and will be adding the complexity to the answer you had last
week, just when you found the new answer this week. The long-term cost
being that we absorb more and more resources into paperwork, bureaucracy,
blaming, litigation and all the horrors that we now have. An utterly
mindless and destructive system.
<P>
And part of my argument as a grand strategy is, we ought to go through and
wipe most of it out. If there's not some overwhelming reason for doing it,
quit doing it. You may not gain much profit but at least the pain will go
down.
<P>
Now, the second example that made me a revolutionary was we developed a
program called "Earning by Learning." We were worried about end states, we
weren't worried about processes; we were worried about outputs, not inputs.
<P>
<P>
We wanted second- and third-graders in public housing to learn how to read.
And so we'd go into public housing with volunteers and we would pay $2 a
book for every kid who would read, and we would do it in a setting where we
used the local public libraries, the books were free, we had the local
commons room so the room was free, we had a volunteer. So the only money
you had to raise, which I normally did just by making speeches and turning
the money over, was you had to pay the kids. If you had 50 kids and they
each read 20 books you had to raise $2,000. A very low-cost, very simple
model, based on incentive.
<P>
We went into Douglas County, Georgia, to the public housing project and an
eight-year-old child said, "You're going to cheat us." And this for me was
the breaking point. This is why, as far I'm concerned, the old order is
gone and the question is just how long it takes to get rid of it. And we
said, "What do you mean, we're going to cheat you?" This kid was eight
years old.
<P>
They said, "You're going to manipulate us into reading and then you won't
pay us." This was an eight-year-old kid who was already gone. I mean, as
far as they were concerned, the whole system was a cheat, all these people
are going to cheat us, you can't trust anybody.
<P>
So we said, all right -- because we believe in responding and listening and
it being a cybernetic system -- we said okay, for your group we'll pay
every week, cash. The first week about seven kids came. We paid them cash.
Read three books, here's six dollars. They had to read the book or answer
questions or in some way prove to the adult that they had mastered this
book.
<P>
These are kid's books, second graders. Six dollars. The following week
there were 14 kids. We said, "What happened?" They said, "Well, when you go
to the ice cream truck and you're buying ice cream and your friend turns to
you and says, how come you have money, you say, well I read, you know."
<P>
Now, my personal guess is that if no more than 10 percent of all current
federal spending for literacy programs was spent through volunteers in this
kind of incentive-driven program, we would begin to move toward 99 percent
literacy -- but it is a totally radically different way of thinking about
life.
<P>
Here are my suggestions for breaking through to this future. First of all,
I believe that during the next few years there's going to be new hope.
<P>
You're going to see genuinely a shift towards a positive, optimistic mood.
<P>
I believe second, there's going to be a new dialogue. That's why Congress
is now on-line and why we're going to change C-SPAN's access to the
Congress. That's why we're going to do a lot of things in public that the
old order did in private, that's why you're going to see a tremendous
effort on our part to reach out. I had a town hall meeting Saturday with
600-plus people. I'll have a town hall meeting every Saturday for the next
10 weeks. And people are going to have access all the time. It is nonsense
that you can't get access to the Speaker unless you pay money. In the sixth
District of Georgia, if you get out of bed, put on your clothes, get in the
car and show up at 2:00 in the afternoon, you have access. And if your
congressman doesn't give you access, fire him and hire one that will.
<P>
After the new hope and the new dialogue, you're going to see us do
something very different. We're going to create a new partnership. The word
partnership is very central to where we're going, and by the way, fits the
information age and I think fits the Internet. Partnership means we both
have responsibilities. Yes, I'll be compassionate, now what are you going
to be? But don't tell me the job is entirely one way. Don't tell me you'd
be glad to be rich but you don't want to work, you'd be glad to be wise but
you don't want to learn. The Declaration of Independence says we are
endowed by our Creator with certain unalienable rights, among which are
life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness. Pursuit implies getting up and
doing it. It doesn't say happiness stamps, it doesn't say happiness
entitlements, it doesn't say we need a federal department of happiness.
<P>
Recently I suggested, and I said at the time it was probably a dumb idea,
to offer a tax credit for laptops. It was a dumb idea; I shouldn't have
said it. But let me tell you what I was trying to get at. I was trying to
get at the idea that instead of saying, wow, all of the really
sophisticated, well-educated, upper middle-class people, you get to be over
here, and so we're going to take 30 percent of the country into the
information age and leave everyone else behind. What we ought to be saying
is we had better care about reaching out a helping hand to every American
and saying we'll do our half, we'll find some way.
<P>
Now maybe it ought to be done by private philanthropy. Maybe it ought to be
done by other kinds of devices. Maybe private companies ought to do it.
<P>
But somehow there has to be a missionary spirit in America that says to the
poorest child in America, "Internet's for you. The information age is for
you. There's an alternative to prostitution, drug abuse and death, and we
are committed to reaching every child in this country. And not in two
generations or three generations; we're committed this year, we're
committed now." If we can wire the world, 84 countries, 42 million people
wired into Internet "Talking to Thomas" in the U.S. Congress, if we can
wire the world, we can wire Washington, D.C., we can wire an Anacostia. We
can find a way to reach out. And I am not, obviously given my background,
recommending that what we do now is adopt a Soviet style centralized
institute of information distribution, but I am trying to
start a debate, a dialogue, and to set up the notion of a partnership
because it will change everything about where we're going.
<P>
The fourth point I would suggest to you is that out of this process a new
team will emerge, so we have new hope leading to a new dialogue creating a
new partnership. And why will a new team emerge? Because people are going
out doing things you don't expect. It is somebody willing to lay it on the
line to entrepreneurially try to create a better future and who's willing
to take the risks of doing it. And you're going to start finding people who
really are making things happen.
<P>
What are the 20 best places in the country on drug addiction? That's
knowable. My guess is that 19 or all of them are private. Where are they?
<P>
Who are their leaders? What are they doing? What are the 20 best places in
the country at taking children born in poverty without family structure and
getting them educated enough to go to college? That's knowable. And I'll
bet you're going to find a lot of them are private. We've got to start
learning from the positives.
<P>
I believe if through our having new hope we have a new dialogue, we can
build a partnership, and a partnership at every level. And that
partnership, by the way, has to involve a radically higher understanding of
the potential of the information age than we have today.
<P>
What you've got to focus on is the notion that somehow we're going to get
information out, we're going to have a dialogue among ourselves, we're
going to get aggregated information back in, we're going to identify the
most interesting and the best ideas, and they're not necessarily going to
come from the people that we know personally or that fit in a social or
credentialed spectrum. I don't know how to do that. It's going to take a
lot of smart people to invent this. We are 1760 not at 1789. We are
beginning to invent the America of the information age, we're not about to
inaugurate George Washington. Let's work together, and usher in the future
for America.
<P>
<i>Newt Gingrich is Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives.</i>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>

