<HEAD>

<TITLE> The Telecommunications Act of 1996 -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2></h2>
<P>
<h2>
The Telecommunications Act of 1996: Intent, Impact and Implications  
</h2>
by Dennis R. Patrick 



<p>

It is refreshing for me to be able to say exactly what I think, unconstrained

as I am by the burdens of chairing the FCC, the context in which I last

addressed some of these issues with some of you. I can remember only too well

my frustration at having to sit through the presentation of some blatantly

anti-competitive presentation calculated to promote the proponent’s business

interest over that of all competitors, and having to respond with something

like:  "You'’ve raised some very important issues; I’ll have the bureau look

at them carefully."

<p>

You should expect my responses these days to be slightly more pointed.

<p>

But before I get any more candid, let me add a quick disclaimer.  I speak

today as a former Chairman, as an individual and as an entrepreneur in this

industry.  As such, my comments reflect my own views only, and not those of

any other individual, institution, or company.  


<p>
Enough said, on to the assignment.  The intention of the Congress, viewing

the Telecommunications Act of 1996 as a whole, seems quite obvious:

<p>
<ul>
<li> To move as quickly as possible toward an open, competitive and largely

unregulated communications marketplace;


<li> replace the regulatory model with a competitive model as the lehead

mechanism for defining and protecting the public interest;

 
<li>To rid ourselves finally from all vestiges of the "public utility" or

"natural monopoly" concept as an intellectual model for thinking about the

industry; and,



<li> To unleash technology and entrepreneurialism so as to maximize consumer

lfare in ways we regulators (ex and otherwise) could never even imagine.<p>

</ul>

To be sure, the Congress has included within the legislation all the relevant

caveats and footnotes, some of which I will address later in my remarks.  But

even with those caveats, I read the bill as reflecting the broad intention I

just described.

<p>

<b>Implications for the Industry<p></b>



It has become almost a cliché, certainly predictable, for speaker after

speaker in our industry to stand up and talk about the scope of the magnitude

of change, peppering his or her remarks with hackneyed phrases like

"Information Superhighway" and "Communications Revolution."

<p>

I’'d love to take a contrarian position and tell you that nothing much is

going to happen.

<p>

But that would be wrong, so I can’'t.

<p>

The Telecommunications Act of 1996 represents a significant milestone.  It

announces that the Federal government is finally, largely, out of the way, or

at least headed in that direction.  It will usher in an era of radical

transformation in the industry the scope and import of which will make

divestiture  look like a footnote in history.

<p>

Make no mistake, this piece of legislation, while I cannot say that I agree

with every line, is a solid and positive step forward.  (Or should I say a

step back to the future.  You do recall that all aspects of the nascent

telecommunications industry were competitive between 1894 and 1907, including

local.)
<p>


Precisely because this Act is much overdue, I predict it will unleash a vast

restructuring of the industry.  It is as if we have removed two bricks from

the edifice of Hoover Dam.  Today, we see a trickle of change; tomorrow we

will see a collapse and reformation of the entire structure.

<p>

Let me comment more specifically on some of the changes that I would predict.

 They can be broken down as between the primary and secondary effects of the

legislation.


<p>
The primary impact is reasonably straight forward: new competitive entry,

intensifying cross industry competition.


<p>
In my view, it is the secondary or "ripple effects" which are of greater

interest.  They include:

<p>
<ul>

<li> Fragmentation in industry structure.  This view is a bit contrarian.

 Especially as we see regional bell operating companies merging, one may be

tempted to leap to the conclusion that removing regulatory barriers may lead

to greater consolidation.  Certainly there will be some consolidation.  But

in the longer term, I suspect that the opportunity for new entry, for the

birth and growth of new technologies and approaches, for the evolution of new

networks... these phenomena will predominate in the longer term, resulting in

a more complex, competitively porous and yes, fragmented industry structure.

 I use the term fragmented not in any pejorative sense but so as to

communicate the opportunity for, and my prediction of, a lot of new entry.



<li> With new entry will come the principal benefits to consumers: intensifying

price and service competition.  The competition will shift away from

Washington and even away from technology, to a very singular focus on

competing for "account control" or consumer loyalty (which is where the focus

should be).  Competitors will compete not only with price, but with bundling

options’, with greater convenience and with pure hype.  It will be a

wonderful thing to behold.



<li> Next on my list of secondary effects is a matter of a general recalibration

of pricing and cost recovery in telephony.  Let me explain briefly for those

of you of who are less familiar with the arcane economics of an industry

distorted by countless years of regulatory interference.



<li> The telephone industry today is characterized by an elaborate web of

non-cost based cross subsidies.  These cross subsidies have been driven by

politics not economics.  The best example, of course, is the funding of

something called "universal service" through a tax which is imposed, in the

initial instance, on long distance carriers and, in the second instance, on

long distance users.  I discuss the matter of funding universal service in

greater detail later.  It suffices to say here that technology and open entry

will find a way to deliver services at their true cost, to the great

detriment of any player forced by regulation to support a non-cost based

subsidy.  Thus my original point: competition will drive prices to costs and

force a recalibration of pricing, subsidies, etc.
<p>
</ul>

Let me close my comments on industry implications by reflecting for a moment

on what drives these changes.  As good a piece of legislation as it is, the

Telecommunications Act of 1996 merely affirms marketplace realities.  That

reality is driven by technology and consumer demand, by entrepreneurs looking

for profit, and by consumer looking for savings and convenience – not by

regulators, not by amateur policy wonks like me or even professional policy

wonks like some of you.

<p>

In my view, we took a left turn, and an incorrect turn, shortly after the

turn of the century when we bought in to a whole set of assumptions which

surround the notion of a "natural monopoly."  These assumptions led in turn,

to a single supplier marketplace, a prohibition on new entry, and -- ipso

facto -- price and service regulation of the monopoly.  

<p>

In the decades which followed, there was no way for us to test the assumption

that there existed a natural monopoly as entry was proscribed.  We’ll never

really know when the technology actually altered the cost characteristics of

the industry such that competitive entry would result in lower, not higher

prices, as the natural monopoly model would assume.

<p>

This model also led to rate base rate of return regulation, hence gold

plating. 
<p>


There also ensued predictably, that perverse relationship that develops

between regulators and the ostensibly regulated industry, especially where

the industry in question has a singular identity.  In that environment,

regulators often become guardians of the status quo, rather than proponents

of pro-consumer change.
<p>


The intellectual log jam I’ve just described was not broken by regulators; it

was broken by entrepreneurs and by technology.  People like Harry Tuttle who

in 1951 had to sue AT&T to allow consumers to attach his Hush-a-Phone to a

telephone mouthpiece; by people like Jack Goeken who in 1967 had to fight a

monumental battle to allow his tiny microwave-based communications company to

carry long distance traffic for 35 users.  Even then, AT&T was arguing that

any diminution in traffic carried by its own network would have the

detrimental effect of raising prices, not lowering them.  It wasn’t true then

and it probably hadn’t been true for decades before.

<p>

In summary, the process of change in our industry has been driven by

entrepreneurship and technology.  In the early period, the drivers were

changing economics of equipment, CPE and private PBX’s as well as microwave

radio networks.  

<p>

Today, changes are driven more on the network side: compression and

digitalization have moved towards commoditizing capacity, denying the big

players the market power they once enjoyed.  In addition, the declining cost

and increasing processing power of computers have altered the economies of

scale, making small competitors more effective.

<p>

This commentary about what actually drives change in our industry provides me

with a natural segue to my final subject, the impact and implications for the

FCC or more generally, for the role of government in this industry.
<p>


<b>Implications for FCC/Government Regulation</b>

<p>

Upon implementing the Act, the FCC should be, and I trust will be, a much

smaller agency with substantially reduced regulatory responsibilities.  Much

of the FCC’s current responsibility should be eliminated by transferring such

responsibilities to (a) the market place; (b) the states; or, (c) other

Federal agencies.  

<p>

I see the Telecommunications Act of 1996 as a clarion call to the Commission

to heed the lessons of history and to fundamentally redefine its role and

relationship to this industry.

<p>

My belief that the scope and nature of the Commission’s responsibilities and

authority should be altered is derived not from any lack of respect for the

Commission, or for the important role it has played to date.  Rather, my

beliefs follow from the following observations:

<p>
<ol>
<li>  Generally, and most fundamentally, free markets serve the interest of

consumers far more efficiently and effectively than government regulation –

in lowering prices, directing resource allocation and in developing

technologies.  



<li> One reason for the comparative superiority of markets involves the

regulators’ inherent lack of adequate information, a phenomenon I observed

up-close and personal for six years at the Commission.  Despite best efforts,

it is impossible for any Federal agency to have access to the hundreds of

millions of pieces of information relevant to technology, consumer demand and

cost benefit trade-offs necessary to make efficient resource allocation

decisions.



One need look no further than the area of spectrum allocation.  Today we have

UHF broadcast stations literally going dark in some cases, while standing

adjacent on the radio spectrum band to 800 MHz cellular telephone licenses

are commanding hundreds of millions of dollars in market value because

consumers value the cellular service.  That disjoint, that dysfunction in

resource allocation, is a direct result of an attempt to engage in central

planning by the U.S. Federal government.



<li>  A third failing of the regulatory process involves its manipulation by

competitors for purposes which ill-serve the interests of consumers.  A

regulation which requires one competitor to justify a products’ price, its

underlying cost, or its availability to all similarly situated is an

invitation to competitors to file a piece of paper contesting "all of the

above."  And it’s a no lose proposition for the intervenor.  At a minimum,

the competitive offering is delayed and, simultaneously, the public interest

is injured.  Thousands of man hours a year at the Commission are spent

inadvertently acting as the pawn of various competitors attempting to

manipulate the process to serve their interest, not the public’s.



<li>  The fourth, and final basis, for my conclusion that we must radically

restructure and reduce the scope of the Commission’s responsibilities

involves the rather obvious expeditious pace of technological change.  If it

ever could, it certainly begs credulity to assume that the Commission can

today keep pace with this change.  For example, the advent of compressed

digital technology literally renders irrelevant the distinction between

voice, video and data, a now purely semantic distinction upon which the

Commission has based a ton of regulatory structure.  In my mind, the only

valuable lines which remain are those which divide competitive from

non-competitive markets.  Technology has rendered not merely inefficacious,

but counter productive, the Commission’s historic penchant to micro-manage

spectrum use.
</ol>

<p>
Let me now address several specific areas in which the FCC can, and in my

opinion should, reduce or eliminate its regulatory intervention.
<p>


<b>Public Utility Regulation</b>

<p>

The Commission’s regulation of price, profit, and the structure of product

offerings (e.g. are they discriminatory?) finds its historical roots in the

so-called "public utility" model.  The public utility model supposes in turn

an absence of competition and, in fact, is driven by an implicit assumption

that the market is not even potentially competitive (i.e., that it is a

natural monopoly).  Obviously this model is completely at odds with the

reality of the modern communications market and its application is

dramatically injurious to our public policy goals.
<p>


All "public utility" regulation should be eliminated unless the market

segment in question is demonstrably non-competitive.  In fact, the Commission

has made significant progress in this direction; Chairman Hundt, and his

colleagues, are to be commended for those efforts.  In particular, the recent

reclassification of AT&T as non-dominant is highly appropriate (and long over

due).

<p>

But, additional deregulation is appropriate.  Some examples follow:

<p>

Private Carriage Contracts.  In the highly competitive market for large

customer contracts, there is no continuing need to require AT&T, MCI, Sprint

or other long distance firms to file single customer filings (e.g. tariff of

12 filings).  These single customer offerings are directed toward the largest

communications customers, companies with sophisticated in-house communication

staff.  As such, FCC tariff filing requirements serve little of the customer

protection purpose traditionally associated with tariff filings.  At best,

they are an unnecessary expense, and at worst, a means of price signaling and

coordination.  They also provide an excuse for competitors to make mischief

by challenging the cost basis or structure of the offering in an attempt to

delay and impede competition.  The effect of these efforts is generally to

slow downward price reductions in a competitive market.  Like the question of

price, the question of whether a product offering is unduly "discriminative"

is inappropriately posed in a competitive market.  Product offerings

customized for particular large buyers, where the market is competitive, are

not likely to be "unreasonable" (i.e., injurious to the public).

<p>

Computer Inquiry Rules.  In the 1980’s, in a series of decisions with which I

was intimately involved, the Commission distinguished regulated basic

telecommunications services from unregulated enhanced services in the

so-called "computer inquiry" cases.  In a well intended effort to deregulate

competitive sectors of the telecommunications market, a series of regulations

were enunciated intended to preclude carriers from leveraging the

noncompetitive side of their business into comparative strength on the

competitive side.  Hence, a series of rules prohibiting bundling and

requiring certain accounting procedures and the like were enunciated.  For

example, long distance companies were prohibited from bundling basic

telephone services with customer equipment or enhanced services.  In

addition, the same companies were required to receive FCC approval of an

affiliate’s offering of enhanced services and to follow precise guidelines

with the respect to the allocation of joint and common costs in the provision

of basic and enhanced services.  In all of these cases, where the basic

service (such as the long distance market today) is effectively competitive,

these regulations are no longer necessary or productive.

<p>

Local Exchange Services.  Regulation of local exchange facilities should be

devolved to the states, except as necessary to assure that interstate users

of local exchange facilities have nondiscriminatory access, and that there

are no barriers to new competitive entrance pursuant to the

Telecommunications Act of 1996.  

<p>

I would emphasize at this point that there is an important transitional role

for the FCC to play in ensuring that the Congress’ intention to provide for

new competitive entry on fair terms is fulfilled.  I am personally aware of

the difficulties cable companies have had gaining fair access to Local

Telephone Exchange facilities in an effort to provide local competitive

alternatives.  Thus, wherever there remain pockets of market power in a

provision of telecommunications services or access facilities, there remains

an important role for the FCC.
<p>


Universal Service.  An important policy goal of the Congress is the

maintenance of universal telephone service.  Generally speaking, the goal of

our universal service policy is to maximize the availability of a defined

level of communication services to all Americans.
<p>


As I mentioned earlier, and as both the Congress and Commission have

recognized, however, the manner in which we support our universal service

goals is in need of radical reform.  Thus, there is currently pending a Joint

Board proceeding to address and revise our policies in this important area,

in particular the subsidy mechanism used to support these goals.

<p>

Without belaboring issues now the subject of a broad inquiry, let me make

several simple points:

<p>

(a) Our current methodology of raising funds in substantial part with usage

sensitive access charges, paid initially by long distance carriers and

ultimately by consumers, distorts the competitive landscape and unfairly

taxes long distance consumers.  Worse, because the support payments are, in

turn, paid to high cost telephone companies, rather than telephone users in

need of financial support to sustain their access to the telephone network,

the current system is unduly expensive (i.e., we raise more money than we

need) and not focused on those truly in need.  The fact is, wealthy residents

in many rural areas are subsidized in their access to local phone service and

the poor in, for example, South Central Los Angeles are not.

<p>

(b) I’d submit that we can substantially reduce the overall amount or cost of

the subsidy and more effectively help the truly needy with a plan guided by

these simple principles:

<p>
<ol>
<li> target individuals, not telephone systems for assistance;



<li> clearly define "universal service" as to the type and level of telephone

services to which "universal" access is thought desirable;



<li> using a defined "means test," identify and make explicit a sum certain

necessary to achieve the universal service objective ("universal service

subsidy target");



<li> raise the subsidy target by requiring all telephone users to contribute a

fixed sum to the subsidy pool; and, 



<li> allow the states to "administer" the subsidy by provision to those

meeting the "means test". 

</ol><p>

The universal service proceeding is one which I would urge the Congress to

monitor closely, as it is one rife with the potential for political

compromise, and much in need of radical restructuring instead.
<p>


<b>Management of the Electro-Magnetic Radio Spectrum</b>

<p>

The current Commission, and indeed, Chairman Hundt, are to be commended for

their strong support of spectrum auctions.  It is ironic that an idea widely

and loudly dismissed by a Democratically controlled Congress when I argued

for it has become such a universally accepted and applauded idea of the

current Administration.  But then, as President Reagan used to say, "There’s

no telling how far we can go if we don’t worry about who gets the credit."

<p>

Spectrum auctions aside, much work remains.  Tremendous new applications in

wireless communications technology today await permission to access spectrum.

 Access to that spectrum by the private sector provides the key to unlocking

a plethora of exciting, innovative, and ever-cheaper services for the public.

 Yet, many parts of the radio band go under-utilized in applications little

valued by the public, while demand exceeds spectrum supply for other

applications.  Indeed, much radio spectrum lies fallow as the Commission

seeks to divine its ultimate use.


<p>
This paradox is a result of a government run, centrally planned allocation of

radio spectrum, a regulatory structure which is increasingly costly in our

dynamic world.  I hasten to add that these inefficient results follow from

the system itself, not from any lack of expertise, competence, or diligence

on the part of the FCC.  The key defect, of course, is an attempt to use a

government funded central planning mechanism to allocate spectrum when even

the most resource-rich players in the private sector cannot keep pace with

the rate of change.  

<p>

It is one of the most profound ironies of our time that, when literally the

entire world has rejected central planning, the United States continues to

use it to allocate that very resource which could, unleashed, confirm and

compound our dominance in the "infotech" global marketplace.


<p>
So what’s the answer?  In the area of radio spectrum management, the

Commission should: (1) auction off remaining radio spectrum as expeditiously

as possible; and, (2) reform its approach to regulating the use of radio

spectrum by focusing almost exclusively on "output" parameters (e.g. rule to

prohibit co-channel and adjacent channel interference) and limit involvement

in what might be denominated "input parameters" (e.g. rules that dictate what

business a licensee pursues).  Stated less esoterically, future "spectrum

licensees" need service, business and technical flexibility as well as the

freedom to transfer their license or sub-lease channels freely.
<p>


I would urge an approach to spectrum management regime in which

entrepreneurs, responding to market incentives, define how spectrum is used,

when and how networks are built, and when the spectrum is better put to an

alternative use.  This would be a regime in which the public’s interest in

more services at lower prices would be best served.


<p>
I hasten to add that this mode, while a significant departure from our

current approach, falls short of calling for a complete "privatization" of

radio spectrum.  The "spectrum license" I envision would provide for a

greater measure of flexibility and partake of more of the characteristics of

"private property," while remaining the property of the United States

government, ultimately in its control.  Reasonable minds continue to differ

with respect to what obligations, if any, ought to attach to certain uses of

spectrum.  Under the scenario I have described, Congress could reserve

spectrum for certain applications thought critical and/or impose service

obligations on certain bands.  Such "reservations" should be narrowly defined

and made as "explicit" as possible so as to minimize distortions in the

spectrum marketplace.
<p>


<b>How Do We Get There From Here?</b>

<p>

Fortunately, and importantly, the Congress has provided the Commission with

the tools to re-invent itself substantially along the lines outlined above.

 Provisions of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 provide the Commission with

broad authority to defer to market forces.  Two of the most important of

these provisions provide the Commission with authority to forebear from

applying any regulation no longer thought to be in the public interest and an

affirmative requirement to periodically review all regulations to ascertain

whether they are still necessary or appropriate.
<p>


The Commission should utilize the tools now within its power to re-invent

itself.  Specifically, the Commission should:

<p>
<ol>
<li> forebear from enforcement of any regulation or statutory requirement no

longer necessary as a result of competitive market forces;



<li> defer areas of concurrent responsibility to sister agencies in order to

eliminate redundancy and consequent ambiguity in standards;



<li> devolve to the states as much responsibility as possible in the areas of

local exchange regulation and Universal Service as outlined above; and,



<li> privatize as many functions as possible.  Again, the current Commission

deserves credit for moves in this direction, most notably for its use of

private resources to conduct spectrum auctions.
</ol><p>


It is important that the size, structure and remaining regulatory authority

of the Commission reflect the philosophy and goals of the Telecommunications

Act of 1996 as soon as practically possible.  Specifically, the agency should

be much reduced in size and, more importantly, much reduced in the scope of

its regulatory activities.  To be sure, important functions will remain:

management of "spectrum licenses" especially as to those "output perimeters"

discussed above; retention of price and "access regulation" in those aspects

of the interstate telephone market not subject to effective competition; and,

administration of any revamped Federal subsidies supporting our universal

service telephone policy objectives.

<p>

If the commission, working with the Congress, can achieve these organization

and substantive changes, I am confident that objectives of the

Telecommunications Act of 1996 will be fully realized and, more importantly,

the public interest will be advanced dramatically.
<p>





<P>
<blockquote>

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
