<HEAD>

<TITLE>How to Speak up for the GOP Revolution -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>How to Speak up for the GOP Revolution</h2>

by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Higgins">Heather Higgins</a>
<P>
We have heard much in the past year about the internal divisions
of the Republican coalition and how those strains would first
polarize, then fracture, this revolutionary venture.  The moderates,
we were told, would balk at the cruelty of the &quot;Contract
with America&quot; and break from the extremism of the budget.
 The extremists, went the theory, would alienate the moderates
by rejecting the politically possible in pursuit of the politically
pure.  We were blessed with those profound insights before the
election; which continued after the election; they went on through
the Contract (remember how the &quot;hard part&quot; was always
just ahead?), up into the appropriations process and the budget
debate; and now they are part of the primary campaigns.  The point
has been that collapse is just around the corner.
<P>
It isn't.  Not because there aren't differences -- there are.
 But because Republicans know there are, and have therefore quite
consciously worked on operating as a team.  They know that in
any majority coalition, by definition, there will be differences.
 The problem is to first find the  common ground and the common
language that holds the coalition together and advances its agenda.
<P>
This is not only common sense, it has been the reality of our
political life since the founding.  The American Revolution became
possible when those favoring economic liberty joined forces with
those seeking a virtuous society.  Yet that coalition, so much
an analogue to the present day, only coalesced when the two sides
learned a common vocabulary -- words such as &quot;liberty&quot;
and &quot;providence&quot; that galvanized all concerned.
<P>
If there is a problem with the Republican coalition, however,
it is that much of the managing is by deferral -- the &quot;tough&quot;
issues are on hold until later in 1996, or even 1997.  This is
understandable; control of Congress came more quickly than expected
and is still numerically slim, making the immediate challenges
first  a swift transition and then advancing an identifiable GOP
legislative agenda.  Not much time, if any, was left for the further
careful stitching together of  this quilted coalition.  This is
the weakness that is about to be exploited, as the latest  argument
for internal division in the Republican ranks.
<P>
The claim is this.  The Republican split is not so much between
moderates and extremists.  Rather, on the one side is the &quot;Leave
Us Alone&quot; coalition, identified in a phrase made famous by
key Republican strategist Grover Norquist when characterizing
the commonalties between gun owners, taxpayers, home-schoolers,
small business owners and others (Mr. Norquist contrasts this
with the &quot;Takings&quot; coalition of  Democrats, comprised
of those who want something from government that has been taken from others.)   On the other is
what the Wall Street Journal  portrayed on the last Friday of
the year alternatively as &quot;civil-society Republicans,&quot;
 communitarians&quot;, &quot;big-government conservatives&quot;
those who ostensibly wish to use the power of the state to promote
virtue, for example through tax credits for charitable giving.
<P>
Leave aside the flaws in the argument -- for example, the fact
that there are  substantial differences between the policy preferences
of communitarians as opposed to civil-society conservatives, or
the fact that tax credits are endorsed by many in the &quot;Leave
Us Alone&quot; coalition as an excellent way of removing power
from the state and restoring it to citizens.  The argument that
there is a conflict of visions is still powerful.  It captures
a real concern felt within republican ranks.  The fear is this:
Presume we do leave folks alone, then what happens?  Saying they
want to be left alone sounds pretty anti-social and selfish. 
Will sufficient people contribute to charity and help those who
need help?  Or will they look at the infirm, the aged, the sick
and the needy and choose to leave them alone?
<P>
What is meant by the &quot;Leave Us Alone&quot; coalition is quite
different from how it often has been characterized.  It's not
that Republicans aren't clear what they mean -- talk to strategists
like Mr. Norquist and it becomes apparent that they have a robust
vision of a strong civil society fully committed to addressing
our social problems.  But Republicans need to remember that these
are arguments that have not been articulated in political discourse
for some time.  In speaking about these ideas therefore -- particularly
given the Democrats' tireless depiction of Republicans as selfish,
greedy, and uncaring, they cannot use the shorthand they use among
themselves.  Rather, Republicans need to develop and use the common
ideas and language of the coalition if they are to resonate with
voters.
<P>
To say that Republicans represent a &quot;Leave Us Alone&quot;
coalition is simply and quite legitimately to explain what Republicans
want. To prevent a wedge being driven into the coalition, however,
it is critical that Republicans also start addressing why they
want it, and why others should as well.  Left in a vacuum, the
phrase &quot;leave us alone&quot; to the unaccustomed ear makes
no distinction between liberty and license, or civic-mindedness
and self-indulgence.  It provides no vision of  the kind of society
Republicans propose, and gives no assurance that the results will
improve, rather than worsen, the current situation.
<P>
In truth, however, the traditional American vision of limited
government and a strong civil society is a noble one.  Republicans
need to explain that in their view, Americans are trustworthy,
responsible adults. And adults should be &quot;left alone&quot;
in order to better carry out their obligations as citizens, in
order to exercise the responsibilities of authentic liberty.
<P>
Authentic liberty is not license; it is the freedom to do what
we ought to do, not whatever we want to do. And the freer a society,
the less intrusive the state, the more compelling the obligations
of individual citizens.
<P>
As commentator Dennis Prager points out, in the Torah, Moses doesn't
say to Pharaoh, &quot;Let my people go.&quot;  Rather, he says
&quot;Let my people go that they may worship their God.&quot;
 Or as Edmund Burke said, &quot;But what is liberty without wisdom,
and without virtue?  It is the greatest of all possible evils;
for it is folly, vice, and madness, without tuition or restraint.
 Liberty without purpose devolves into license and has little
social claim; liberty with purpose has the moral authority to carry a revolution.  The distinction is critical and needs to be articulated.
<P>
This language will be difficult for some.  As a coalition, for
example, Republicans tend to have a hard time with anything smacking
of &quot;caring&quot; and &quot;compassion&quot;.  It's not that
they object to the real article -- anyone who believes in minimal
government has indeed a deeper obligation to private charity --
but that in political discourse those words became a code for
&quot;government program.&quot;
<P>
Moral vocabulary, too, will be difficult.  The Progressive era
moved Americans away from a language of internal virtue and external
principles, providing instead a lifetime for the deliberately
relative language of &quot;values.&quot; Yet slowly, people are
beginning to realize that in life &quot;value-neutral&quot; is
itself a set of values, and that there are indeed some virtues
critical to any society which aspires to democracy, prosperity, and freedom.
<P>
Liberty is arguably the most powerful idea in American life, made
so by the complexity of the idea and the many visions to which
it speaks.  As David Fisher explains in &quot;Albion's Seed&quot;,
the &quot;most important fact about American liberty is that is
has never been a single idea, but a set of different and even
contrary traditions in creative tensions with one another... It
has become the most powerful determinant of a voluntary society
in the United States.  In fact, this plurality of freedoms may
prove to be the nation's most enduring legacy to the world.&quot;
<P>
Harnessed properly, understood in the context of its obligations
to civil society, liberty is also the resonant image that will
speak compellingly to the Republican coalition and convincingly
to the nation.

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
</BODY>

