<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Future of the Revolution -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>The Future of the Revolution</h2>
Remarks by <a href="#Miller">Jim Miller</a>, <a href="#Huffington">Arianna Huffington</a>, <a href="#Norquist">Grover Norquist</a>,<br>
<a href="#Kelly">Chuck Kelly</a>, <a href="#Galston">Bill Galston</a>, <a href="#Barone">Michael Barone</a> and <a href="#Higgins">Heather Higgins</a>
<P>
<I>The following remarks were delivered at &quot;The New Majority:
 Democratic Governance in a Revolutionary Age&quot; conference,
hosted by The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation on January 22,
1996.  The conference explored the possibility of political realignment
and asked:  Is there a &quot;new majority&quot; taking shape in
America and other western-style democracies?  Who is part of the
new majority, what are its beliefs - and how is it related to
the transition from an industrial to an information-age economy?
 Which (if either) American political party is best positioned
to represent it?  And, what impact will it have on the 1996 presidential
election?</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
<B>by Bill Myers</B>
<P>
Earlier today, Vin Weber began our discussions by arguing that
we have had our revolution, it is now over and our job is to stop
scaring folks with revolutionary rhetoric and to begin the real
work of rebuilding society consistent with the principles which
drove our successful revolution.
<P>
This afternoon, we will talk about the future of the revolution,
of our revolution.  Is Vin right?  Is our revolution over and
is reconstruction about to begin?  Have we already won?
<P>
Or, as I suspect is more likely, has our revolution yet to begin?
 Is the current-day Congressional imperative - to balance-the-budget-in-seven-years-using-CBO-numbers
- the rallying cry of a successful revolution or simply one more
repudiation of a failed order?  Can we really look at a policy
agenda heavy on process reform and light on substantive change
and declare a revolution even started, much less won?
<P>
Our panel will consider these question.  But to begin, let me
suggest that our talk of revolution - won or not - may be little
more than hubris masking a disappointing policy agenda bereft
of vision or revolutionary fervor.  Can we really claim a &quot;green
eyeshade&quot; agenda to be revolutionary when, as Jeff Eisenach
points out, it is much more reminiscent of Herbert Hoover than
of Newt Gingrich?  When will a new majority (any new majority)
emerge that champions a positive vision for America and offers
a policy agenda that advances that vision?
<P>
Perhaps the elections of 1994 were really not all that different
from those of 1992 - in both, voters expelled unsatisfactory incumbents,
and installed newcomers who promised Big Change.  Will those same
voters conclude that they have won that change come 1996?  Or
will they decide that another<I> revolution</I> is necessary then?
 And if so, who will lead it?
<P>
<a name="Miller"></a>
<B>A Way Ahead</B> by <a href="/pff/people/director.html#Miller">Jim Miller</a>
<P>
Let me begin by saying the good news. We revolutionaries have
an army in the field and that army has worked hard, but so far
the success has been holding in check the status quo, the elitists,
the socialists.  But we haven't overcome them.  We've also won
a few important skirmishes, but by and large, they have been rather
modest - things such as making sure that the laws that apply to
everyone else also apply to Congress.  The major reason we haven't
won more skirmishes is that every time we get ready for a skirmish,
the Senate pulls back or the Administration threatens to veto
and we lose the resolve.  So we have an army in the field.  We
have engaged the enemy at times, but we haven't yet prevailed.
<P>
Now what do we do to prevail?  It seems to me that we have to
take the moral high ground.  We must not fight simply on these
little issues. I say little, not because they're not hard fought,
but because they're part of a bigger puzzle, a part of a bigger
overall theme, part of the bigger revolution.  We have been fighting
for a balanced budget.  We have been fighting to save Medicare
and Medicaid.  We have been fighting to slow the overall rate
of growth of government.  But we also have a much broader agenda,
and it's an agenda predicated on our philosophy and the notion
of what constitutes an appropriate role of government.  
<P>
I personally believe that we need to talk more about returning
government to our fondest vision of a limited government, one
that insures our freedom, does what's absolutely necessary, but
otherwise stays out of our pockets and off our backs and out of
our hair.  
<P>
We want a frugal government, a government that doesn't waste our
money - and I can't even begin to tell you all the places and
ways in which the Federal government wastes our taxpayer money.
 We want a prudent government, a government that makes the right
kinds of decisions and employs common sense in its decision making.
 We have drifted far from that.  I think the revolution of 1994
was a revolution to bring government back to basic principles,
not just to balance the budget, not just to continue the rate
of growth of government, but to recognize the fundamental powers
that were established in the Constitution and the vision of our
Founders for our national government.
<P>
The second thing that we need to do is to get on with the rest
of the agenda.  We need to be talking about such things as getting
government out of the business of undermining the institutions
of civil society.  Institutions that frankly are more important
than government.  The Federal government, whether it means to
or not, is undermining our faith and undermining our family. 
For example, the marriage penalty tax undermines and is biased
against the family - you have a situation where under certain
circumstances people are better off financially if they simply
live together rather than be married, and that's nuts.  That's
a nutty proposal, a nutty policy for a government to be following.
 So we need to change a lot of these institutions of government
and to eliminate bad incentives or incentives that tend to tear
down those institutions that are more important to government
and are more necessary to the preservation of a civil society.
 
<P>
I think the third thing we've got to do is to change tactics a
bit.  We have to go from where we are now.  We can't revisit the
fact that we have lost the public relations war on the current
fight over the budget. A year ago, Citizens for a Sound Economy
did polling and focus groups. We found that people thought that
if you have a budget impasse and it was a matter of fighting for
principle, they would blame the President if there were a shutdown,
but if it were perceived as business as usual gridlock, then they
would blame the Congress, the new Republican Congress.  Well,
I think the Administration has won, and they won for several reasons.
 One, the revolutionaries didn't recognize the importance of the
public relations message soon enough.  We were caught up in the
euphoria of winning and extrapolated from that.
<P>
The second reason that we got caught is that frankly we underestimated
the willingness of the statists - particularly the Administration
and many Democrats in Congress - to represent incorrectly what
the facts are and what's at stake.  We  know that what the revolutionaries
are trying to achieve is not to destroy Medicare or Medicaid,
not to have big cuts in spending on some of these entitlement
programs to finance tax cuts.  The willingness of the Liberals
and the statists to misrepresent, and notice I'm using a very
nice term, to misrepresent the facts is far beyond what we would
have believed.
<P>
I think we need to take the moral high ground, we need to get
on with the agenda and we need to change that tactics on the public
relations front and characterize the fight better and do a better
job in representing what's at stake to the American people.
<P>
<a name="Huffington"></a>
<B>Seven Steps to Recovery</b> by <a href="/pff/people/director.html#Huffington">Arianna Huffington</a>
<P>
The GOP has had a string of bad news recently: In a recent ABC/Washington
Post poll, 74 percent disagreed with how the Republican Congress
is handling the economy  (versus 50 percent disagreeing with Clinton's
performance).  The GOP has been completely outmaneuvered by Clinton
on the balanced budget and appears to be retreating even on its
promise not to raise the debt ceiling; and, the President is universally
expected to continue hijacking, in his State of the Union address,
the conservative rhetoric of strengthening families and renewing
institutions. 
<P>
There are two ways for Republicans to deal with all these setbacks.
 One: They can spin them.  Two: They can heed them as the wake-up
call they are.  So far they've chosen the spin cycle.  They're
comforting themselves with transparent excuses:  It's the Senate
with wimpy Republicans caving in; it's the uncompromising House
freshmen, recalcitrant and extremist; it's Clinton, the Great
Empathizer; it's Dick Morris, the brilliant strategist.   
<P>
As anyone familiar with 12-step programs can tell you, there is
nothing as inventive as the human mind in denial.  And since the
GOP is unquestionably in denial, here is my suggested seven step
recovery program. (In the budget saving spirit of the times, we
have reduced 12 steps to 7.)
<P>
The first step for the GOP is to acknowledge that it has a problem.
 
<P>
The second step is to stop whining, especially about the media.
 As Michael Barone once said,  the Constitution guarantees a free
press - it does not guarantee a fair press.  The GOP should forget
about whether the media is misrepresenting their message and go
about improving it.
<P>
The third step is to stop sounding like accountants and to begin
sounding like leaders.  The good news for Republicans is that
80 percent of the American public wants a balanced budget.  The
bad news for them is that so does Bill Clinton - in seven years
with CBO numbers.  So Republicans need to move the debate beyond
balancing the budget, not because this battle is over, but because,
for the moment, the President has framed the debate in way that
makes it impossible for Republicans to win.  Both sides want to
balance the budget, but the President, in his own words, wants
to &quot;balance the budget in a way that reflects our values.&quot;
<P>
The fourth step is for the GOP to stop repeating, ad nauseum,
 that it is not cutting anything - but merely reducing the rate
of growth.  This may be factually correct, but didn't Republicans
campaign on the theme of cutting things - cutting government,
cutting entitlements, cutting taxes?  Did they come to power to
reduce the rate of growth of government or did they come to power
to reduce government?  
<P>
So instead of being so defensive about what they are doing, I
suggest that they take step five and be courageous enough to tell
the American people just what they want to do: reverse 60 years
of New Deal and Great Society thinking, according to which all
solutions to social and economic problems revolve around government.
 Yes, this is bold, but a time of crisis requires boldness, decisiveness,
and honesty.  This rethinking of the role of government has to
go hand in hand with a fundamental redefinition of the role of
the citizen - challenging the American people to meet less from
Washington with more from themselves and their communities.  
<P>
The sixth step, without which the revolution will remain stalled,
is to talk about community solutions - about what is working around
America.  They must talk about it  not once in a while but as
frequently and as seriously as they have been talking about balancing
the budget.  The GOP must go beyond just talking about dismantling
government, and start talking about with what they are going to
replace it.  This is a critical step.  When Newt Gingrich first
became Speaker, he was going to hold Congressional &quot;success
hearings.&quot;  He was going to bring to the Capitol the community
leaders who are making things work and are turning lives around
- introducing them to the American public as the people who embody
the alternative vision of rebuilding America.  
<P>
The final step is to bring a sense of urgency to the debate -
to shift it from balancing the books in seven years to taking
steps right now to reform conditions in education, in welfare,
in the ways we deal with those most in need among us.  Let Dick
Gephardt and David Bonior defend a broken system of government
programs that has left millions of children hungry, abused or
neglected, and let the Republicans speak of weaving a real safety
net from the involvement and resources - in time and money - of
millions of Americans.  
<P>
Instead of spinning all these setbacks or blaming the media, it
is time the GOP took these seven simple steps to produce a message
that has both economic and moral truth on its side.  If Republicans
truly want to recover from what ails them, they must seize the
moral high ground without which no party can be a majority party.
<P>
<a name="Norquist"></a>
<B>The Leave Us Alone Coaltion</B> by Grover Norquist
<P>
I think there will always be tactical up and downs.  I'm in the
long run very optimistic about the course of the revolution and
the reason is both about ideas and institutions.  
<P>
First of all, I'm not surprised at the level of opposition.  I
don't think we should be surprised that this White House and the
present defenders of the welfare state are willing to lie and
bully and repeat lies.  Every day in this country or every week
in this country, people are killed in an attempt to rob somebody
of $100.  This revolution is talking about taking about $1.5 trillion
away from the people who have run this welfare state, the annual
federal budget.  We are lucky that they haven't put snipers up
on the roof to come after us.  I mean this is an awful lot of
resources that are presently in the hands of the welfare state
that are being threatened by this revolution, and they will defend
it by lying and calling names and throwing all sorts of heavy
objects.  So the level of opposition I don't find surprising;
 I just think we have to continue through it.
<P>
But most importantly, I think if we look at the assets of the
coalition and the cohesiveness of the conservative or Republican
coalition, we see a very strong coalition going into not just
this next election, but the next 20 elections.  A lot of people
focus on Washington, and yes, there was a big win in 1994 for
the Republican Party and for the party representing the values
of less government: 52 House seats; 8 new Senate seats; then 5
more Democrats from the House joined the Republican Party; 2 Senators
joined the Republican Party.  But at the state level, radical
change is deeper.  
<P>
The Republican party picked up about 480 state legislative seats;
51 Democrats in state legislatures now have switched parties in
addition to the 480.  Prior to 1994, there were 17 states where
the Democratic party controlled the governorship and both houses
of the legislature, which meant they could change labor law, tax
law, campaign finance law, any kind of rule change they wanted
for their benefit. There were three states over which the Republicans
had similar control.  Now, after the 1994 election, there are
seven states that the Democrats control: they have Hawaii, Georgia,
and the rim of the Confederacy: Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky,
West Virginia and Maryland.  The Republican Party has 15 states
where they control the governorship and both houses.  This is
where a lot of the interesting activities happen around the country,
and what makes a lot of the devolution that federalists and others
have been advocating and talking about possible. Fifteen states.
States like New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois, Michigan,
Wisconsin - large states - and that number is going to grow in
the next several elections.
<P>
The states are fundamental building blocks, not just of the nation,
but of the polity as well, and I think it's particularly important
that this revolution happened at the state and local level as
well as the federal level. If Mario Cuomo was still Governor of
New York, and Ann Richards was still Governor of Texas, do you
really believe despite our best intentions that this Republican
House and Senate would run and send medicaid and welfare out to
the states and hand $7 billion over the next seven years to Ann
Richards or $20 billion to Mario Cuomo to spend on Democratic
precinct workers to try to kneecap the Republican party?  I think
it would be very, very difficult if you didn't have the depth
of 31 Republican governors and 17 totally Republican states.
<P>
In additon, we have a coherent and cohesive governing, conservative
Republican coalition as we move forward in the 1996 elections.
I would argue that what holds the Republican conservative coalition
together, this revolution, is that everybody in the coalition
wants to be left alone by the government.  They're the leave us
alone coalition: property owners who don't want their property
taken away or declared a wetland; taxpayers that don't want their
money taken away from them; gun owners who don't want the guns
taken away.  You have home schoolers who want their children left
alone.  These are not people who want everybody else to home school.
 They don't want to tell you how to educate your children.  They
just want the government out of their family life and their decisions
as parents. 
<P>
We're trying to recreate civil society and have competent charitable
institutions that need to be left alone, where people who are
actually doing something about getting people off of drugs and
trying to help people who need help.  They can't have the government
coming in and taking a quarter to a half of what people earn and
a quarter to a half of people's time and then expect people to
have time or resources for voluntary and charitable.  Nor can
you afford bad government charity driving out and hobbling good
private sector and faith-based charitable work, because if down
the street from your effort to help people get their lives turned
around, the government says you don't have to bathe, you don't
have to get up in the morning, you don't have to work and we'll
give you money and we'll give you food for free, then you can
continue to be a drug addict.
<P>
Thus one of the most important things in this coalition is that
everybody in it simply wants to be left alone by the government.
 I include the social conservatives and the Christian right, because
they can best be understood as a parents rights movement that
wants the government out of the lives of their families and their
children.  Remember that the so-called religious right got organized
in a self-defense effort in 1978 when the government was going
after Christian radio stations and Christian schools.  The conservative
coalition is very cohesive.  They don't want anything from each
other.  They can work together in a room and everybody can work
together toward the same end: of getting the government out of
everybody else's lives and opening up space for return to a civil
society.
<P>
<a name="Kelly"></a>
<B>Looking for Leadership</B> by Charles Kelly
<P>
There is obviously in everything you've heard today a series of
assumptions about what's going on in Washington and how this government
has to be restructured here in Washington.  And I know that's
how most of the people in Washington feel.  Yet when I travel
as I do and speak at rotary clubs and little tiny groups wherever,
from the redneck bars of the south to whatever drinking establishment
seems to be appropriate in the community to get a feel for the
people, one thing always comes back. It is not that they're thrilled
with the Republican revolution, not that they're thrilled with
the Presidency of Bill Clinton, but that they detest government,
not only government in the abstract, but the individuals of government,
the living, breathing Congressmen up here.
<P>
It is not as if you get a resurrection or belief and trust by
turning out one bunch of people as the public did in this country;
they threw George Bush out of office.  They said that's enough.
 Two years later, they threw as many Democrats out as they could
and said that's enough.  Now is that a Republican revolution or
is that a manifestation of some more profound and deep seeded
distrust for the whole institutional abstraction of the way this
country lives?  
<P>
It is certainly the experience that came to me working seven days
a week pretty much for two years.  Now this trust can only be
met I think by something that restores confidence and that is
trust, and that's what people have for Colin Powell.  They believed
that Colin Powell was a trustworthy leader.  The reason they believe
in Colin Powell is that he's a real person.  He's lived a real
life.  Character does count.  He's not one of these abstractions
that goes from high school politics into the local Congressman's
office and then worms his way up the process and becomes a legislator.
 
<P>
When I traveled around the country and talked to people in the
states, including the governors, our strategy was to try to get
the governors' attention.  The governors, most of them, have come
out of legislatures and they admire Bob Dole as a legislator.
They think he's a wonderful legislator.  He knows how to cut a
deal; he knows how to split the difference. But it is precisely
what happens when the difference is split that offends people
because it is the giantism, the endless and prostration of more
and more, that people have come to distrust.  People do want to
be left alone.  That's true.  They want to be left alone to collect
their checks from the government and &quot;take what's due me.&quot;
 They don't want to have it all disappear over night. 
<P>
The word revolution is a tough word.  We had one revolution in
this country.  Patrick Henry perhaps started the revolution, but
he couldn't conclude it.  We needed a George Washington to carry
the revolution forward.  We do not have in this country trusted
leadership.  We have people who are exercising power and are deeply
distrusted, and until we can understand that, I don't think we've
learned the lesson.  
<P>
The French Revolution brings the echoes of the troubles' wheels.
 It didn't end in a pretty fashion.  But the worst thing it seems
to me was not just the guillotine, the worst thing was the pleasure
that people took in watching the beheading, and that's what people
see around the country in this Congress.  They say these guys
are taking pleasure in the beheadings, and that's not the way
leadership works, and that's my second word.  The first word is
trust.  The second word is leadership.  Legislation is not leadership.
 The Constitution was not written around the idea that Congress
should be the executive of the government.  Accountants are not
leaders.  We've got to have people who can be trusted for who
they are, what they have done, what kind of character they have,
what kind of lives they've lived.  Without that, I don't think
we can be successful as a Republican party or as a governing party.
 
<P>
That brings me to the third point, people are desperate for something
that they can do.  They want a belief in themselves as citizens,
not as puppets on a string, not as people whose pockets are being
picked.  The idea of citizenship is a very, very powerful one
in this country, and nobody is talking about that.  They're talking
about hobbling together coalitions of various special interest
groups that fund various political activities.  People don't care
about that, at least they don't in the scope and experience that
I've had.  I was on a board of directors some years ago with a
man that I admire greatly named Peter Drucker, and Peter says
the secret of success is to see as a whole what others see only
in parts. You hear it all the time. 
<P>
We've got to have someone who will say, what is our safety net?
 What is the level that we're going to have for our people?  Nobody's
talking that way.  We're talking about a subterfuge really, as
people see it.  We'll give it to the states and let the states
take care of it.  I was trained as a lawyer some years ago, and
I don't practice, but I will tell you that out of all of the people
that I knew in law or in the Bar, nobody wanted to go into the
state court if they possibly could avoid it because they didn't
trust the state courts.  They wanted to get into the federal system.
 That attitude is still present.  People are suspicious about
the way some states are run.  They're certainly entitled to be
suspicious about Arkansas.  We've learned a little bit.  They're
suspicious about Alabama and Mississippi and Georgia, and they're
probably suspicious about some of the western states because they
don't have the kind of problems that people have in New York or
Pennsylvania or Ohio.  So there is a great deal of discontinuity,
disconnect and disorientation in our society, that nothing that
happens in this town deals with at all because there is no leader
to speak to them.  There is no trusted person.  
<P>
Having said all that, the answer is not easy for me because I
believe that Colin Powell would have won the general election
by at least 70 percent of the votes. Therefore he would not be
dependent upon various groups of financing and other support,
and thus he alone could speak for the national interests as opposed
to being a captive of a bunch of special interests. I think that
the Republican revolution when it decided, suddenly when it came
to power that it wasn't interested in campaign finance reform,
I think it lost a very great deal.  
<P>
<a name="Galston"></a>
<B>How to Move Forward</B> by Bill Galston
<P>
Well, for obvious reasons, I'm not here to praise your revolution.
But for less obvious reasons I'm not here to bury it either. 
I'd like to step back a little bit from the front lines of partisan
combat, which, by the way, the American people detest as heartily
as they detest government itself, and reflect on problems that
we're all trying to grapple with in one way or another. I believe
that politics done right in a democracy means addressing the people's
most fundamental concerns in a forward looking way that takes
account as much as possible of the common interests and the common
good.  That is a very high standard, but I think that was George
Washington's standard, and as George Washington once said, &quot;Our
duty is to raise a standard to which the wise and honest may repair,
the event is in the hands of God.&quot;  
<P>
So I prefer to begin not where Washington is, but where I think
the American people are.  What's on their minds? I think that
there are three central concerns on the minds of the American
people today, which I will summarize as economic anxiety, social
disintegration and political dysfunction.  
<P>
Many of my conservative friends are inclined for one reason or
another to underplay the existence of economic anxiety in this
country.  I think you would be better off spending your time taking
that phenomenon seriously and thinking about ways of addressing
it.  We are not making up the statistics about wages.  We are
not planting stories about AT&amp;T's layoffs on the front page
of the daily newspapers.  We are not creating gaps between front-line
workers and CEOs. These are social facts that the American people
are grappling with.  They don't necessarily want our answers,
but they certainly don't want anybody to say, no, this isn't happening,
these aren't real problems and we don't care about them.  It's
just not true. 
<P>
Social disintegration, I don't need to tell this group about that.
You know, concentric circles of disintegration starting with the
family, broadening on out to neighborhoods and communities.
<P>
 
<P>
Political dysfunction is a sense that our fundamental institutions
of government are not performing they way they ought to in a democracy.
 They are not responsive.  They are not effective.  They are not
transparent.
<P>
So to turn this around, what do the American people want?  I think
for the economy they want opportunity and at least a modicum of
security as well.  They are not satisfied with an opportunity
society that removes all elements of security from their economic
lives.  That is not an acceptable answer to the American people,
and you should think about that.  For the society, they want I
believe a restoration, a restoration of social order and also
a restoration of sense of social connection.  There's a profound
sense of social disconnection, and I believe the American people
are crying out for some response.  With regard to politics, I
believe that they want a much greater measure of responsiveness
and also of integrity than they see today.  
<P>
Now if these are the concerns, if this in broad outlines is what
they want, what's the way forward?  I think we're all in one way
or another grappling with the question of the way forward.  As
far as the framework is concerned, I would suggest that what the
country needs and what the American people want is something like
a new progressive politics for the information age.  We lead them
to believe that politics is irrelevant to the question of how
to have liveable lives for average families in the new information
age.  Politics is not irrelevant to that set of concerns.  
<P>
I believe that the American people today are in favor neither
of paternalism nor of libertarianism.  I agree with Vin Weber
that the American people are not rejecting government root and
branch.  Speaking as a Democrat, I would be delighted if Republicans
wage the 1996 election as the leave us alone coalition, because
the leave us alone coalition is not and will not be a majority
in this country. I would add that the leave us alone coalition
is frequently the leave our subsidies alone coalition.
<P>
 
<P>
I was very struck with Frank Luntz's presentation about the American
people are thinking.  He offered a long string of negatives: they
don't like this; they don't like that.  But no political movement
can build a majority on negatives.  I don't care who you are,
especially when you're talking about a permanent national governing
majority that includes the Presidency.  That's not what Presidential
leadership is about.  It is not about negation.  It is about dismantling
what no longer works and replacing it, whether it's government,
civil society or the market, with something that works better.
 
<P>
What does this mean more specifically?  With regard to the public
sector, with regard to government, the goal I believe as far as
the American people are concerned is empowerment.  The means:
incentives rather than regulations or commands whenever possible.
 The level: as local and close to the people as possible. The
extent: government only when market and civil society cannot do
the job.  I think there's a substantial measure of agreement in
the country on those four points and the question is to devise
policies that are consistent with those four points.  
<P>
I would submit to you that today there is no great public support
for either political party in Congress.  From the people's standpoint,
I would suggest to you neither party is seen as standing for reform
of the political system, neither party is seen as offering clear
answers to the profound problems of social and moral disintegration
in this country, and with regard to the economy, we have an unholy
split where Democrats are offering security without opportunity
and Republicans are offering opportunity without security, two
losing formats.  
<P>
Now what is the path to the new majority in these circumstances.
 Here I'm going to offer more of a negative than a positive point.
 It's not simple at all given where we are.  Why not? Because
the detached center is heterogenous.  It's not all one thing.
 There are different people in this detached center unassociated
with either political party.  Colin Powell's detached centrists
are not just the same as Ross Perot's detached centrists, who
are certainly not the same as Pat Buchanan's radicalists.  These
people are all untethered from the party system as we know it
today, but they do not agree among themselves.
<P>
I would add that there are profound generational differences as
well, very important generational differences. For instance, the
depression was a unifying experience.  The Second World War was
a unifying experience; creating a middle class and fighting the
Cold War and defeating communism in the 1940's and '50's was a
unifying experience.  For the past 30 years, we've had nothing
but disunifying experiences, and we now have two generations whose
political outlook reflects the politics of disunity and I think
putting Humpty Dumpty together again is not simple.  
<P>
I will conclude with some grandiose historical retractions.  As
I look at American history, I see three eras of fundamental party
change and of new majority creation.  The 1850's, the 1890's and
the 1960's.  In the 1850's, you had the creation of a new majority
through the disappearance of an old party and the rise of a new
one.  In the 1890's, you had the creation of a new political system
because the ideas that the Progressive movement launched in one
way or another soon became the common property of the entire political
system. By 1912 you had the most important political debate between
two Progressives, Wilson and Roosevelt, and the guy who stood
squarely for the old order - the incumbent President of the United
States - who happened to come in third. The political change model
of the 1960's is neither party replacement, like the 1850's, nor
change of overall political outlook in the system as in the 1890's,
but rather fundamental change in one political party, namely the
Republican party and the long march to power of the conservative
movement.
<P>
I do not know which of these three models of party transformation
and of new majority building will be the model that governs the
next 20 years, but I do offer this prediction, that as we look
back on 1996 from the vantage point of 2016 or even 2006, the
current partisan affiliation and the current lines of partisan
confrontation will come to seem as antique to us as the politics
of the 1880's and early 1890's came to seem by the first and second
decade of the 20th Century.
<P>
<a name="Barone"></a>
<B>A Return to de Tocqueville</B> by Michael Barone
<P>
Let me say I think that we are in the midst of a revolution, but
perhaps we ought to call it a small revolution or perhaps think
up another word as they thought up the word recession in the 1930's
to describe the depression that wasn't as big as the depression.
 This revolution has been going on for a little longer than we
think, and will continue to have important effects regardless
of which party wins the elections.
<P>
We've had a return to Tocquevillean in America.  I think that
today's post-industrial America in important respects, not in
every respect, but in an important respect more closely resembles
the pre-industrial America that Alexis de Tocqueville described
in the 1830's in <I>Democracy in America</I> than it does the
industrial America in which we grew up.  Industrial America was
a big unit America: big government, big business, big labor. Those
big units recovered from the depression, won World War II, built
prosperous post-war America.
<P>
Big institutions developed enormous prestige in that period. 
We're always talking about the decline in respect for institutions
and trust in institutions in America, and we take as our base
point polling data that was started in the 1950's or early 1960's
when trust in institutions was very high. There seems to be an
unspoken assumption by a lot of people who use these figures is
that, hey, trust in institutions in America was always high, you
know, from 1620 and stuff and then it tumbled down in the 1970's
and '80's. In fact, I wonder if we weren't in an unusual period
in the 1950's and '60's.  I mean Mark Twain in the 19th century
certainly was not the only American who referred to Congress as
our only native criminal class.  There was other skepticism about
institutions.  We have had different qualities of leadership at
different points in our time.  The first President Buchanan did
not have the same qualities that the man who hopes to be the second
President Buchanan does.  
<P>
Industrial America was a culturally uniform America. So many people
went through that same thing, World War II, that we were literally
a nation in uniform.  It was a conformist America.  A lot of people
in the fifties thought there was a lot of problems with that.
 It was an America that believed in basic institutions and big
government, and it tended as a natural course because of its character
as a civil society to vote more often for the Democrats than the
Republicans, because they were the party on balance most closely
identified with big government.  And even a Republican President,
Eisenhower in 1952, with a Republican House and a Republican Senate,
didn't make major tax cuts.  He refrained from cutting the very
high tax programs that he thought were bad.  He refrained from
attacking the Social Security program which he personally felt
wasn't a great idea.  He started building interstate highway programs,
major public works, the National Defense Education Act, getting
the government into financing graduate school education and so
forth.  He was moving with the times and with the character of
the country against, in his case, his own personal inclinations
because he felt that was the right thing to do as a leader of
the country at that time.  
<P>
Today I think we've changed.  We've watched the big institutions
crumble in different ways.  We've watched big government become
incompetent in different ways that the people of 30 years ago
would not have believed.  I mean if you were driving around Washington,
D.C. this weekend, the big government of the District of Columbia
which by any standards of local governments is a huge local government
with enormous money, the traffic lights were out all weekend at
the entry points to the city. I mean this is a city government
that is incompetent, a big government that's incompetent to perform
even the most basic levels of public safety and protection here.
 We've seen big government get corrupted in various ways, and
the District of Columbia is obviously an example at one end of
the spectrum.  
<P>
Big business changed vastly, having to down size, having to change.
The big three auto companies, supposedly in total possession of
the American market, John Kenneth Galbraith assured us in 1967,
now in big trouble.  Big labor is almost disappearing.  Today,
we are a culturally fragmented country.  Religion was the single
demographic factor that most separated Americans voting in the
1992 and 1994 elections, even more than race. It's an America
which naturally tends to favor, not always, but tends to favor
devolution of power, tends to oppose concentration of power, and
therefore more often tends to favor the Republican party rather
than the Democratic party. I think that this revolution, the Newtonian
revolution if we want to call it that, has been going on longer
than we think, even though it has gone over something of a rocky
road.
<P>
The language of reporters and journalists is very interesting.
 During the 1993-94 political struggle over health care reform,
we in Washington were writing that there will be reform of health
care financing based on an assumption that reform will only happen
if Congress passes a federal law.  Otherwise, there won't be reform.
 Well, if you go out and look as Bob Samuelson did in a competing
publication of my own some weeks ago, what has actually happened
to health care finance around the country over the last five years,
there have been immense numbers of changes and reforms and differing
ways or organizing and financing health care.  The rise in health
care costs, which we were assured for all sorts of what seemed
like excellent reasons were going to go higher, have been cut.
In fact, health care reform has been going on and the failure
of the Clinton health care plan was in effect a decision to let
that issue stay devolved.  Let it be handled in a decentralized
way.  Some people may feel that was an unfortunate decision, but
it was the decision that the society through the political process
made when we had a Democratic Congress, when Newt Gingrich could
hardly get on network television. It was impossible to cobble
together in a devolution minded society a centralized program
that a majority would not have some problems with.  
<P>
Obviously in 1995, looking at the budget issue now, the Republicans
have not had complete success.  On the other hand, at the lower
levels of government, spending and taxation are very substantially
different from would have occurred if even a slender Democratic
majority had been re-elected to control Congress.  We are in a
process where the actions of the political process are ratcheting
the size of government down.  They don't always ratchet it successfully,
but the movement is in that direction instead of the series of
political forces that we had starting with the New Deal that attempted
to ratchet the size of government up.  If you wanted an egg program
in the old days and I wanted an urban program like food stamps,
we'd say, hey, let's do them both, and we'd ratchet the government
up.  Now we're doing it more in the other direction through cuts.
I think even some of the failures with the Contract with America
have been successes.  I mean Congress, and to some extent - even
if I think insincerely - the Clinton White House, are acting as
if the balanced budget amendment was passed.  We're sitting here
talking, not entirely in fictitious terms, about how to balance
the budget in seven years.   With term limits, Members of Congress
are acting almost as if term limits have been passed.  We see
all these members who everybody assumed had lifetime careers,
that wanted lifetime careers, deciding to go onto something else.

<P>
The basic trends in society are having their effects in the political
process regardless of the polls and the problems that the Republicans
currently are having.  In retrospect, looking at the budget thing,
I think that the Republicans made a mistake in a couple of ways.
 They made mistakes a lot of liberals make that others shared
their views when they assumed that other people would be delighted
at seeing government shutdown, and I think they failed to understand
that when you're perceived as being in charge, disarray, disorder
works against you, but I think the tendency of the Presidential
election this year is going to change the political posture in
which people are looking at these issues.  
<P>
I think disarray now works against President Clinton and will
continue to do so up through the election.  Disarray does not
help a President, and I think that while people have been looking
at the plans that the Republicans have brought to the table, brought
to the floor in Congress, and asking questions about them as they
quite reasonably might, in the summer and fall of 1996, people
are going to be asking what both parties will do, and in that
respect, I think that also in my view that we are in an era of
greater straight party ticket voting and that means that the voters
might very well have to face the question, do you want a Republican
government?  Do you want a Democratic government?  
<P>
In that regard I would say  Republicans have something of an advantage.
Voters have questions and qualms about a Republican government,
and we've seen those go through the Republican opinion polls,
but voters' attitude toward a Democratic government was pretty
well showed in the 1994 elections.  One party has a potential
majority.  The other party has a very hard time getting a majority
in my view in light of where we're going.
<P>
My conclusion is that this revolution, if it's a revolution, or
this change in direction in the flow of public policy, will continue
to a greater or lesser extent regardless even if Bill Clinton
and the Democratic Party are elected in 1996.
<P>
<a name="Higgins"></a>
<B>The Correct Vision and Projects</B> by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Higgins">Heather Higgins</a>
<P>
 
<P>
The subject is the future of the revolution, and I'd like to break
this into three parts.  The first is where we are now.  The second
is how we ought to proceed, and the third is an assessment of
the future of this little venture on which we think we've embarked.
<P>
Where we are now I'd like to present to you in Gingrichian model
terms since Gingrich is perceived as being the central force of
the revolution.  Any of you who have listened to Newt at any length
surely have heard his modeling plan of vision, strategies, projects
and tactics.  If you are in fact trying to be a force for change
in a society that will lead it forward, then you have to start
at the very top when you describe your vision. I think the vision
we are talking about is a world in which individuals have the
authentic liberty to fulfill their responsibilities as citizens.
 If that is your vision, then one of your strategies would be
to limit the size of government to allow greater responsibilities
for citizens, and if that is one of your strategies, then one
of your projects, one of them, is to call for a balanced budget
with no increase in taxes, because, as we all know, balanced budgets
in and of themselves are something of a shibboleth.  You could
balance the budget by nationalizing the economy.  It's all a game
and it's where you balance it and how you balance it and what
the programs are that you have in place that matters.  
<P>
The problem that the Republicans have now, to be very frank, is
that somehow the mere project of balancing the budget has been
elevated to the language of a vision.  An economic language will
always unnecessarily be trumped by a moral language, and Bill
Clinton has been very smart.  He has used moral language.  He
is really speaking to a vision or representation of a vision.
 Whether or not we think that it's all a lie or we think that
it's all a fraud, it is convincing language to the listeners.
 On the one side you have economic data and accountant talk, and
on the other side you have moral language.  
<P>
This was entered into quite innocently.  Balanced budget was a
slogan shorthand that meant a great deal to a great many people.
 Most of them understood exactly what was meant, understood it's
context, but forgot that that needed to be explained to the larger
community lest it be trumped by more explicit language on the
other side.  There are signs, however, and I am optimistic that
this language is slowly being learned.  For example, Dick Army's
recent language about the extensions on the debt ceiling being
tied to specific language in any bill which changed the shape
and form of government and allowed us our liberties back.  He
was not just talking about CBO numbers in seven years, which I
think is quite important.  I think that there will be a return
to what Gingrich had stated as being the unshakable, non-negotiable,
principles which were a balanced budget with tax cuts, radical
and substantial changes in the way we do welfare, and changes
in the way we do Medicare.  
<P>
How to proceed.  There recently has been a spade of articles which
I would urge you all to pay attention to because I think they
are the latest analysis, and I think that they are in some measure
wrong.  The first salvo to this effect was in <I>The Wall Street
Journal</I>, the last day of 1995.  There's been a variant on
the theme by David Brooks in a recent <I>Standard,</I> which is
a very good article and he makes a number of good points, but
there's one particular aspect where I disagree with him. It is
a variant I would say on the argument that we have heard ever
since, even before the Congressional elections, that there would
be a split between the moderates and the conservative radicals
 in the Republican Party.  The prognosticators have always said
it's going to happen.  It was going to happen before we ever got
to January, after they won.  It was going to happen all the way
through the Contract; if you will remember, the tough part was
always still coming.  It was going to happen all the way through
the appropriations process.  It was going to happen as we got
down to the budget negotiations themselves.  
<P>
I think that people have learned that this split doesn't quite
work out the way they think it's going to, and so the latest version
that you're hearing now is that there is a split between the leave
us alone coalition and - shall we call them cultural conservatives
- otherwise referred to <U><I>by The Wall Street Journal</I></U>
mistakenly as communitarians.  Actually, in fact, I would argue
that this is a very superficial difference.  The problem, however,
is just simply one of language.  
<P>
Leave us alone tells us what people want.  It doesn't tell you
why they want it. But in fact, if you think about it, adults need
to be left alone in order to exercise their moral responsibilities
from the excesses of government.  Yet unless you explicitly spell
out why you want what you want, you leave yourself vulnerable
to attacks that you want to be left alone because you're cold
hearted and cruel and your ultimate objective is to leave them
alone - them being the people who are genuinely in need.  That
is not in fact what this coalition is about.  In fact, if one
believes in limited government, one has a greater moral obligation
to take care personally of people who are in need than those who
simply assume that the government is going to take care of it
for you.  
<P>
Yet the reality is that the Republican party has a great deal
of trouble with the language of compassion and the language of
values and morals, and I think in large part that problem comes
about from the fact that for the last 30 years caring and compassion
have been code words for larger government programs.  They are
not part of the rhetoric and the debate, and they need to be learned.
<P>
Where do we go from here and what is the future of the revolution?
 As much as we all like to give Newt Gingrich credit for it, I
would contend that the revolution was going to happen eventually
without him in any event, and I would say that the revolution
itself is doing fine while the Republican party may be in some
trouble right now, but I think that it is merely temporary.  
<P>
The revolution was inevitable because of a confluence of external
events. If you look at, for example, communist systems of government,
there was always an original claim made for them that they were
tremendous for productivity.  And if you looked at them in their
early years, there was a tremendous jump in the redistribution
of wealth, and there really was a sort of kick to the economy
as Lenin's crowd came in and redistributed wealth and all the
rest.  The problem is that it didn't last as a system.  It imploded
from its own weight, and I think that we're starting to see the
inevitable outcome of flawed systems.  You're starting to see
the inevitable outcome of an entitlement mentality, both in terms
of the dollars that need to be spent and in terms of the behavior
that it induces.  You're seeing the inevitable outcome of a focus
on groups as opposed to individuals, or on bureaucrats as opposed
to families, or on centralized regulation as opposed to common
sense. It obvious to people that the system itself does not seem
to be working.
<P>
 
<P>
More than that, though, we have an aging demographic and ultimately
that is probably one of the most important variables out there.
 We live in a society which in my lifetime has been completely
dominated by the Baby Boom generation.  When they were young in
the fifties, this was a totally child centered society.  As they
got to be adolescents in the sixties, we got an adolescent culture.
 As they moved through their various life stages in the seventies
and then the eighties, as they got inquisitive, society got inquisitive,
they are now having children.  If there is any factor which is
going to reshape how a society thinks about its future, it's going
to be its concern about raising it's own children, and I guarantee
you that the rules you wanted for you are not the same rules you
want for your children.  
<P>
Ultimately I think we are going to find this new synthesis.  I
suspect it will be through the Republican party, although I do
not make any guarantees that that will be in fact the claim, and
we will hopefully establish a new vision of government that will
itself have moral legitimacy for its limited role and return power
to the people.

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
