<html>
<head>
<title>Speech by Jeff Eisenach before the U.S. Conference of Mayors -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
 
<p>
<center><P>
<h2>Conservatism</h2>
<b>Speech before the U.S. Conference of Mayors
<br>By Jeff Eisenach</b>
</center>
<p>
Thank you for having us here today.
<p>
As President of the PFF and Advisor to Speaker Gingrich ....I’ve been given to understand that part of my role here is to present the "conservative" agenda for renewing America’s cities.
<p>
I will fail this task, for three reasons.
<p>
First, I cannot tell you today what the term "conservative" means.  For the last six decades, or so, it could have been defined in part as "not giving a damn about the cities."  Yet I have flown 2000 miles to be here with you today, accompanied by my partner and collaborator in thinking through these issues -- a life-long Democrat who may cause you bodily harm if you even think about calling her a conservative.
<p>
Secondly,  neither conservatives -- whatever they are -- nor liberals -- whatever they are -- have an approach to the cities worthy of the word "agenda." There are inklings, beginnings, first glimpses and hopeful signs.
 But an agenda:  I don’t think so.
<p>
Finally, it’s not even quite clear what we mean by "city."  The City Limits?
 The SMSA?  Whoever participates in the local Council of Governments?  Is a city an economic unit, a cultural one, or a governmental unit where the Federal government sends checks for handing out to the poor?  Why do we have cities? Should we have cities?
<p>
So let me start by being honest.  I don’t know what a city is or ought to be, I have no agenda for how to make one successful if I did, and I can’t even tell you what ideology I bring to the table as I approach the issue.
<p>
Now, before you pack me back off to Washington in disgust, let me tell you a few things I do know, which I think might be helpful.
<p>
First, the information revolution is real, it is here right now and it is forcing profound change in virtually every institution in society.  If you have not already done so, I strongly encourage you to buy and read a copy of Alvin and Heidi Toffler’s new book, Creating a New Civilization, which is the most elegant and concise description of the changes now happening to all of us.
<p>
Second, the central implication of the information age for government is the death of bureaucracy as a means of accomplishing human goals.  It worked for nearly a century, and that’s a pretty good accomplishment for any system.
 But centralized control through hierarchical institutions is no longer a good way to get things done.
<p>
Third, the Federal government is in the process of dealing with the fact I just mentioned.  The most successful bureaucratic system ever on the planet is being torn asunder by the same forces that have already changed IBM, General Motors and the Soviet Union.  You are feeling the impact of that change right now, and you will continue to feel it for many years into the future, regardless of which party controls Congress or the White House.
<p>
Fourth, the reason the information age is killing bureaucratic systems is that it permits the creation of something better:  agile, just-in-time, customized, "virtual" systems that permit flexibility and diversity, accomodate constant change and produce results.  In short, it is now possible, thanks to the collapse in the price of information, to create "institutions" over night, do what needs to be done during the day, and close them before sundown the following evening.  And the new virtual organization respects no geographic or legal boundaries.  (Gage story)
<p>
Now, based on items three and four, let me make a couple of suggestions regarding economic development and your relationship with the Federal government.
<p>
First, do not ask today what your Federal government can do for you, or even what you can do for it.  It’s lucky to take care of itself on an average weekday, and it’s already getting plenty of advice.  Instead, ask what your Federal government can stop doing to you.  Ask, as Rudy Guiliani said recently, for your freedom.  In fact, don’t just ask for it:  Demand it.
<p>
And, getting it, figure out how you can use that freedom to your advantage.
 Let me give you an example of what I mean:
<p>
On the way down on the plane, I read the materials you provided on Senator Hatfield’s Local Empowerment and Flexibility Act of 1995.  And it gave me the following idea:
<p>
Suppose the Federal government were to say to metropolitan mayors that it would entertain proposals to eliminate regulatory and spending restrictions for any metropolitan area that applied.  Eliminate restrictions on Section 8 spending; eliminate Davis-Bacon Act requirements; Eliminate unfunded mandates.  Any metropolitan area -- including surrounding jurisdictions -- could apply to become a "free city," on one condition:  The mayor of the central city had to make the application.
<p>
I think the implications for relationships between cities and their surrounding jurisdictions are obvious:  You would have a bargaining chip -- a very large bargaining chip, I suspect -- you do not now have.  And you could use that bargaining chip to achieve one of the most pressing objectives of any sensible urban policy:  Reintegrating the suburbs and the central cities into coherent social and economic units.
<p>
Is this proposal too radical to be considered.  I frankly don’t think so.
 Let me ask Jane, who has been involved in the Federal relationship with the cities for many years, tell you a little bit about what she is now seeing -- really what she is now creating -- in Washington.  
<p>
<center>

</center>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
