<html>
<head>
<title>The Lessons of the 1992 and 1994 Elections -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h1>The Lessons of the 1992 and 1994 Elections</h1>

<b>by Vin Weber [From the February 1995 <i>American Civilization</i>]</b><br>


Throughout the good times of the 1980s, when the Republicans were really
doing very well, we used to look at the polling and we found an interesting
phenomenon.<p>

If you divided the zones of public policy issues in three ways, Republicans
were able to dominate the 1980s at the Presidential level because they
owned the national security/foreign policy zone and the economic zone. On
just about any question you asked related to those two zones of issues,
people had overwhelmingly greater confidence in the Republican Party than
they did in the Democratic Party.<p>

But here is a third zone comprised of social issues. And whether it is the
environment or poverty or health care or any of those things that we think
of as domestic policy, that zone remained firmly in the grasp of the
Democratic Party.<p>

Thus while people were endorsing Republican approaches to the economy, they
continued to believe in what they had learned over the decades since the
New Deal: that government leadership should address a whole range of
problems.<p>

And while they might not have been happy with the way government was
addressing problems, they didn't see any alternative to a governmental
approach to environmental protection or the problems of the poor or
anything else to the traditionally associated with New Deal Liberals or
Great Society Liberals or the Democratic Party generally.<p>

But as long as we were winning the Cold War and the economy was strong, it
didn't matter, and so Republicans won elections at least at the
Presidential level.<p>

Then you get to the 1992 election, which all of us who are Republicans
ought to remember these days when we are euphoric about 1994. Much of the
Clinton campaign victory was owed to the fact that the public, now in a
period of some uncertainty about the economy and with the Cold War won,
rejected what they viewed as the passivity of the Republican Party, and the
Bush Administration more specifically, toward that third zone of domestic
policy issues.<p>

The Republicans were swept aside because the voters were rejecting a party
that had nothing to say, in their view, about a whole range of social
issues and perhaps even a bit about the economy because we lost some of our
edge from the 1980s.<p>

The best example of this is the health care issue. It's important to
refresh your memory; Bill Clinton did not invent health care out of whole
cloth.<p>

All of us who were in the Congress at that time and doing things like
holding town meetings had known that for years that public concern about
the issue was very real. Clinton was reacting to a genuine concern that had
been rising with the public.<p>

Why then the dramatic reversal of 1994? The health care issue and how it
unfolded over the course of 1994 tells much of that story.<p>

Again, I make the point, it's important to understand that the health care
issue was not an invented or contrived issue. It was a real serious concern
of people. After its failure legislatively, and certainly after the 1994
elections, there seems to be a sense that this was inevitable; what a huge
mistake the Clinton people made in trying to do this with our health care
system. It was clearly a mistake. But not one that was nearly as
predictable as we now might say in retrospect. Because every other time a
Democratic President has come into office and then did precisely what
President Clinton did in 1993, he succeeded.<p>

They identified a major national problem, proposed a Federal Government
solution, certainly encountered some opposition from those who were
ideologically opposed to use the Federal Government to solve problems, but
basically got their program enacted.<p>

Why did this not happen with Clinton's health care proposal leads to a real
understanding of the questions that face us today in politics. Because
again, the problem was real. But by the end of the debate, people had
rejected it. Why? Too bureaucratic. Too centralized. Too expensive. Too
much Government.<p>

Let me tell you, as popular as the program is, the Social Security system,
if it were being created out of whole cloth today, would be subject to all
those same criticisms because it is centralized and rather bureaucratic.
Yet those criticisms wouldn't have sunk Lyndon Johnson or Franklin
Roosevelt.<p>

It's a different day.<p>

And what happened was, in the 1994 election, we saw the rejection of that New
Deal liberal model of problem solving once and for all. The question now is,
"What can replace it?" A survey done by Frank Luntz for 
<a href="/pff/index">The Progress & Freedom Foundation</a> immediately
after the election bore out the rejection of that traditional model of
governmental problem solving by the voters in the 1994 election.<p>

Sixty to seventy percent of the voters in Luntz's survey consistently said
that every one of those domestic problems today is better solved by the
state or local government than by the Federal Government. And 59 percent
said they thought private charity could solve the problems of the poor
better than any level of government.<p>

A rejection certainly of centralized government and a rejection of
government as an instrument that we really haven't seen in any of our
lifetimes. That's much of the story of 1994.<p>

Now the question to me is, "How do we make sure that in 1995 we don't
simply lead to the result that we experienced in 1993?" I think we need to
remember some of the lessons of 1992 as we look forward and try to deal
with these problems.<p>

The first one is there has to be that alternative model of problem solving
that people did not see in the Bush Administration. This model must include
a serious commitment to a devolution and a diffusion of power. If we simply
try to reform the Federal approach to problem solving to be more consistent
with what we might think of as conservative values, it seems to me we are
going to come up against the public's fundamental lack of confidence in a
centralized approach to government.<p>

Welfare is probably the best example. A reform of the Federal welfare
system is not in our interest. We must put resources in the hands of other
entities so that people see an alternative model to problem solving rather
than simply the passive approach to problems that they've learned over
several generations of Federal Government dominance.<p>

That means devolving power to the states and localities. But even more
important, because government itself is being rejected even at state and
local levels, is diffusing power out from government to individuals.<p>

We need to invent a model which reflects the flattening of society, the
rejection of centralized edifices of control, which instead leads to the
empowerment, to use an overworked word, of people in their communities and
in their families to solve their problems.<p>

The second message that we should remember from the 1992 elections is a
basic economic issue. But it's important politically that we recognize an
important new reality. There seems to be a conventional wisdom that argues
that a strong economy benefits the party in power and a weak economy
benefits the party out of power. And hence, if the economy turns sour, that
certainly will finish the Clinton Administration off once and for all.<p>

I would argue that there's a different reality at work today, and it
relates directly to the dynamic of the Third Wave forces that are
transforming our society. The new reality is that a strong economy benefits
the party that is on the side of the transformation of society currently
taking place. And when the economy turns weak, the party that is warning
about the dangers of that transformation benefits.<p>

That is why Republicans just won a stunning realigning election in the
midst of a pretty strong economy. That is also why, if the economy
genuinely turns south in 1996, it will probably help the Clinton
Administration far more than it will help the Republicans in the Congress
who are arguing that now is the time to devolve power and divest the
government of most of its authority.<p>

Thus we must remember, progress will be achieved more readily when people
feel more economically secure. When people are worried about their
paychecks, they are less willing to discard the comfortable, but no longer
workable, systems designed for the Second Wave.<p>
<i>Vin Weber, a former six-term Congressman from Minnesota, leads PFF's 
Center
for Political Renewal.</i><br>

<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
