<head><title>Reasserting States' Rights -- PFF</title></head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<h2>Reasserting States' Rights</h2>

<b>An Interview with Gov. Mike Leavitt</b>
<P>
<i>American Civilization speaks with Governor Mike Leavitt of Utah about the
Conference of the States: An Action Plan to Restore Balance in the Federal
System. As co-chairman of the National Governors' Association, Leavitt is
leading an effort among governors and state legislatures to restore the
balance of power between the national government and the states.</i>
<P>
<br>
<b>AmCiv</b>: What is the Conference of the States and what are you trying to
accomplish?
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: Americans feel alienated from their national government and
want government decisions that affect their lives made locally or at the
state level. What we are trying to do is create a forum that would
demonstrate the states' resolve to take back from Congress the powers that
rightly belong to each of the states.
<P>
We are currently trying to get a resolution passed in each state that
authorizes them to send delegates to the Conference, where they will
examine proposals to restore the balance in the federal system. Currently
we have 35 states where a resolution for participation in the Conference
has been introduced in their legislature, and we expect the remainder of
the states to do the same.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: Are you getting any resistance?
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: We have had little serious resistance so far. In Colorado we
had a skirmish, because a real far right group called the Patriots is
worried about constitutional conventions in general, and they worry that
somehow this will turn into a constitutional convention, and exploit the
constitution -- but they're the only opposition thus far. It would be
impossible for this to turn into a Constitutional Convention.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: What happens next, after the states have chosen delegates to attend
the Conference?
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: They'll be two meetings. The first one will be just a
convening meeting, when we'll elect officers, establish by-laws and the
priorities of the agenda. This will be in July. Then in October we will
meet in Philadelphia, where the delegates will consider, refine and vote on
ways of correcting the imbalance in the federal system.
<P>
Any item receiving the support of the delegates will be included in the
States' Petition, which will be an action plan for change. It will be the
highest form of communication between the states and the Congress, and it
will gain its authority from the sheer power of the process the states
followed to initiate it. It shouldn't be taken lightly because it will
symbolize the states' seriousness to restore balance in our system.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: What types of items do you expect to be on the Petition?
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: We are establishing this in a way that limits any attempt to
make this a vehicle to deal with some of the more divisive issues -- school
prayer, federal lands, immigration, any of those issues that would become
so specific that we'd lose the capacity to agree on. We'll be excluding
those issues from the discussion.
<P>
In my assessment we'll likely focus on three areas as the primary means of
change. The first would be a state initiated amendment process, where you
invert the current process and allow as an alternative means of amending
the Constitution 38 states to actually initiate an amendment, instead of
just the Congress. This levels the playing field, because currently states
cannot initiate amendments except at the extraordinary step of a
Constitutional Convention. I mean, certainly the Founders intended the
states to have a role in amending the Constitution, to be able to initiate
it through the conventional process. But that has proven so unworkable,
impractical, that it has never been done.
<P>
Another topic that's generating a lot of interest and might become part of
the States' Petition is a proposal made in 1980 by, ironically, Bruce
Babbit. The idea would be to have two-thirds of the states have the power
to, in essence, sunset any federal law except those dealing with foreign
affairs or national defense. It provides the states with a mechanism to
remove onerous burdens imposed by the central government.
<P>
A third area that I think people will be interested in talking about will
be this whole area of unfunded mandates. And I think there's a lot of folks
exercised about that. A good model for this is the Safe Drinking Water Act.
<P>
<P>
Initially it was 40 pages long. They're re-authorizing it now, and it's
about 800 pages. As a 40 page document, it was a very successful law; as an
800 page document, its burdensome.
<P>
But let me be clear. The Conference of the States isn't about who is going
to do welfare, or who is going to do Medicaid, or who's going to take care
of transportation. This is establishing a framework that creates checks and
balances -- that restores the checks and balances.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: Congress is very friendly to states, and doing some really good
things. But they're focusing on day to day issues that are very
controversial, not on the structural long-term reforms that will create
balance in the system.
<P>
But we don't know if we're going to have a state friendly Congress six
years from now, or ten years from now. The Conference of States, then, is
an opportunity to put into place those long-term reforms that will maintain
the proper balance. It is about more than day to day issues.
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: Correct. Also, it is non-partisan and the Conference will be
paid for out of state appropriated money, not political contributions.
Right now we're just a speck on the radar screen, but when the States'
Petition passes the Conference and it goes back to the states, we hope
people then will engage in actively encouraging grassroots support for its
passage in the 50 state legislatures. And if 75 percent of the states can
agree on certain articles of the States' Petition, then we'll send it to
Congress as notice of our seriousness.
<P>
The whole idea is to create a process that is so deliberate, and so arduous
in nature that it becomes the single highest form of communication between
the collected states and the Congress, something so unequivocal that it
cannot be denied as the will of the people.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: While you're here, let's switch subjects for a moment and talk about
the idea of block grants, which is a topic of much discussion in Congress
these days.
<P>
The problem we see with block grants is that they are ultimately next
year's temptation to micro-manage. There was a great quotation in The New
York Times where a Republican staffer in Congress is quoted as saying that
what these governors want us to do is leave the money on a stump in the
forest in the middle of the night, so they can run off with it and do what
they want.
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: That's exactly what we want.
<P>
<b>AmCiv</b>: But what happens if you get a Democratic Congress six years from now
-- and it won't just be Democrats -- the instinct to micro manage is
endemic to the federal government?
<P>
<b>Gov Leavitt</b>: Ultimately what you have to do is move the capacity to tax
back to the states. If you could take a block of programs that cost X, and
essentially shift the responsibility for them to states, and at the same
time reduce federal income tax by X (or maybe a bit less than X so that you
are getting some deficit reduction out of it) and then just invite states
at the same time to increase their taxes to whatever degree they desire or
need to meet their responsibilities.
<P>
In this way you take away from Congress the ability to micromanage. It is a
far more permanent change than block grants.
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
