<head><title>The Future Of Medical Innovation: Reaping The Benefits Of The Knowledge Revolution -- PFF</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" background="notebook.gif" link="#8C1717" vlink="#545454" alink="#FF0000">
<a href="/pff"><img src="pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a>
<P>
<ul>
<center>
<h2>The Future Of Medical Innovation: Reaping The Benefits Of The Knowledge Revolution</h2>

<b>by Thomas Lenard and Brian Mannix</b>
</center>
<P><br>
<blockquote>
<h3>Introduction</h3>


We are witnessing an explosion of scientific knowledge that will form the
basis for medical advances well into the twenty-first century.  But our
ability to realize fully the benefits of these advances--actually
delivering new products to patients--is threatened by an outmoded
regulatory framework.  The purpose of the Progress & Freedom Foundation's
Medical Innovation Project is to design a new process for bringing medical
products to market--one compatible with legitimate concerns for safety and
leaps in scientific knowledge.<P>


This new process will consist of several parts:  it will provide for review
and certification of new pharmaceuticals and medical devices, as well as
the dissemination of information about these products to the medical
community; it will include a tort liability framework that stimulates
manufacturers to produce safer products, but does not discourage them from
introducing products that save lives; and, it will protect intellectual
property rights, without which these products would not be on the market at
all.<P>


In sum, the new system must provide our citizens with the safety
protections they want and need, but not impede the development of
twenty-first century technologies that measurably improve their health.
Remaining with the system we now have will lead to a continued movement of
our medical technology sectors overseas, where the benefits of new
technologies will be enjoyed while they are unavailable here.
<P>

<h2>Stifling Innovation</h2>


The United States is the world's leader in biomedical research:  in public
sector spending through the National Institutes of Health and other
government agencies; in private sector research and development
(particularly through the many entrepreneurial firms sustained by U. S.
venture capital markets); in the dramatic scientific discoveries that all
this research has produced; and, in manufacturing the drugs, diagnostics
and medical devices   that apply these breakthroughs to improving human
health.  Unfortunately, it has become increasingly difficult to bring these
new medical products to the market.  Many studies (see references) provide
convincing evidence of the discouraging effect our current regulatory
procedures have on the development of new products.  Americans receive the
benefits of fewer new drugs and medical devices later than they should.
Our review and approval process is one of  the slowest in the world, and it
is now routine for new drugs and devices to be available in other countries
before they become available here.
<P>

During a clinical trial, if researchers observe that the patients in a
"treatment group" are dying at a significantly faster rate than those in a
"control group," the experiment is halted.  And if researchers observe that
a control group is dying at a much faster rate than a treatment group, the
experiment is also halted and the treatment made available to both groups.
What researchers cannot do, however, is make the treatment available to the
population of patients outside the experiment.  In effect, the great
majority of patients are compelled to remain in what is essentially a large
control group, whether or not it is a safe place to be.  Ultimately, the
system as now configured may deprive patients of life-saving products that
never come to market because the overall costs of innovation have been
driven too high.
<P>

The current approval process also deprives patients and their doctors of
critically important information. The biomedical research industry is an
information industry, and the FDA's principal functions are all in one way
or another information-related.  Yet manufacturers are prohibited from
disseminating much valuable information about their products.  Roughly half
of all drug prescriptions, including most of those for children, are
written for unapproved "off-label" uses.  The FDA prohibits and sanctions
manufacturers from marketing drugs for these uses.  Thus, for example, the r
esults of National Institutes of Health studies of off-label uses cannot be
circulated to physicians.  At the same time, however, a pediatrician who
withheld a drug from a sick child simply because it was unapproved would be
subject to a charge of malpractice!
<P>

The regulation of drugs and medical devices should be from the point of
view of helping patients.  With this in mind, we propose the development of
a new institutional arrangement to ensure the safety of new drugs and
medical devices--one that will be explicitly offered as a replacement for
much of what the Food and Drug Administration now does.  Our purpose is to
design a new structure that will yield the correct balance of objectives:
on the one hand, to bring new medical products to patients; on the other,
to provide at least as much assurance as we now have that those products
are safe and effective.  A replacement system must also facilitate the flow
of accurate information on the safety and efficacy of drugs and medical
devices.
<P>

<h2>The Role of the Private Sector</h2>


The appropriate division of private- and public-sector responsibilities to
accomplish these objectives is a major focus of our project.  What should
be the government's role?  A major task is to examine the advantages and
disadvantages of placing substantially greater reliance on private
institutions, which experience has shown usually provide performance
superior to that of government institutions.
<P>

Many react to this idea by saying a government watchdog is essential to
ensure safety:  How can we expect parents to give a prescription drug to
their children without the assurance of a safety review by the FDA?  We do
not  suggest that drugs and medical devices come to market without careful
review, but there are ways to do this that do not unduly slow innovation or
discourage the production of valuable information.  We need a system that
strikes the right balance: one offering all patients access to the best
health care options available and with the best information we can provide
about risks and benefits.  The bottom line is the benefit to the patient,
and whether patients can be served better by a new system.
<P>

<h2>The Revolution in Medical Technology1</h2>

Rapid advances in information technology are transforming many industries,
and nowhere is that more evident than in medicine.  The combination of
computers, sensors, and imaging systems--CAT and PET scans and MRI--are
replacing invasive procedures and "exploratory" surgery.  Microscopic
cameras and microscopic tools are making Fantastic Voyage not seem so far
fetched.  Already physicians have tested a "virtual colonoscopy" that
couples a virtual-reality imaging system with a CAT scan.  Without
inserting an instrument, the physician can "fly" through the patient's
colon on screen, searching for signs of disease.  In addition to creating
fantastic medical devices, data processing capabilities promise to allow
far more efficient tracking of treatments and outcomes for large numbers of
patients, allowing successful medical strategies to be identified.
<P>

The rapid pace of progress in information technology has been equaled, if
not exceeded, by the explosion of knowledge about the genetic and molecular
foundation of life--what we call the new biotechnology.  This new knowledge
provides us with a far better understanding of the causes of diseases, a
far better ability to identify and characterize infectious agents  and a
far better ability to design countermeasures.  We can identify a "typo" in
an individual gene and are learning how to correct it.  We are beginning to
understand the complex mechanisms by which genes are turned on and off, and
how cancer and other diseases result when these mechanisms go awry.
<P>

Modern medical technology enables us to know far more than was previously
possible about the causes, and likely remedies, for a wide range of
illnesses.  Identification of genetic defects has expanded exponentially;
already two children with Severe Combined Immune Deficiency2  have been
treated with corrective genes.  The recent identification of the cystic
fibrosis (CF) gene may make possible a similar gene therapy approach.  Gene
therapy is also being attempted for cancer, a disease with genetic
components.
<P>
Patients are now being treated with the protein products of human
genes--such as human growth hormone and human insulin--which are produced
by genetically modified bacteria.  The bacteria are engineered to contain
and express the same gene that the treated individuals lack.  One major
advantage of these bacteria-produced biologicals is that they can be made
to match perfectly the human version (so that diabetics can use human,
rather than pig, insulin), yet there is no chance of contamination with
viruses (as can be the case when the same product is obtained from animal
donors).
<P>

When human donors must be used--as is still the case with blood and other
organ transplants--biotechnology supplies sensitive tests to identify known
dangerous contamination or tissue mismatch.  New biotechnology-based tests
for exposure to HIV-1 and the hepatitis viruses are essential to assuring
the safety of the U.S. blood supply.
<P>

Genetic engineering brings special advantages to the production of
vaccines.  In the past, the principal risk of vaccination involved
administering a pathogen sufficiently intact to provoke an immune response,
but not so intact as to produce serious disease, even when administered to
millions of individuals.  Walking this line requires very careful quality
control.  Developing a successful vaccine was previously a hit or miss
proposition, but new technology allows us to construct vaccines lacking key
genetic sequences required for virulence but retaining intact antigens,
thereby making vaccines safer, more effective and more economical.  In
addition, improved understanding of the genetic basis of the immune
function opens the door to developing treatments for various auto-immune
diseases, as well as offering the possibility of enhancing the immune
response to infectious diseases.
<P>

Biotechnology also gives us tools for identifying and studying the
pathogens that cause infectious diseases.  While satisfactory progress
against AIDS has been frustratingly difficult to achieve, it is difficult
to imagine what lines of research could be pursued without the tools of
biotechnology.  Other biotechnology applications in medicine include
diagnostic applications based on monoclonal antibodies and DNA probes,
biopolymers or synthetic tissues used for implants, prosthetics and other
clinical uses.
<P>

<h2>From Laboratory to Patient -- Research and Development in
Medical Innovation</h2>

The discovery and development of pharmaceuticals and medical devices is a
time-consuming, uncertain process that requires years of expensive
laboratory work, preclinical and, ultimately, clinical testing.  It now
takes approximately 12 years to bring a drug to the market, at an average
cost approaching $400 million.3   Only a small fraction of laboratory
investigations yield a compound suitable for animal studies, and only a
small fraction of those are promising enough to warrant clinical testing on
humans.  Many years of costs are incurred before there is even a chance of
patients receiving new medicines and companies earning returns on their
investment.  This is of special significance for start-up companies, such
as many biotechnology firms which have no products bringing in revenue
while they invest in researching new medicines.
<P>

The uncertainties associated with the R&D process are dominant factors, not
only for biotechnology firms, but for the medical technology sector
generally.  At the most basic level is the scientific risk associated with
the research.  Researchers simply do not know what is going to work, how
well, or when.  If the science does work out in some form, and a product
can be brought to market, what will the market be like?  How much
competition will there be, here and abroad?  Will other scientific
developments quickly make this new product obsolete, perhaps before it is
even ready?  Investing in intellectual property carries its own particular
risks, since investors cannot be sure that, years later, they will still
own that for which they paid.  Talented individuals cannot be
indentured--after collecting a large salary for many years, they may walk
away with the firm's most significant assets. Only patentable inventions
have secure value, and the patent process has its own risks.
<P>

Additional uncertainty can be created by government or private health-care
financing rules.  Patients may not have coverage for new treatments
(regardless of whether they are approved by the FDA).  Or the price paid by
health care programs may be too low to fully recover research and
development costs.
<P>

Finally, the FDA approval process creates its own major uncertainties, both
with respect to ultimate approval and the time and expense required to gain
approval.  FDA disapproval at some stage of the process can change the
value of a firm and its effective cost of capital overnight, especially for
small companies without diversified product lines.  These regulatory
uncertainties reduce the returns from research and development in the
pharmaceutical and device sectors and, therefore, the number of new
therapeutic products that are developed.
<P>

Many risks are intrinsic to the drug and device development process itself,
but some--most importantly, the regulatory risks--may be at least partially
avoidable.  To the extent we reduce regulatory uncertainties, and the
regulatory component of development costs generally, we increase the flow
of capital to this market and the flow of new products to patients.
<P>

<h2>From Helping to Hindering the Market--A Brief Historical Review of Drug and Device Approval</h2>


Pharmaceuticals regulation always has been appropriately concerned with
information.  Sellers of medical products frequently know more about their
products than buyers, and this can be harmful to the proper functioning of
the market.  But over the years the focus of drug regulation has shifted,
from trying to correct this information asymmetry to becoming a central
participant in the basic processes of generating and disseminating
information throughout the major phases of a product's development and
marketing.4
<P>
The purpose of the Pure Food and Drug Act of 1906, the first major piece of
drug legislation, was to provide consumers with accurate information about
the quality of products they were purchasing.  False and misleading claims
about drugs and their contents were prohibited, and manufacturers were made
liable for adulterated or misbranded drugs.
<P>

The Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act of 1938 established the requirement for
government approval before a drug could be marketed.  Manufacturers were
required to test for safety in animals and humans and submit those test
results to the FDA for review.  The process was far shorter and the FDA's
role more limited than now.
<P>

The Kefauver-Harris Amendments of 1962 ushered in the current regulatory
regime.  First, they required that manufacturers provide premarket evidence
of efficacy as well as safety.  Second, they marked a major change in the
FDA's role in pharmaceuticals regulation--from essentially being a reviewer
and evaluator of information to playing a central decision-making role in
the conduct of clinical research.  FDA now regulates in detail the
protocols for the clinical trials undertaken prior to the New Drug
Application (NDA), evaluates the data, may require additional testing, and
has to approve what manufacturers can say about their products.
<P>

The 1976 amendments to the Food, Drug and Cosmetics Act established a
two-track approval process for medical devices.5   As with the process for
pharmaceuticals, the premarket approval (PMA) process for devices requires
submitting clinical and other scientific evidence on safety and efficacy.
Most devices go through the less demanding 510 (k) process, which applies
to devices that can be shown to be "substantially equivalent" to products
already on the market before the 1976 amendments.
<P>

An important corollary of the current drug approval process is that
manufacturers are precluded from disseminating any information on the
effectiveness or safety of their products, unless such data have been
included in an approved NDA.  Similar restrictions apply to manufacturers
of medical devices.
<P>

Physicians, however, are free to prescribe approved products for
applications other than those in the NDA, and these "off-label" uses are
now estimated to account for roughly half of all prescriptions.6
Nonetheless, manufacturers are not allowed to refer to any published
studies, including refereed journal articles or textbooks, in their
promotional materials or to sponsor educational symposia about new uses.
They cannot, therefore, tell you or your doctor about research results on
such subjects as the effects of aspirin on heart attacks or of estrogen on
cancer.  (Your doctor can tell you if he happens to read the right medical
journal.)  Device manufacturers face comparable restrictions in the kinds
of hands-on demonstrations they can offer physicians.
<P>

These restrictions deprive doctors and their patients of valuable
information.  They may, moreover, discourage useful studies of off-label
uses from being undertaken, since information from these studies cannot be
freely used in medical communications.
<P>

<h2>Case-by-Case Regulatory Review</h2>


The goal of the case-by-case regulatory approach to reviewing new medical
products is to block dangerous products while permitting beneficial ones to
go forward.  There are two kinds of mistakes government reviewers can make:
(1) approving a product that turns out to be dangerous, and (2) blocking
or delaying a product that would have been beneficial.  While both types of
mistakes impose serious consequences on patients, they are not viewed as
equally serious by regulators.  Victims of the first type of mistake,
approving a product that turns out to be dangerous, are very visible,
provoking Congressional hearings, public outcry and perhaps even loss of a
job for the responsible reviewer.  This "Congressional-fishbowl syndrome"
provides a strong disincentive to approve something that has even a remote
potential of having unexpected negative effects.  Mistakes of the second
type, however, go largely unseen.  Victims of a delay in or disapproval of
a beneficial product are not readily observed.7   The costs of the second
type of mistake, therefore, are not readily apparent, providing the
reviewer with a strong incentive to err on the side of conservatism,
requiring extensive proof before approving new products.
<P>

It is always possible to generate additional information and increase
statistical precision by doing additional testing.  And this may improve
the chances of detecting problems in a new drug or medical device, although
the returns from additional data gathering can be expected to diminish
sharply at some point.  The institutional pressures faced by FDA do not
recognize that equal weight should be given to the costs to patients when
beneficial products are kept off the market.
<P>

There is a substantial consensus that the 1962 Amendments have slowed the
rate of pharmaceutical innovation.  A series of studies by prominent
researchers found that the 1962 Amendments and ensuing regulations had a
significant adverse effect on the introduction of new chemical entities,
after controlling for the influence of other factors.8  There is also
evidence that the PMA process for medical devices had a similar effect.
International comparisons provide additional evidence:9
<P>
Average development times for pharmaceuticals, including clinical testing
and review times, are 77 percent higher in the United States than in other
countries (9.2 vs. 5.2 years).10
75 percent of the new drugs approved (between 1984 and 1992) were already
available in other countries.11   These drugs are frequently available in a
large number of countries for a number years before approval in the United
States.12
<P>
The number of PMA medical device approvals declined steeply in the late
1980s and early 1990s, falling to a low point of 12 approvals in 1992.  In
that year, average approval time was 663 working days, more than twice the
time needed in Europe and Japan.13
Medical device manufacturers are increasingly locating research and
manufacturing facilities offshore.  For example, the CEO of a major medical
device manufacturer--responsible for developing pacemaker
technology--recently reported that virtually all of his firm's major
products are now being developed, tested and produced overseas, and, most
importantly, are available to patients elsewhere much earlier than they are
available here.14   He indicated that American patients are sometimes
receiving therapies that are two-to-three generations behind those
available in Europe, Canada and Japan.
<P>
These effects cannot be remedied by tinkering with the current system,
because they reflect a systemic problem.  The skewed institutional
incentives faced by FDA result in an imbalance of the benefits of FDA
regulation (in terms of keeping unsafe and ineffective products off the
market) relative to the costs of denying patients access to beneficial
products.
<P>

<h2>A Framework for Change</h2>


The issue, then, is how to achieve the objectives of safety and efficacy
for new medical products in a way that does not sacrifice the equally
important objectives of bringing valuable therapies and information to
patients in a timely manner.
<P>

We should begin by recognizing that the market, supplemented by the tort
system, already provides substantial incentives to produce safe and
effective products.  Moreover, current trends in health-care financing,
which increase the importance of health maintenance organizations and other
large, sophisticated buyers in the market, make those incentives stronger
than they were at the time the existing regulatory framework was being
developed decades ago.  Managed-care providers don't want to provide
coverage for unsafe or ineffective medical treatments.
<P>

There remains, however, a potentially troublesome information asymmetry
between sellers and buyers, and the market may not provide sufficient
incentives to overcome it.  The current regulatory requirements for
information on safety and efficacy may be too high in many instances, and
unnecessarily keep useful therapeutic products off the market.  But, the
clinical tests and other studies needed to generate data on safety and
efficacy are very expensive, and one can envision situations where firms
might do too little testing.  One can also imagine cases where firms might
downplay the importance of adverse results on safety or efficacy, in order
not to jeopardize a product's profitability.
<P>

Proposals for change should build on the many incentives already available
in the market for the generation and dissemination of accurate information
on quality, safety and efficacy, but should also recognize that patients
have come to rely on the third-party stamp of approval that the FDA now
confers.  They need to be equally comfortable with any alternative
arrangements.  With these factors in mind, there are (at least) three
interrelated sets of issues relating to reform of the process by which
medical innovations are introduced:  institutional issues, legal issues and
scientific issues.
<P>

<h2>Institutional Issues</h2>


The current review and approval system provides a very strong incentive to
keep unsafe products off the market--at the expense of also keeping new
beneficial products off the market.  In the process, it also suppresses the
distribution to the medical community of valuable information on off-label
uses.  The critical task, then, is to design a new system that corrects
these defects--one that encourages the flow of innovations and new
information while retaining the public's confidence in the pharmaceuticals
and medical devices on the market.  This requires that consumers have at
least as much assurance in the safety and efficacy of those products as
they do now.  The net result should be a significant increase in public
health benefits.
<P>

For some time a number of private-sector entities have accomplished
safety-related functions in other product areas, and may provide useful
lessons for the drug and device approval processes.  For example,
third-party product certification is done by Underwriters Laboratory;
voluntary standards development by the American National Standards
Institute and the American Society for Testing and Materials; and peer
review of safety systems by the Institute of Nuclear Power Operations.
<P>

The major questions here concern the role of government in the review and
approval process, and the circumstances under which the incentives faced by
nongovernmental certifying entities would be an improvement over those
faced by the FDA:
<P>

Can the FDA be restructured to avoid the adverse outcomes experienced under
the current regulatory regime?  What can be learned from the experience of
other countries, which approve the marketing of new drugs and devices more
rapidly?  Could greater reliance be placed on panels of outside experts, as
is the case elsewhere?
<P>
Can private entities be structured to avoid the information asymmetry--that
sellers sometimes have an incentive to withhold information from buyers?
Should a private certifying agency be certified by the government?  Should
private certifiers compete with the FDA?  Should manufacturers, in this age
of user fees, have the option of submitting their data to either a private
firm, the FDA or both?  Would private certifiers be subject to conflicts of
interest and how would those be handled?
<P>
How much reliance can be placed on market pressures from buyers?  The
large, sophisticated buyers of medical care that now dominate the medical
marketplace have a strong economic interest in selecting products that are
both safe and effective.  These large buyers can place direct pressure on
pharmaceuticals and medical device suppliers to disclose relevant
information.  They may also prove to be good customers of private
certification firms.  Should large buyers, such as HMOs and hospitals, be
able to make their own certification decisions?  Could buyers and sellers
of medical products jointly sponsor private certifiers that would, as a
result of their joint sponsorship, have the right incentives to provide
objective information?
<P>
Should different levels of certification be encouraged, as long as the
information available is fully disclosed?  Along these lines, should the
efficacy requirement be retained for all approvals?
<P>
Should the certification process carry with it any restrictions on the
dissemination of information by manufacturers?  If so, what should be the
criteria be for defining these restrictions?
<P>

<h2>Legal Issues</h2>


Product liability laws serve an important purpose, both in providing
compensation to victims of accidents and illnesses and in stimulating
manufacturers to produce safer products.  A less regulatory approach to the
approval process for drugs and medical devices may increase the importance
of product liability laws in providing appropriate incentives for safety as
well as the dissemination of reliable information.  The questions that need
to be considered concern the role of  the tort system within a restructured
drug and device review and approval framework:
<P>

How can the product liability system be structured to recognize both types
of errors that manufacturers can make--the marketing of an unsafe product
and the withholding of a safe one?15   (If it only recognizes the first
error, its biases will be similar to those of the current regulatory
regime.)<br>
What is the effect of product liability law on the incentives to produce
data both before and after a product is marketed, and to disseminate
accurate data on risks to users--patients, physicians and hospitals--of the
product?<br>
<P>
How should liability exposure be divided in a system in which there is
greater private responsibility for the introduction of new drugs and
devices?  What would be the liability exposure of private certifiers?  How
can the liability rules be structured so that these entities have
appropriate incentives for safety, but still participate in the system?
<P>
How should the tradeoff between the insurance and safety functions of
product liability be made?  This involves standards for determining both
liability and damages?
<P>
Given the national (and international) scope of the pharmaceuticals and
devices markets, should a federal product liability statute preempt state
statutes?
<P>

<h2>Patent Protection</h2>


The growth in the number of drug patent applications indicates that the
body of scientific knowledge relevant for pharmaceutical advances is
growing rapidly.16   Longer patent lives increase the expected
profitability from research and development expenditures, with a consequent
increase in the rate of technical advance.  For the patient, longer patent
protection should increase the availability of new products.  The downside
is that prices for these products will be higher for a longer period of
time.
<P>
The effective patent life for pharmaceuticals products is the difference
between approval of the New Drug Application and the expiration of the
patent.  This is generally far shorter than the statutory patent life of 17
years (recently extended to 20 years under GATT).  Recognizing the
interrelationship between the approval process, and in response to evidence
that the average effective patent life for products subject to the FDA
review and approval process was declining, Congress passed legislation in
1984 increasing patent life for pharmaceuticals and medical devices for up
to five years.
<P>

Any change that speeds the entry of new drugs and medical devices to the
market will increase the effective patent life.  The implications of this
need to be evaluated in the context of any proposed new system.
<P>

<h2>Scientific Issues</h2>


Medical innovation is about science, and the development of adequate safety
and efficacy information involves issues of experimental and statistical
design.  These necessarily involve a weighing of costs and benefits,
because it is always possible to do another test or to increase statistical
precision by expanding the sample size.  Major scientific issues involve
the extent and type of testing needed for different categories of products:
<P>

Given that testing is expensive, and keeps drugs and devices off the
market, how much testing is enough and when does it become too much?  The
answer will clearly vary depending on the nature of the therapy, the
condition it is designed to address, and the available alternatives.
Nevertheless, we need to address the value, at the margin, of the
information produced under the current system.
<P>
What is the appropriate balance between pre and postmarket studies?  The
U.S. approval process, in contrast to some other systems, is heavily
weighted toward premarket testing, which keep drugs and devices off the
market longer.
<P>
Who should be responsible for issues of experimental and statistical
design?  The FDA has increasingly taken this responsibility itself, though
there clearly are other repositories of this expertise.
<P>
What has been the effect on the review process of the requirement to
provide evidence on efficacy?  Should this requirement be revised?
<P>

<h2>Reaping the Benefits of Knowledge</h2>


The body of knowledge relevant for medical innovation is increasing at a
rapid rate, providing growing opportunities for therapeutic advances.  At
the same time, the "informational-cybernetic paradigm" of modern molecular
biology offers the promise of greater medical gains aimed at the causes of
many diseases, not just their symptoms.17   This environment demands a
system that facilitates the flow of medical innovations to patients.

<P>
Designing a new system to bring medical products and technologies to the
patient more efficiently is a complex problem, involving interrelated
scientific, economic, institutional and legal issues.  The sectors that
create new medical knowledge are diverse, as are the products they create.
We need a mechanism that accommodates this diversity and nourishes the
creative process.
<P>

As a nation, we spend tens of billions of dollars on medical research each
year, and most of it is conducted in the private sector.  Our citizens must
be confident that they are reaping the benefits of the vast research
establishment we have erected--a flow of medical products that are safe and
the best available.  They and their doctors must also be sure they can
obtain the information necessary to make choices about their medical care.
Our goal is to develop a system that satisfies these goals.
<P>

<p>
<h2>Selected References</h2>


