<html>
<head>
<title>Treating Illness Before it Occurs, and Other Marvels of Modern Medicine -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> 
<ul><blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a>
<center>
<h2>Treating Illness Before it Occurs, and Other Marvels of Modern Medicine</h2>
<p>
By William Haseltine
<p>
</center>
<p>
Health, our own health and the health of those we love is a fundamental concern both to us 
as individuals and as a nation.  Health is an issue which unites all of us. That is why it is important 
that we understand the revolution in medical science now occurring.
<p>
Historically, the practice of medicine has been the application of external entities, devices, 
or plants and mineral extracts to our bodies.  Probably the earliest medical intervention was the 
splint -- clearly an extrinsic device to help speed repair of our body.
<p>
Very likely, as far as we can tell by examination of a number of societies around the 
world, the next type of medicine, and in fact the predominant form of medicine until the early part 
of our own century, was the use of plant extracts, other natural substances and minerals taken from 
the earth as medicines.  These too are clearly extrinsic.
<p>
This century has brought a change with which we are all familiar, those little white pills 
that probably some of you took this morning.  Most of those are synthetic chemicals.  It was the 
great flowering of synthetic organic chemistry in the last part of the previous century and the early 
part of this century that gave rise to the great pharmacopeia which treats many of our ills.  But 
again, those are extrinsic to our bodies.
<p>
<h3>The Genetic Revolution</h3>
<p>
The revolution which has occurred in biomedicine since the early 1950s has given us a 
much deeper understanding of our human body in terms of its microscopic components -- the genes 
and proteins. That understanding has begun to transform the fundamental nature of medicine.
<p>
For example, the body makes a variety of hormones. Many of the hormones are proteins 
that control very fundamental processes, such as how we grow as a child or how fast we replace 
injured or damaged tissues. Each hormone, as indeed each protein, each sub-microscopic 
component in our body, is made by a gene.  A gene can be thought of as an instruction to make a 
protein.  One gene makes one protein.
<p>
What fueled the initial biotechnology revolution was a very simple technology, the ability 
to take a single gene and make in a fermenter, sort of a big pot, as much of any particular human 
protein as you wanted.  It was that simple revolution that changed the face of biotechnology.
<p>
One of the early products from this research is the human growth hormone.  The gene was 
isolated, a lot of proteins made, and that purified human protein is now used to treat dwarfism. 
Another gene that was isolated was the gene that promotes blood clotting, the precise product that 
is missing in hemophiliacs.  Rather than using blood transfusions and concentrate on the blood, we 
now use this purified protein to treat hemophilia.
<p>
Similarly, humans make proteins that are involved in dissolving clots.  That protein is now 
used to treat people with heart attacks, when clots develop in the blood vessels of the heart. Purified 
human insulin is now made from the human insulin gene and used to treat diabetes.  Purified 
human hormones that control either how fast red or white blood cells grow are used in cancer 
therapy to great effect.
<p>
All these are natural products that are used today to treat serious illness.  Incidently, these 
handful of products that I just described account for about $8 billion of sales worldwide and have 
created more than 15,000 jobs in the pharmaceutical industry in the United States alone. These are 
just a few indications of what is to come. We can predict that there will be a torrent of products in 
the future.
<p>
<h3>A New Paradigm for Medicine</h3>
<p>
The new medicine is based not on extrinsic entities, splints, natural products from plants 
and the earth, or synthetic chemicals, but our own genes and our proteins.  It is a move from an 
extrinsic treatment to an intrinsic use of those substances which we naturally use to cure ourselves.
<p>
Not only are the proteins themselves used as the new basis of the new medicine, but the 
gene, that description, that piece of information used to program a cell to make a protein, is also 
becoming a medicine.
<p>
The change that is now in progress is more profound than the substitution of one kind of 
pill for another.  The change from extrinsic to intrinsic medicine will trigger a qualitative shift in 
the medical paradigm and will have a profound impact both on the type of medicine that is 
practiced and on our health care system as a whole.
<p>
Today much of medicine is based on the following practice: diagnosis of disease after it 
has occurred, followed by treatment to alleviate the symptoms without necessarily curing the 
underlying cause of those symptoms.  Diagnosis of disease followed by non-curative treatments is 
the rule for diseases such as arthritis, high blood pressure, heart disease, Alzheimers, many cancers, 
as well as most other chronic ills.
<p>
This medical paradigm is now changing.  We are now entering an era when disease will 
be predicted before it occurs.  Genetic text will be read to predict predisposition to disease.  That 
prediction will not always be bootless, as I illustrated with the case of colon, ovarian, and uterine 
cancer.  Nevertheless, there are remedies that can be based on that prediction.
<p>
Abnormal genes and proteins will be used to detect other diseases at a very early stage 
before illness occurs.  Prediction and early detection will permit avoidance of high risk activity 
through careful management, education, and treatment.  Changes in lifestyle, diet, exercise, will be 
designed to avoid many diseases before they occur.
<p>
The use of human genes and proteins offers another opportunity when coupled with 
disease prediction.  Healthy genes will be used to replace missing or damaged genes before disease 
occurs.  Replacement of genes can be used then to avoid the illness.  Naturally occurring proteins 
can also be used to replace missing and damaged proteins.
<p>
Finally, medicine will begin to move into an era of cure, forever altering the underlying 
cause of a disease through gene replacement.  The medical paradigm will shift from detection of 
disease, to prediction of disease before it occurs, management to reduce risk, prevention of the 
disease, and when necessary, cure.
<p>
<p>
William Haseltine is chairman of the board and CEO of Human Genome Systems, Inc. The above are edited remarks he delivered at PFF’s Medical Innovation Project on June 15, 1995.
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>




