<html>
<head>
<title>21st Century Medicine -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2>21st Century Medicine</h2>
<p>
By Newt Gingrich
<p>
<br>
Many Americans will be surprised by the following assertion: During the 21st century 
health care will become dramatically less expensive, not more expensive.  If we are aggressive 
enough in pursuing the opportunities that lay before us, there well may be a 20 percent drop in the 
cost of health care in the first decade of the next century.
<p>
Driving this are five explosive changes that are occurring simultaneously. First is the rise 
of molecular medicine which will lead to cures for diseases at the genetic level. Second, increased 
computational power provides us with the capacity to create virtual reality that allows doctors to 
test therapies very early. Third, distance electronics, such as a worldwide satellite system, will 
allow experts in one part of the globe to guide therapy in real time in another part of the world.
<p>
Fourth is the rise of expert systems, meaning very specific and accurate diagnostic 
abilities. For example,  HealthSouth has a new machine that tests for carpal tunnel syndrome and 
can tell you before you get it whether or not you are developing symptoms, so your employer can 
pull you off the line and retrain you before you actually become a workman’s compensation case.
<p>
While this means enormous financial savings, there is a deeper meaning.  This particular 
machine is an expert system, designed by one of the two or three leading experts in carpal tunnel 
syndrome.  It actually is more accurate than a normal doctor, because a normal doctor does not deal 
with carpal tunnel syndrome.  You must have a fairly noticeable case before a normal doctor can 
find it while the machine finds it very early.
<p>
Yet even more fascinating is that no one runs the machine.  There is no fee.  You don’t 
pay a technician.  You don’t pay a nurse.  You don’t pay the doctor.  All you do is turn the machine 
on.  That is why there will be a 20 percent crash in the cost of health care in the first decade of the 
21st century.
<p>
The final change that will contribute to lower costs is the rise of customer driven health 
care markets. For example, my mother-in-law at 80 years of age checks her own blood count every 
day -- her own blood sugar -- and then varies her insulin based on what she teaches herself, based in 
her home laboratory.
<p>
Soon we may have more complete home diagnostic systems that, at very low cost, allow 
you to get up in the morning and if you don’t feel well you test yourself. You may then 
electronically send the data to your doctor, who looks at it and either says, "Stay in bed and eat 
chicken soup;"  "Go buy the following three things;"  or, "Come see me.  This might be serious."
<p>
This is a totally different model of care, based not on doctors or hospitals, but the 
consumer.  It’s not an improved version of the dying world.  It is the new world.
<p>
These five changes will drive a revolution for a healthier America. Yet at the same time 
they present great opportunities for America in the world marketplace.
<p>
We ought to see these advances as the greatest job opportunity of the 21st century, and say 
to everybody on the planet, "Show up here, give us your money, we’ll provide you health care, and 
then you get to sell us whatever it is you think you can manufacture." Maybe health ought to be 
moved out of the Department of Health and Human Services and into the Department of 
Commerce.  Health care will be a major source of foreign exchange earnings for the United States.
<p>
<h3>Stumbling Blocks</h3>
<p>
Yet to get there we must address several problems.  One is our anti-capital accumulation 
tax code. The tax code punishes people who leave companies and set up their own business.  It is 
not designed to deal with a rapid rate of innovation.
<p>
Another problem is that our litigation law is anti-entrepreneurial.  High tech corporate 
CEOs complain that if only the resources devoted to litigation expenses could be retasked to 
productive efforts, they would produce much in job creation.  But as it now stands, entrepreneurs 
face potentially enormous liability damages that inhibit investment in innovative technology.
<p>
A third problem is the Food and Drug Administration.  There’s a brand new report out that 
says in just the manufacture of health tools, the FDA will probably cost America 50,000 jobs in the 
next five years.
<p>
For instance, we currently have a law that says to medical manufacturers, “if Germany 
approves a device, but the FDA doesn’t approve of it for sale in the United States, you can only 
manufacture it if you build a factory outside the United States. This has got to be the dumbest 
single law on killing jobs we have. It needs to be repealed and if any sophisticated country in the 
world approves a particular product, you should be able to make it in the United States for export 
purposes.
<p>
We also need to rethink the structure of research and development. We should set a lot 
more goals.  The person who comes in with the first breakthrough in a certain area, give them a big 
reward, which was a terrific model to spur innovation up through the 1930s.
<p>
People tend to forget that most aviation progress in the 1920s and 30s was made in 
response to people who flew in order to win prizes.  It was not made by large, cumbersome, slow 
government bureaucracies, typically doing what they think is risk averse.
<p>
We should rethink our approaches in R&D and to find more aggressive ways to be more 
risk taking, and to focus on lowering the costs.  Under what circumstances can we empower the 
customer, lower the cost and use these breakthroughs to create dramatically better health care and 
better knowledge about health at lower cost.
<p>
For example, Medicare is actually slowing down the rate of innovation by refusing to pay 
for experimental tests.  I mean this is dumbest possible position if you are at the edge of a 
revolution in health care.  It is like saying, "Please don’t let us get there, it will lower the cost of 
everything."
<p>
I believe that if we would of had a Food and Drug Administration of the modern kind and 
a Medicare system of the modern kind, X-rays today would be as scarce as cat-scans, and no dentist 
in America would have one, because you can not make an argument that checking your teeth is a 
medical necessity.
<p>
Instead, because it was done in the free market and nobody figured out how to get the 
government to stop it, we think of x-rays as ubiquitous and routine. That’s a modest example of 
how much this current government raises the cost of health care, allows Americans to die 
unnecessarily, prolongs illness, and kills American jobs, all simultaneously.  A remarkable 
achievement, not matching that of the Soviet empire, but certainly in the same general zone.
<p>
I don’t say that as hyperbole. With the rise of expert systems, long distance electronics and 
computational power, there is no reason we can’t have a revolution in learning, in law and in health 
that will be truly dramatic.
<p>
<p>
<I>Newt Gingrich is Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives.  This is adapted from a speech given at PFF’s Medical Innovation Conference, June 15, 1995.</i>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
