<TD WIDTH=79><I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">41</FONT></I></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Despite the benefits of PMA privatization,
action remains blocked by special interests. This is yet another
example of how good intentions are simply not enough to move the
process in Washington. There are thousands of pages of reports
describing the benefits that privatization would bring to the
general taxpayers; there are hundreds of pages of reports showing
that any possible harms to various interest groups would be much
lower than the groups claim; yet, this blizzard of paper is not
going to move the privatization of PMA's forward. What is needed
is a plan that recognizes the interest group nature of the political
process; a plan that recognizes that current beneficiaries of
federal programs such as the PMA's will slow, and in some cases
stop altogether, privatization efforts; a plan that would create
the proper incentives for current beneficiaries to become champions
of privatization. Such a plan is focus of this report.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">PART 2</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">BLOCK-SHADEGG PRIVATIZATION
PROPOSAL<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Resolving the Interest Group Problem</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We propose to privatize the PMA's in a way
that will hurt neither the end users of PMA power nor the people
who enjoy the non-power benefits of the federal hydro projects.
In fact, our privatization plan overcomes traditional interest
group opposition by attempting to turn the end users of public
power and other beneficiaries of federal hydro programs from opponents
of any privatization into potential proponents. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In designing a program to privatize federal
hydroelectric assets, Congress can learn many lessons from the
recent privatization experiences of other countries. A good contrast
between a well-designed privatization plan with strong public
support (and strong support for the politicians who put it through)
and a plan that ignored the stakeholder aspects of privatization
and thus magnified the fear of privatization and slowed the process,
is provided by comparing the Czech and Hungarian privatization
experiences.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Czechs have led the world in privatizing
their economy. In 1990, only about 4 percent of their GDP was
privately produced. By 1995, 67 percent of GDP was privately produced.
The Czech privatization efforts were successful because, in part,
they relied on voucher privatization - a system in which each
citizen could purchase, for a little bit more than the average
weekly wage, vouchers that could be exchanged for shares of those
enterprises being privatized. The government then sold (or privatized)
its enterprises in a unique auction in which millions of people
were able to bid for thousands of corporations' shares and pay
for them with their vouchers. The share value citizens obtained
was on average substantial (a few months income). This mobilized
the self-interest of the Czech people and created very stable
political support both for privatization and the transition from
communism in general. The Czech privatization process was completed
in two separate waves. As the profits of the first wave became
evident to average citizens, they started to criticize the government,
not for privatizing too much, but for reserving too much property
for direct sales and not allowing the general public to bid on
more assets with their vouchers.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Hungarian government, on the other hand,
offers a cautionary tale for any would-be privatizer. Hungary
downplayed mass privatization and put a good deal of emphasis
on the budgetary and foreign capital inflow implications of privatization.
The government attempted to sell their enterprises to international
corporations or to the current managers and paid very little attention
to stakeholder politics. It was not uncommon for the Hungarian
government to sell an enterprise very cheaply to a group of managers,
who immediately resold it at a handsome profit. While there is
nothing economic inefficient with such transactions, the public
viewed them as unjust - a small group of the privileged benefited
most from privatization while the &quot;man on the street&quot;
was left only with assurance from economists and others that eventually
the efficiency gains  would trickle down. Abstractions apparently
do not sell very much better in Central Europe than in the United
States, and this privatization approach eventually led to a loss
of confidence in privatization. The initial program had to be
stopped and revised and the privatization process significantly
slowed down.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">While privatization would lead to a net increase
in the wealth of Central and Eastern European nations, not all
of these countries were able to make rapid progress in privatization.
Similarly even though the gains to the winners in PMA privatization
will exceed any losses, privatization still may not succeed. Those
who believe they might be losers due to a public policy change
may, if losses are sufficiently concentrated and benefits sufficiently
diffuse, stop a generally beneficial policy change. The lesson
from the formerly communist economies is that a creative privatization
program, such as that used by the Czechs, can make almost <I>everybody</I>
a winner and generate enough political support to accomplish the
privatization. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This is exactly what our privatization proposal
is all about. We have designed a plan that has the potential of
making everyone winners. All end users of PMA power who might
be hurt by rate increases will receive fully negotiable warrants
entitling them to a below market purchase of &quot;their&quot;
PMA stock, and thus to potential capital gains significant enough
to offset most, if not all, of any rate increase. In fact, since
private ownership is likely to increase efficiency, their potential
capital gains should actually outweigh the present discounted
value of any rate increase. The recipients of the non-power activities
of the hydro projects would be given shares of a river association
(having a corporate structure) that would own and manage the non-power
side of &quot;their&quot; projects. They will thus be the ones
deciding how to structure the provision of non-power activities.
 Since the arrangement we propose guarantees a sufficient flow
of revenue from the power source to the non-power river corporation,
all river users will also receive a valuable asset.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">A Warrant Approach to PMA
Privatization</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Conversion of PMA's into Government  Corporations</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Before proceeding to the core elements of our
proposal, we need to describe how to prepare the target PMA's
for sale. At present, the PMA's are simply federal agencies operating
within the Department of Energy. They keep accounting records
under government accounting methods and have no equity capital.
They do not finance their expenditures with their own internal
funds or through the capital market, but through annual appropriations
from Congress.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The first logical step on the way to privatization
is to turn these federal agencies into more standard corporations,
with shares that could be sold to private citizens. This is exactly
what Congress did when it privatized Conrail. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The federal government would establish a separate
corporation for each of the PMA's. Each PMA would incorporate
in a state within the region where it operates and have the same
powers as any other private corporation. These corporations would
have the authority to operate and maintain the generation and
transmission facilities and to market transmission services and
electricity. Each corporation would be directed by a Transition
Manager appointed by the President of the United States, who would
have the powers and duties of the Board of Directors until the
board is elected by the new owners. On a given date, each corporation
would issue capital stock to the Treasury and all funds, debts
and contracts of the PMA's and all facilities to be privatized
would be transferred from the federal agency to the new corporations.
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Distribution of Warrants</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The next step is the key step: The <I>ultimate</I>
consumers of PMA power - those who actually use PMA power distributed
by their co-ops or munies (or in some rare cases their IOU) to
light their homes and operate their businesses - would be given
warrants that would entitle them to purchase a fixed number of
shares in the PMA by a pre-set date at a price that we call &quot;strike
price.&quot; We propose that the strike price (which is treated
in much greater detail below) be set below the expected market
value of the shares. How many shares each particular consumer
will be able to buy with his warrants will be based on how much
power he bought from the PMA in the past (the specific time is
referred to as the reference time period).</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The concept is probably best communicated by
example: Suppose that the Wildcat Electric Cooperative purchased
power from WAPA that amounted to 10 percent of all the power produced
by the to-be-privatized WAPA facilities. Further assume that Ms.
Smith has a rather large house and during the reference year consumed
0.02 percent of power sold by Wildcat Electric Cooperative. Thus
Ms. Smith consumed 0.002 percent of power produced by WAPA facilities.
As a consequence, Ms. Smith will be given a warrant that entitles
her to buy 0.002 percent of WAPA shares at the strike price. If
WAPA Inc. issued 10 million shares, the warrant would entitle
Ms. Smith to purchase 200 of these shares at the strike price.
She could, of course, purchase as many warrants from other customers
as she wished and hence purchase as many shares of WAPA Inc. as
she thought desirable.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The warrants issued to end-users would be fully
negotiable; anyone will be allowed to buy or sell warrants at
any conditions agreeable to the contracting parties (i.e. buyer
and seller). The actual sale of PMA shares would take place on
a specified date to the individuals holding warrants on that day.
After that day, the warrants that were not redeemed for shares
would become void.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Translation of Warrants into Profits</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The most politically attractive feature of
our privatization proposal stems from the fact that the strike
price would be set below the expected market price. If, for example,
the market price of a share is $5 while the strike price is only
$3, Ms. Smith can make, by exercising her right to purchase 200
shares at the strike price of $3 and reselling them at market
for $5, a profit of $400. Estimates of potential profits for average
consumers as well as some analysis of these estimates are presented
in Part 3 below. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Of course since the warrants are fully negotiable,
Ms. Smith does not even have to risk her own money to earn a profit.
 Because the warrants entitle <I>anyone</I> holding them to purchase
stock at below the market price, they in themselves have value.
 Potential buyers of a PMA would be willing to pay up to the difference
between the market price of the stock and the strike price for
a warrant controlling a single share.  As we expect that the warrants
would sell for close to this difference, Ms. Smith's  warrant
would be worth $400--the difference between the market price and
the strike price, $2, multiplied by the number of shares it controls,
200.  So she can sell her warrant and earn just as much as if
she had purchased shares using the warrant and sold them at the
market price.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is likely that a majority of the original
warrant holders - households such as Ms. Smith's - would not actually
exercise their warrant entitlements to become shareholders of
their PMA. They may not be interested in being an owner of a PMA,
and the relatively small number of shares that their warrants
entitle them to purchase would not enable them to exercise any
appreciable control over the PMA's management. Instead, we expect
most warrant holders will simply sell their warrants, make a tidy
profit and never bother with actually buying shares and risking
their own capital in a privatized PMA.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Czech experience, while not an exact analogy,
provides instructive lessons on how our  Ms. Smith would respond
to privatization. The Czechs did not, as it turned out, actually
have to exchange their vouchers for shares of enterprises. Instead
they could entrust a part or all of their vouchers to one of a
number of investment funds (usually established by banks or other
investment corporations). It was the fund that bid for and eventually
obtained the shares of the enterprises being privatized. The people
who entrusted their vouchers to the fund became shareholders of
that fund. As it turned out, these investment funds actually saved
the entire privatization process. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">When the Czech privatization program began,
there were millions of people who did not understand the voucher
scheme, who had no experience with &quot;shares&quot; or &quot;capital
markets&quot; and who did not see any real value in the shares
they could potentially obtain. Even among those perceptive souls
who could see the value of the stock gained in exchange of vouchers,
there were doubts about whether anybody would buy their shares
(there was no stock exchange at that time). Early in the process
not many Czechs showed an interest in buying vouchers and participating
in the process. In fact, in the early stages the whole process
was deemed to be a political failure. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">But the profits were too enticing. The difference
between the voucher price (1,035 Czech Crowns or about $40) and
the expected market value of the shares an average citizen could
obtain (30,000 Crowns or almost $1200) created a <I>huge</I> profit
potential. Through a little marketing -  a charismatic leader
of an innovative Harvard Investment Fund appeared on the TV screens
declaring &quot;Whoever entrusts his vouchers to Harvard Fund
will get 10,350 Crowns in cash next year&quot; - Czechs quickly
became aware that they stood to make money and enthusiastically
joined the privatization effort. For our purpose, it is also worth
noting that other investment funds had little choice but to join
the race. They started bidding up the prices for vouchers, redistributing
the gains from privatization from the funds to the general public.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are a number of parallels between the
Czech experience and our PMA privatization proposal. We expect
that many people would not understand the uses of their warrants.
There may be people who fear that they will not be able to sell
their shares above the strike price. However, there is little
doubt that many utilities, investment bankers and other groups
are interested in gaining control over the PMA's generation and
transmission assets. These interested parties will make a market
in warrants.  In fact, they are likely to make a market at issue;
that is, as soon as the legislation is signed, bidding may start
for the right to buy warrants at the time of their issue. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The potential buyers of warrants will likely
advertise through newspapers and television or directly contact
recipients of warrants. The highest price that each prospective
warrant buyer will pay is equal to the difference between the
value they attach to the shares and the strike price. Competition
among various parties for warrants, and hence for control over
the PMA's, will force each potential bidder to bid as high a price
as they can. Each bidder will be forced by competition to bid
just short of how much the warrants are worth to them. This competition
between bidders will assure that the original warrant holders
(i.e., the current end users of PMA power) will reap much of the
gains from privatization. These gains are precisely the mechanism
that we think will turn current opponents of privatization into
proponents. It will not be rate increases, which are not likely
to be very significant anyway, that PMA's end users will be most
concerned about; instead, they will be concerned about how much
money they will get for their warrants, and will be checking their
newspapers  and their mail for the latest offer. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As the market for warrants develops, the prospective
buyers are likely to be quite inventive in their efforts to buy
warrants from the end users. It is likely that potential buyers
will make tender offers - public announcements that they are willing
to buy warrants from any original warrant holder at a specified
price - and communicate them to the warrant holders through the
media or mail. Some warrants, of course, will be purchased by
speculators who do not desire to gain control over PMA's but want
to resell the warrants. We are persuaded that Wall Street will
make a market in warrants and in short order the market will change
from a decentralized and spontaneous one to a centralized market;
a market that will concentrate supply and demand at one place;
a market that will eventually achieve an equilibrium price for
warrants and will move the warrants to those who value the ownership
of PMA's most highly. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The competition in bidding for warrants will
assure that the ultimate owners of PMA's are those who will be
able to operate them most efficiently. Those who can run PMA's
most efficiently will be able to outbid other potential buyers,
and the current end users will get most of the gains from reallocating
the PMA's to the most efficient owners. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The governmental involvement in the market
for warrants should be limited to making information about end-users'
warrant holdings easily available, so that the costs of contacting
them are minimal. Low costs of obtaining this information as well
as equal access to such information are important conditions for
maximizing the end users' gains. Publishing the list of end users,
together with the number of warrants they hold and their addresses
in the Federal Register will just do that.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Investors who worry that this plan will not
enable them to gain a controlling interest in the newly privatized
PMA's need not be concerned. Even if all of the warrants for the
PMA shares were in the hands of individual households, there is
no reason to believe that creatively structured tender offers
would not yield sufficient warrants to gain control of the PMA's.
As in the Czech experience - even more so because our capital
markets are so much more advanced - most households will avail
themselves of the opportunity to reap profits now by selling their
warrants rather than holding shares or selling them to their preference
suppliers at non-competitive prices.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">TABLE 3:  </FONT><FONT COLOR=#000000 FACE="Arial">DISTRIBUTION
OF WARRANTS AMONG ULTIMATE CUSTOMER CLASSES</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#000000 BORDER=1>
