</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">*End users purchasing power from investor-owned
utilities are not included in this table. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<img SRC="img00005.gif"><BR>
<P>
<img SRC="img00006.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><img SRC="img00007.gif"></CENTER>
<p>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">PART 4</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">EMPOWERING THE RIVER USERS</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is easy to say that the government should
privatize the PMA's, but it is not quite as easy to specify what
exactly should be sold. Selling the PMA's assets as they appear
on the PMA's financial statements would mean selling their transmission
facilities (or in case of SEPA, which does not own any transmission
assets, the government would be selling only rights to market
power). Under this scenario, the operation of dams and production
of electricity would still be provided by the Corps of Engineers
or Bureau of Reclamation. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Yet this is only one approach to PMA privatization.
The PMA sale also might include powerhouses, dams, locks, land
around the reservoirs - or even the water itself (provided that
ownership of water is not already defined by water rights). Each
option has a different impact on the management of both power
and non-power resources, on incentives of all the parties involved,
and on the revenue to the Treasury. Perhaps most significantly,
different options affect the gains to end users.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The more assets sold as part of the PMA will
not always translate into greater PMA market value. Before any
privatization plan proceeds, the federal government must decide
not only what physical assets to sell, but also the rights, responsibilities,
restrictions and contractual arrangements tied to these assets.
In other words, the government must define a split between power
and non-power activities and an institutional mechanism that will
shape the relationship between them. Generally speaking, we suggest
that the government should make such a split and create such an
institutional mechanism that will maximize the value of the warrants
subject to satisfying the interests of the users of non-power
activities.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Outlined below is an attempt to find such an
option. First, we look at some &quot;traditional&quot; suggestions
for deciding what parts of the federal hydro projects should be
privatized and how to address the problem of provisioning non-power
benefits of these projects. Then we describe our own proposal
(the river association approach), which we believe would lead
to a more efficient use of the nation's water resources. Most
importantly, just as warrants make privatization interesting to
the end users of PMA power, we believe that our proposal would
turn the current beneficiaries of the non-power activities (who
so far oppose any privatization efforts) from privatization opponents
to advocates. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">The &quot;Traditional&quot;
Privatization Options </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Sell It All</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">From an administrative perspective, the most
straightforward approach to the privatization problem is to sell
everything that PMA's and the Corps/Bureau own - power marketing
rights, transmission facilities, power houses, dams, water locks
and the land surrounding the reservoirs, including beaches. If
this option were chosen, the easiest way to deal with the multiple
use aspect of the original water projects would be to make the
privatized dams subject to FERC licensing rules (this is the approach
currently used where IOU's own hydro projects). </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are at least four problems with such
an approach.:</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">License Costs.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
FERC licensing (and subsequent relicensing) is a complicated,
costly and uncertain procedure that lasts several years. The utility
seeking the license; interest groups; environmental groups; state
and federal agencies with jurisdiction over issues like fish and
wildlife, navigation or irrigation; and the FERC itself all spend
substantial resources on an administrative process that aims to
balance the competing demands on water resources. Utilities must
submit license applications that include often unnecessary studies
on the economic, engineering, environmental and safety features
of the project, many of which probably would not otherwise be
prepared. Moreover, the licensing process itself probably introduces
unnecessary uncertainty into the hydro business. As a result,
including dams subject to FERC licensing in any privatization
will frustrate the buyers and reduce the price they are willing
to pay. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Environmental Regulations. </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">Environmental
regulations imposed on the project licensee (such as fish ladders
or minimum spillage requirements) also impose significant costs.
While the licensee may try to seek recovery of these costs through
higher rates, this will become difficult in increasingly competitive
electricity markets Environmental regulations will almost certainly
lower the licensee's expected profits; thus including the dams
in privatization, if they are subject to these burdens, will lower
the PMA's value and end-user gains.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We are not proposing that environmental requirements
be abolished or environmental benefits necessarily be reduced.
Yet we do think that the government should realize that privatizing
the dams may put the dam owner (and/or the power consumers) in
the position of paying all of the costs for regulations that they
have very little say in establishing. Such a disconnect between
regulation writing and cost bearing is likely to result in inappropriate
standards. As a result, the &quot;sell it all&quot; approach may
actually result in excessive environmental standards and reduced
PMA values - and thus lower proceeds to the Treasury than from
a more limited privatization. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Locks.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> Many
dams in the Southern United States have locks that enable boats
to travel up or downstream past the dam. A number of utility representatives
have expressed the opinion that they would rather avoid having
responsibility for the locks. Their aversion seems to stem from
the sense that operating locks would result in a potential public
relations problem since waterways are commonly perceived as a
public resource.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The problem arises because each opening of
a lock causes a visible loss of power output due both to spillage
of water that could otherwise flow through a turbine to generate
power and to a back-up pressure that the water flowing from the
lock puts on the turbine. Currently, since navigation is one of
the purposes of federal water projects, the Corps or Bureau simply
open the locks to any boat that wants to pass the dam. This may
cause inefficient losses in power output. An unrestricted, profit-maximizing
private owner of such a hydro project would have motivation to
reduce such a loss by tolling boats $250 for each passage or at
least by introducing a reasonable opening timetable. Assuming
that the private owner is not in a position to exploit a monopoly,
the toll solution actually leads to more efficient allocation
of resources. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A utility that purchased the dam may be restricted
from acting as a profit maximizer by its FERC license, which could
request it to open the lock for everybody wishing passage. In
this case the utility would bear all the costs of uneconomic lock
openings and would thus bid less for the PMA's. However, even
if private buyers are not restricted in what they could do with
the locks, it is not assured that the efficient outcome (achieved
by pricing and/or an optimal opening timetable) would occur. Waterways
are perceived to be a public resource, and any effort by the utility
to deny free access through the dam would probably create enormous
 public opposition. Having a good public image and demonstrating
concern for the non-power aspects of the water project may be
an important part of corporate strategy with long-run and favorable
profit implications. Having full responsibility for locks in a
dam might place the utility that bought the PMA between Scylla
of lost power output and Charybdis of bad public relations - a
dilemma that potential buyers of a PMA are willing to pay to avoid.
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Recreation.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
A similar problem may be raised around recreation facilities (i.e.,
using reservoirs for boating). Again, the Corps currently does
not charge anything close to market value for their use. If the
power producer only bears the maintenance costs and provides free
recreation, it loses money. If the power producer tries to charge
for this service, it loses its public goodwill. Recreational facilities
do not enhance the market value of the PMA's and may reduce that
value.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Lease It All</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">While privatization, by definition, involves
creating actual ownership over assets, another possibility is
for the federal government to lease dams and powerhouses to a
newly privatized PMA. This is actually the way the Argentinean
government privatized its Alicura Hydroelectric Project on the
Limay River. The state-owned enterprise operating the project
(Hidroelectrica Alicura S.A.) was privatized, but the government
retained ownership of the dams and powerhouses and gave concession
to Hidroelectrica Alicura to use these facilities for 30 years.
The concession contract specified the rights and obligation of
the power producer in a way similar to FERC license and established
a monthly payment schedule the power producer pays the government
for use of the facilities. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Although such an approach may be less controversial
than sale of the dams to the private parties, and is definitely
better than if the federal government remained both the owner
and operator of the projects, we do not advise it. First, it is
not free of the problems discussed in the &quot;Sell It All&quot;
section. Second, it adds a new problem: An inherent feature of
any long-term lease is the disincentive on the part of the lessee
to undertake desirable investment and capital maintenance actions
at the end of the lease period, because the benefits of such investments
and maintenance cannot be fully realized after expiration of the
lease. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Sell Only the Power Resources and Let the
Federal Government </FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Continue to Operate the Dams</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another approach to privatizing PMA's is to
sell the powerhouses and all other power resources through a warrant
offering, and let the federal government (in most cases represented
by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the Bureau of Reclamation)
retain ownership and control of the dam and responsibility for
the non-power activities of the water project. Currently there
are a small number of hydro projects in the U.S. operating under
this structure. For example, the Holt and Bankhead water resource
projects on the Black Warrior River in Alabama were originally
built for navigational purposes. During their enlargement in the
1960's by the Army Corps of Engineers, the Alabama Power Company
installed a powerhouse under FERC's (actually Federal Power Commission
at that time) license. This historical accident created a structure
where the investor-owned utility (Alabama Power) owns, operates
and maintains all facilities directly used for power generation,
while the Corps owns, operates and maintains the dam structures,
locks and recreation facilities. The Corps has responsibility
for managing the water flows and coordinating this activity with
the Alabama Power Co. The two entities exchange information necessary
for the smooth operation. The license anticipates that construction
and improvement of fish and wildlife facilities or recreation
facilities may be provided either by Alabama Power Co. (under
FERC's supervision) or by the U.S. Corps of Engineers. In the
latter case, the Alabama Power Co. is required to provide (without
charge) its land and other property needed for such construction
or improvement. Alabama Power is also required under the operating
agreement to supply free power for the operation and maintenance
of the lock and, most significantly, to pay the Corps of Engineers
an annual fee determined by the FERC. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are some advantages to the Holt/Bankhead
solution. First, although the entirely private aspects of these
projects are subject to FERC licensing procedures, the Corps'
activities are not. This structure, at a minimum, saves both ratepayers
and taxpayers money in the form of reduced administrative expenses,
and may actually reduce the regulatory burden by having the government
internalize the costs of the non-market benefits of the dam. A
private power company could produce these non-power benefits (e.g.
recreation facilities, flood control) but given the politically
sensitive nature of these benefits, it is probably less costly
to have the political entity do so. At least in this case, the
government internalizes the costs of regulating these benefits.
If a private firm produces the non-power benefits under a regulatory
scheme, the costs of this regulation are exported to the power
company and eventually to its customers. Such a scheme for operating
the dam might actually lead to higher overall costs of running
the dam.  Second, if the government runs the dam, it relieves
the electricity producer from responsibilities that are in conflict
with power production and that might cause conflicts with the
public (e.g. navigation). Having a politically responsible entity
operate the dam may reduce the costs of these conflicts. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The structure of a Holt/Bankhead type relationship
is crucial for efficient operation of hydro projects as well as
for the price that the potential buyers of the PMA's would be
willing to pay to the warrant holders. Most relevant to the value
of the powerhouse are the arrangements for financing dam operations,
of which a number of approaches exist.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Taxes.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> Theoretically,
one could make the argument that government's dam operations and
production of non-power activities of the water projects are collectively
consumed (or public) goods and should be financed from government's
general revenue. Whatever the merits of this theoretical argument,
we can put this solution aside because it is politically infeasible
to sell the profitable or revenue producing part of these projects
and leave the government with the obligation to fund the dam's
operations. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Fixed Fee.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
One possible alternative is to use the current Holt/Bankhead arrangement
and have the power resource owner pay the federal government a
fixed fee, set at a level sufficient to cover at least the current
costs of operating and maintaining the non-power functions of
a project. Under this plan, the power producers would have the
same costs as they would if they owned the reservoir and provided
the non-power functions directly, at least during the initial
period. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">From the government's perspective, setting
the fixed fee at the current level of operational expenses (including
depreciation and indexed for increases in costs of living) will
enable the federal government to collect sufficient revenue to
produce the same amount of non-power activities as it produces
now. Moreover, this structure should provide some incentive for
dam management to control the growth of expenses. We are presuming
that the officials who manage the dam resources would find having
additional funds appropriated to supplement their power fees unlikely.
To make this cost-reducing incentive effective, the Corps of Engineers
or the Bureau of Reclamation should be financed in a way that
these agencies do not deposit their receipts in the Treasury and
then ask for congressional appropriation, but rather are self-financed,
and are allowed to keep their revenues in a way that, say, BPA
can. (Such a change would be desirable even while the PMA's are
awaiting privatization.)</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">From the non-power users' perspective, under
this proposal the federal government would have enough resources
to provide the same level of &quot;their&quot; benefits, and we
do not think that there is a reason why the federal government
would restrict the production of these benefits. Hence, the non-power
users are not made any worse-off under this proposal. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">However, the fixed fee approach has a drawback:
It does not provide any incentives to the dam operating agency
to economize on water usage or for optimal intertemporal water
allocation. Water spillage is not free nor is the value of water
to the power generator constant over time; water is much more
valuable in summer (the period of peak seasonal electricity demand)
and during working hours (the period of peak daily electricity
demand). A fixed fee that does not depend on magnitude and timing
of water flows ignores both the value of water as well as the
fluctuations of this value over time. It does not give the dam
operator any incentive to make efficient decisions about magnitude
and timing of spillage and lock openings. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Flow Charge.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
One approach to financing dam operations that would tend to optimize
the magnitude and timing of water flows (i.e., would help structure
the decisions on competing uses of water for energy production,
navigation, irrigation and spillage) is to have the power producer
pay a flow charge. The power house owner would pay a certain amount
of money per unit of water flowing through the turbine. The initial
flow charges, and they could be either flat rate or time dependent,
would be set so that at current flows the federal government could
recover its cost of dam operation. We realize that the governmental
agencies that would run dams such as the Corps or Bureau of Reclamation
are not-for-profit entities; however, we believe that they, at
least to some extent, care about the revenue they may generate
from their activities if only because it reduces their need to
seek appropriated funds. A revenue stream that increases with
the amount of water flowing through the turbine may make the Corps
or the Bureau consider more carefully the way it manages water
flows. The flow charge system builds in an opportunity cost for
each lock opening or spillage or irrigation discharge. It does
so because the Corps or the Bureau could, instead of any of these
activities, let this water flow through the turbine and generate
additional revenue. A flow charge might, for example, dissuade
the agency operating the dam from providing virtually unlimited
lock services and induce it to preschedule the lock openings or
group boats together. The latter would reduce the total spillage
through the locks, increase flow through turbine, and generate
greater revenue for the dam operator. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">If the flow charge also varied with time of
year and, possibly, time of day, the charge would serve as a tool
for resolving intertemporal water use problems. Water is more
valuable to power producers during peak periods and they are willing
to pay higher flow charges during those periods. From that perspective
the government agency that operates the dam would be motivated
to manage water flows more prudently and to conserve water flow
for periods when it is a more valuable resource. The dam operator
would be encouraged by the time-dependent flow charge to try to
schedule most of the lock openings for early mornings and late
afternoons, and to do whatever it could do to maximize the summer
turbine flows.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">One approach to setting flow charges would
be to use the historical costs of operating the dam as well as
the historical flows through the turbine, and then to set the
flow charge such that if the current volume and timing of flows
were maintained, the yearly sum of the flow charges would just
equal the costs of operating the dam. If there are sources of
revenue other than power (water supply, marina leases), these
revenues should be subtracted from the operating costs so that
the addition of flow charges and non-power revenues would just
equal the costs operating the dam.  From the power producer's
perspective, this means that he would pay the same amount of flow
charges as he would in other solutions so that the flow charge
would not reduce the PMA's value to potential buyers. However,
flow charges do give power producers additional value, represented
by an institutional arrangement that makes the government agency
more likely to provide sufficient water to the turbine and at
times when it is most valuable. From the government's perspective,
setting the flow charge in this manner assumes that the operating
agency has sufficient revenue to run the dam and provide the same
level of non-power activities as in the past. The agency, however,
has the potential to increase its revenues and use this money
for other public purposes such as improving recreational sites.
From the non-power users' perspective, the size of some of their
benefits may actually increase. Of course, some non-power users
may be adversely affected by possible reallocations of water flows,
but these affects are most likely to take the form of changes
in the timing of their consumption rather than changes in the
amount of consumption. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Disadvantages of a Holt/ Bankhead Arrangement</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A Holt/Bankhead type of ownership structure
involving private ownership of the powerhouse and government ownership
of the dam resolves many problem associated with total government
or total private ownership of water resource projects and, because
of its neutral distributional consequences, appears to be politically
acceptable. However, there are several objections against this
solution which leads us not to recommend its use. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Lack of Economic Incentives Due to federal
Ownership.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> The first objection to
a Holt/Bankhead approach is straightforward. A substantial amount
of water resource activities (i.e. non-power benefits) would still
be provided by a governmental agency. Even though the governmental
agencies are concerned about expenditures and revenues, we do
not believe that the federal ownership would provide sufficient
interest in minimizing costs and trying to optimize water flows
in order to maximize revenues from flow charges. As it would be
very hard to adopt an alternative flow charge concept that would
not guarantee revenue high enough to cover historical costs under
historical flows, it is likely that the dam operating agency would
be satisfied with keeping status quo and might not attempt to
cut costs or optimize water flows. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Lack of Discipline Due to Monopoly Position.
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">The federal ownership of all dams
supporting power generation of privatized PMA's places the federal
government in a purely monopolistic position that negatively affects
economic efficiency in two ways.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">First, the federal government would be in a
position to take advantage of setting flow charges at a level
exceeding the competitive level. The relationship between the
power resource owner and the dam owner is a typical case of a
bilateral monopoly, but the market power of a dam owner is somewhat
constrained if there are more dams with different owners. If there
are more dams with different owners, the power producer will give
preference in dispatching to the powerhouses located in the dams
that charge lower flow charges (other things remaining equal),
and a dam owner attempting to charge excessive flow charge will
actually lose revenues from the powerhouse. Such a constraint
is lacking if a single federal agency owns all of the dams. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Second, if one entity owns all the dams in
a region, it will have an adverse effect on the dam owner's incentives
to minimize costs. Since a fixed fee or flow charge, paid by the
power producer, is likely to be based on the cost to provide traditional
non-power benefits, and since the government would somehow regulate
that price, the agency operating the dam would be always guaranteed
sufficient revenues. This gives the agency a very weak incentive
to operate efficiently. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Separation of Costs and Benefits.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
The separation of the costs and benefits of the non-power activities
is also a problem in the split ownership regime. Under the Holt/Bankhead
type arrangement, most of the costs of non-power activities are
unilaterally passed on to power producers and hence (if the market
for electricity becomes sufficiently competitive) on to power
consumers. While, as a starting point, having power consumers
pay all of the costs may make this a politically feasible way
to privatize the PMA's, it also causes certain long-run problems.
Particularly, there is nothing to induce the non-power users to
pay attention to how much their benefits cost and nothing to induce
them to adjust their demand for these benefits according to their
costs. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Currently the non-power users reveal their
preferences though the political process, either by participation
in a FERC licensing procedures or, in case of public ownership,
by attempting to persuade the public authority that operates the
dam to provide &quot;their&quot; benefits. Unless there is some
sort of realistic charge for the non-power activities, users will
demand the highest possible amount of these activities because
they will not have to bear any significant costs for their actions.
These costs are then borne by power producers, who, in turn, use
the political process to limit the levels of non-power activities.
The outcome is what usually appears to be a reasonable compromise,
but it is a compromise based on balancing political pressures
instead of balancing costs and benefits of each non-power activity.
This undoubtedly leads to underconsumption of some activities
and overconsumption of others. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Political Irrelevance.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
The last objection to using a Holt/Bankhead arrangement in privatization
is that it does little to make the users of non-power activities
interested in and advocates for privatization. Their strong opposition
against  privatization efforts in the past suggests that they
might be so concerned about &quot;their&quot; benefits that even
a Holt/Bankhead arrangement would be perceived as too risky. If
they are satisfied with the status quo, why should they like any
change (even if the change is unlikely to make them worse off)
if that change does not make them explicitly better off? To build
the necessary political support to privatize the federal hydro
program and reap all the benefits from private ownership, we need
to mobilize the support of non-power users. Just as the warrant
concept turns the end users of PMA power into privatization supporters,
we believe that a river association approach for privatization
of federal dams presented below could have a similar impact on
non-power users. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">The River Association Approach
to</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Privatization of Federal
Hydro Projects </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Stakeholders other than power consumers - environmentalists,
fishermen, sporting associations - were among the strongest opponents
to last year's privatization proposals. They feared that private
ownership of water resource facilities would not lead to a sufficient
supply of &quot;their&quot; benefits (e.g. wildlife protection,
fishing, water sports, flood control, etc.). Under the current
state of affairs, these stakeholders either rely on the &quot;reasonable&quot;
behavior of the public agency that operates the dam or try to
assure provision of &quot;their&quot; benefits through political
influence. Privatizing through a private/public partnership, in
which the private owner owns only the power resources and the
public agency controls the dam and the non-power water project
activities, leaves these stakeholders in much the same situation
as they are today. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Absent any compelling advantage resulting from
a private/public partnership model, weaknesses of such an arrangement
are the inefficiency of the government agency that provides the
non-power benefits, the separation of costs and benefits of the
non-power activities, and the fact that the benefits themselves
are often not exactly what the non-power stakeholders actually
would like.</FONT>
P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">One simple way to improve on the Holt/Bankhead
privatization model is to directly involve the non-power stakeholders
in the management of the dam. This can be done by transferring
the dams to an association of stakeholders: farmers who need water
to irrigate their fields, second home owners who want the reservoir
to provide the amenities they were seeking when they purchased
their property, the power producer who needs the dam water to
generate power, water consumers who want the dam to provide sufficient
supply of water, resort owners along the beach who want the dam
to be attractive for the general public, and perhaps some other
stakeholders whose &quot;rights&quot; to the dam are not tied
to the land (environmentalists who want wildlife habitat preserved,
fishing associations who want to have sufficient number of fish
in the reservoir and down stream, barge companies that want to
have the lock open any time they need it, rafting companies who
want to have enough downstream water, surfers' associations who
want to have enough upstream water). As explained in greater detail
below, we believe one association should be formed for one river,
and that that association should own all of the existing federal
hydro non-power assets on that river (hence the name &quot;river
association&quot;). The association would own everything that
the federal government now owns (except the power resources) and
would make decisions about, and bear responsibility for, dam maintenance
and water management. In most cases this association would be
composed of local stakeholders so that local organizations are
the ones deciding local, or at least regional, issues. Financing
of dam maintenance and non-power activities would be provided
by revenues from the power producer, like in the Holt/Bankhead
type of arrangement (either by an annual fixed fee or, in the
best case, by a flow charge), and other possible sources (e.g.
water supply).</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Incorporating the River Association</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The general purpose of the association would
be to provide the desired benefits to its members, thus it might
seem appropriate that its structure be co-operative or non-profit.
However, there are strong reasons to favor a more traditional
corporate structure. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Establishment of River Corporations.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
For each river, on which the federal government owns and operates
a SEPA, SWPA or WAPA hydro project, the federal government would
establish a corporation (e.g. the Arkansas River Corporation).
The federal government would transfer all its property in these
hydro projects (except for the facilities directly used for generation
and transmission of electricity) to these corporations. Contracts
with current employees of the Corps of Engineers or Bureau of
Reclamation (those who perform activities not associated with
power production), liabilities and responsibility for managing
the water flows would also be transferred to the corporations.
The government would then issue shares of each corporation, the
nominal value of which would be equal to the accounting value
of the property transferred to the river corporations.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Distribution of Shares.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
The following step has a number of parallels with our warrant
proposal.<I> The federal government would distribute (without
charge) the shares of the river corporations to the non-power
stakeholders </I>according to a procedure defined in the statute.
The current users of non-power activities would thus become owners
of &quot;their&quot; dams, and would thus have direct control
over the distribution of &quot;their&quot; benefits. Since the
river corporation would have a guaranteed stream of revenue from
the power producer (i.e., the privatized PMA), the non-power users
would not only be given the responsibility for water resources,
but also a potentially valuable asset.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Advantages of the Corporate River Association
Approach</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Cost Minimization.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
The river association would have an obvious incentive to minimize
the costs of operating the dams and producing the non-power activities.
Such an incentive would be present even if the association were
a co-op or a non-profit, but the corporate structure makes this
incentive much stronger because any cost savings can be distributed
among shareholders (non-power users) as dividends. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">How the fixed fees or flow charges are structured
will have a powerful impact on incentives. If the fixed fee or
flow charge is set to cover exactly the expected costs of dam
operation, (i.e., some form of rate of return regulation as traditionally
applied to electricity rates), the cost minimizing incentive for
the river association would be much weaker. Thus we propose that
the fee or charge originally should be set at the level of historical
costs as incurred by the Corps or Bureau in the period just before
transfer, and then indexed to the consumer price index or some
other benchmark. Such an approach is not without problems, but
its cost minimizing incentives and its predictability both to
power producer and dam operator make it attractive. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Budget Impact.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
Although it seems that by giving away shares to the dam the federal
government receives no compensation, this is not the case. While
the government would be relieved of some of its assets, this privatization
structure will not have a negative impact on federal finances.
Giving the dams and their obligations away will not reduce the
proceeds from privatizing the PMA's. The price at which the PMA's
are going to be sold to the warrant holders is fixed at the strike
price, and the revenues that the government is going to generate
by auctioning off the shares it obtains by federal warrant entitlements
is determined by other factors, such as the level of the fixed
fee or flow charge. It does not matter to investors whether these
fees or charges are paid to the operating agency or a river association.
What matters is the level of the fees and the likely performance
of the dam operator. Because the fees or flow charges would be
set at the same level regardless of whether the federal government
or the river association owns the dam, and operating the dams
is not intended to be a profitable activity, the federal budget
will not suffer if a river association operates the dams. In fact,
it might even get some revenue if this ownership pattern is likely
to result in better run dams. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Reconnecting the Costs and Benefits.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
Under the river association plan, the non-power stakeholders will
not be concerned about whether the new owners of the dam are hostile
to their interests - for they will be the owners. They will determine
how much of &quot;their&quot; benefits should actually be produced.
No longer would bureaucrats living thousands miles away decide
how much of the non-power activities should be produced and how
to resolve the disputes of competing demands on water resources,
but the people who live near the dam and who actually use the
dam and benefit from it will. The people who have competing interests
in the dam would no longer lobby the government to promote their
particular interest. Instead, they will simply sit together around
a table and find a solution among themselves. There seems to be
a political tendency to devolve many environmental regulations
from the centralized government to the level at which the environmental
problems are best solved - at the local and regional level; the
river association concept is a good example of applying this tendency
to a specific issue. The river association concept also presents
the type of local self-government that has historically characterized
American democracy.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">From an economic perspective, the corporate
river association approach may eventually lead to a more efficient
allocation of resources. The non-power users who now become hydro
project owners will have reason to think about how much the benefits
they are enjoying are really worth. If they decide to cut expenses
on a particular activity, they can take the savings in higher
dividends. It is possible that in some cases people will prefer
cash to their non-power benefits. On the other hand, if dam management
decides to spend more on a particular activity, their dividends
will be lower; and it is possible that in some situations people
will prefer less cash in exchange for more non-power benefits.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">For example, the river association members
may decide to built a fish ladder in order to protect fish. However,
such an environmental benefit is not free, and the river association
members will bear the costs in terms of lower, perhaps zero, dividends.
The point is that before they were given control of the dam operations,
they had no title to dividends and less fish. Building a fish
ladder makes the association members better off, and they decided
to do so with full realization of costs of their activity, materialized
in lower dividends. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This is exactly what we mean by reconnecting
the costs and benefits. Having dividends from dam operations depend
on the level of non-power production builds-in a feedback between
the costs (in terms of opportunity costs) and benefits, without
making any of the non-power stakeholders worse off - no stakeholders
will have to pay any out-of-pocket costs in order to keep their
initial level of benefits, and the stakeholders may always have
the option of keeping the status quo in terms of the level of
non-power activities. While doing this would result in zero dividends,
what is important is that stakeholders have the information about
how much they are sacrificing by having their dividends unchanged.
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Political Impact.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
We think that the river association approach might change the
political dynamics of PMA privatization in a way similar to the
impact of warrants. Instead of trying to persuade the non-power
stakeholders that privatization is not harmful to their interests
(which has not proven to be a very effective strategy), we propose
to empower them to pursue those interests. We believe that for
most non-power stakeholders the possibility of co-owning a dam
and deciding on its future is much more attractive than the current
arrangement in which they need to rely on political influence
and/or some sympathetic bureaucrat. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The river association plan goes farther than
giving the people who use the dam a voice in its operations; it
also gives them a monetary stake in its management. When the non-power
users learn about the possibility of owning the dam, influencing
its operations and benefiting from any improvements in its management,
we believe they will see new advantages of privatization. We anticipate
that the non-power stakeholders will refrain from opposing privatization
efforts and instead many become its promoters. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Controversial Issues in the Corporate River
Association Approach</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are a very large number of options for
structuring the river association, each with a different efficiency
as well as distributional implication. Several issues must be
resolved before an association is formed, the property transferred
to it, and shares distributed to the non-power stakeholders. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Size.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> It is
possible to have a separate association for each reservoir, one
association for all reservoirs on a single river or a river system,
or, at the extreme, one association that includes all federal
hydro projects in a single PMA's marketing area. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">For a number of reasons, the one river one
association seems to be most desirable. While associations tied
to a single reservoir would have the advantage of creating strong
personal ties between the members and the association, in some
cases they may be unstable because they would be too small. They
may also be too small to internalize many of the effects of the
project and potentially could, by seeking only their own interests,
harm associations located downstream. As for &quot;supersize&quot;
association comprising the entire PMA area, we have serious doubts
that it would be able to operate effectively. The ownership of
such an association would be very dispersed and, as a consequence,
individual stakeholders would not have strong enough incentives
to participate actively in the management of the dam. A mega-association
would also put together stakeholders who actually have neither
common interests nor common conflicts - stakeholders benefiting
from, say, the Clair Engle Lake on the Trinity River in Northern
California have little in common with the people benefiting from
the Hoover Dam. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">On the other hand, an association that contains
all of the non-power resources along a single river has an inherently
logical basis. This option puts together groups of people who
share a common resource (one river) in which actions of one group
of stakeholders may influence the well being of other group of
stakeholders in the association. For example, by including as
participants of a single association all farmers taking water
for irrigation from various locations along  a river, this structure
would effectively prevent the upstream farmers from &quot;exploiting&quot;
the downstream farmers by opportunistically over-consuming water.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Even though having one association for one
river seems to be the most appropriate general approach, there
may be specific dams, rivers and watersheds for which a different
structure may be more suitable. It would not be reasonable to
insist on &quot;one-size-fits-all&quot; solution; instead, we
encourage that the spread of river associations should realize
the regional problems and interests.  </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Who should get the shares?</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
This is obviously one of the most important and most controversial
questions concerning the structure of a river association. Excluding
some non-power users hurts these users in two ways: First, they
are deprived of the chance of receiving dividends from the association
and, second, they might lose some of the benefits they currently
enjoy by not having a direct say in reservoir management. On the
other hand, including too many users may lead to too widely dispersed
ownership and risk that the stakeholders will not be interested
in active participation because their individual influence would
be too small. It might also lead to the inclusion of stakeholders
with too limited an interest in the specific water resource. This
is particularly the case of some environmental groups whose interests
are not tied to land and resource ownership along the river and
whose focus is national environmental policy. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A group whose &quot;rights&quot; to shares
seem to be obvious are people whose interest in the dams is somehow
tied to the ownership of the land or to the consumption of water.
The link between the dam and people's well being is strongest
in the case of farmers, who enjoy irrigation, and residents, who
benefit from water supply and flood control. Any change in the
water supply may have a dramatic impact on their incomes, well
being and/or safety. For other landowners, such as resort and
vacation home owners, worsening the recreational qualities of
the reservoir may have an impact on their incomes and on the value
of their real estate property. Tying the eligibility for shares
to the land ownership has an advantage of providing a transparent
rule for distribution of shares: In proportion to the land, with
a possible ceiling that would protect smaller owners.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Although land ownership and water consumption
may appear to be two different things, they should not be separated
when talking about ownership of the river association. This is
obvious in the West, where water distribution is very often determined
by water rights, and the water rights are part of the title to
the land, whereas farming or urban (it should be emphasized that
privatization of the dams must leave the current water rights
intact). Then the only difference between assigning shares in
proportion to land holdings or water holdings is that using land
as a determinant enables including those landowners who have a
stake in the dam but do not hold water rights. This principle
can also be used for areas where water rights are not established,
simply looking at water consumption <I>as if</I> it was based
on water rights. Urban water users probably require special treatment.
It would not make much sense to disperse the ownership of the
river association among thousands of urban households who own
very small pieces of land relative to farmers. What would make
more sense is to have the local municipal or investor-owned water
company represent the interest of urban water users in the river
association, using the area they supply as a measure of  their
stake, again with a possible ceiling to protect individual farmers
or vacation home owners. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are other stakeholders whose incomes
and well being are directly tied to the water project, but are
not related to land ownership. Incomes of barge companies depend
on such factors as the amount of water in the river and the reservoir,
as well as the operation of locks (opening frequency, tolls).
But since those interests do not depend on land ownership, their
stake is much harder to measure. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">And the existence of more or less intrinsic
benefits of hydro projects complicates this problem even further.
Fishing or kayaking associations do have an interest in the dam,
but it is an interest that is harder to define in terms of eligibility
for shares and very difficult to measure in relation to the interests
of land owners. However, excluding such associations may have
negative environmental impacts; for example, fishing associations
may play a very positive role in protecting fish and habitat.
Finally, on top of this &quot;subjective value pyramid&quot; are
the environmental organizations who do not derive any direct benefits
at all but who want to preserve fauna and flora and may even be
willing to pay for it. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are some solutions for allocating interest
in the dam. For example, the government might assign the bulk
of the shares (say 80 percent) to the power company, land owners
and water users (distributed by size of holdings) and then undertake
investigations on who would be assigned the remaining interest.
The eligibility of these other claimants would need to be proven
by, say, evidence that a particular barge company uses the river,
that members of a particular fishing association actually fish
in a given dam or that a particular environmental organization
did participate in licensing hearings or made a similar effort
indicating their concern in the past. While the final decision
will to some extent be arbitrary, we think that it should be made
by an administrative body on a case by case basis. Not only would
attempts to solve this at a legislative level result in lengthy
congressional hearings slowing down the formation of river associations
(while administrative body may at the time of investigating the
eligibility for shares also work on other details) but they could
also lead to a unified ownership structure for all projects, which
would probably disregard fairly significant regional differences.
The role of Congress in this issue should be limited to defining
the procedure for assigning shares. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another possibility might be to allocate some
shares to the power company and then auction off the remaining
shares. This would lead to a distribution of ownership that would
reflect the real values attached to the dam by various parties.
This system, however, eliminates the positive political impact
of free shares and may even foster opposition from those who have
interest but would not be entitled to free shares. Auctioning
the shares, while theoretically appealing, is a political non-starter</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Participation of the Power Producer.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
There is little doubt that the power producer is the most important
single stakeholder in decisions about the dam. It is probably
the party with the most resources at stake. A reservoir that is
safely and reliably managed is the key to the power producer's
success at any hydroelectric project. The company that owns the
power resources will not only want to influence decisions about
dam operations and maintenance, but it is also willing to bear
significant costs incurred in these operations. The importance
of dam operations, as well as the willingness of firms to contribute
to funding such operations, is best illustrated by those water
projects that are purely private. In these cases, the power companies
bear <I>all</I> costs and the projects are still profitable.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Excluding the power producer (i.e., the privatized
PMA) from participation in river associations is possible but
may not be the best solution. Including the power producer in
the river association might make co-ordination of activities better
and lead to greater operating efficiency. However, including the
power producer in proportion to their stake might, under a simple
majority rule, lead to the power producer always having a majority
- which could in some cases harm non-power stakeholders. It is
important to include the power producer in the association in
a way that is beneficial both to the power producer and to non-power
users. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Giving free shares in the dam to the power
producer is something that might encounter fierce opposition.
What instead might be acceptable to both parties is raising the
capital for the association by selling preferred shares to the
power producer. The amount of shares would not be too great, so
as to protect the non-power users. The power producer would get
more direct influence over key decisions, and the association
would get a start-up cash endowment, part of which might be used
as a reserve fund. This cash, however, also may be used to provide
the non-power users with some additional benefits. Whatever decision
the shareholders choose, increasing the capital by the power producer
increases the value of shares to the non-power stakeholders. Another
advantage of raising the capital is that it makes the disputes
over fixed fees or flow charges less sharp, since at least part
of such a charge would accrue to the power producer - as a river
association shareholder. Raising association's capital in such
a way does reduce the value of a PMA to the potential buyer because
the cash endowed to the association is &quot;dissolved&quot; among
other shareholders; on the other hand, this decrease in value
is somewhat compensated by the benefits described in this paragraph
that the power producer will also share with other association's
shareholders. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The internal decision-making mechanism of the
river association might be structured in a more subtle way than
simple majority rule. The shares issued to the power company are
preferred shares; they may carry a prior claim on dividends but
they might also carry a non-preferential voting restriction. In
this case the preferred stockholder might only be entitled to
fractional voting rights. On the other hand, to guarantee that
a majority of non-power users could not harm the power producer,
an affirmative rule of the preferred stockholder might be required
for some major decisions. This would give the power producer the
ability to block some actions but not the power to undertake actions
alone. This might be combined with some near unanimity rule to
override a veto by the power producer. The number of options are
numerous enough so that the role of the power company is soluble
in a mutually acceptable way. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Transferability of Shares.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
Normally, shareholders in a corporation are free to transfer their
shares at any time and under any conditions they want. However,
there are some reasons why it may not be optimal to implement
this principle in the case of corporate river associations. The
purpose of the river association is to pool together the stakeholders
to enable them manage their common water resource. The corporate
structure is intended to mobilize the interest of stakeholders
by giving them valuable assets and focusing their attention on
the opportunity costs of the non-power activities. However, completely
free trade in the associations' shares may harm the first objective
of keeping all stakeholders involved in the management of the
dam. On the other hand, not enabling the non-power users to trade
their shares dramatically reduces the value of these shares and
hence weakens the incentive of non-power users to invest in long-run
improvements in the dam. Such restrictions also reduce the ability
of the association to solve intra-user conflicts. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">One solution to the transferability problem
might be to allow the trading of shares only among the non-power
users. This would guarantee the balance between power and non-power
interest and would potentially lead to a more appropriate distribution
of shares among non-power users. The users who do not attach very
high value to membership in the river association would sell their
shares while those who place a high value on non-power activities
as well as the chance to actively manage the dam would buy them.
The drawback is that the potential scope (hence number) of buyers
is quite limited, which has a negative impact on prices at which
the shares could be sold. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">An alternative to this type of limitation on
sale might be to grant a right of first refusal to current users.
This approach would (in the stock certificate) lift the limitation
on the scope of buyers but protect the interests of current users.
A user wishing to sell his shares would be required to give the
right of first refusal to all of the current users at the outside
offer. If not enough users wish to buy the his shares in, say,
a week, then he could sell the shares without restrictions to
anyone at any price. Such a solution again assures that if some
users do not want to keep their shares, the shares would remain
in the hands of other users who attach sufficient value to them.
A good general principle would be a requirement that if someone
received shares due to ownership of land and later decided to
sell their land, then the shares must be sold together with the
land.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Privatization of Power Is
the Priority</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We have presented a variety of options for
structuring the sale of the PMA's along with the advantages and
disadvantages of each. We strongly prefer transferring the non-power
facilities and activities of federal hydro projects to corporate
associations of non-power stakeholders, because we believe that
the association is the appropriate entity to operate dams and
is the best institutional form in which to reach a reasonable
compromise of competing demands for water resources. However,
we realize that creating river associations could be a very complex
and potentially time consuming process: a process which could
substantially delay privatization of federal power. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is our position, however, that the privatization
of federal power activities should be given priority. That is
why we conclude that sale of PMA's via warrants should be initiated
as soon as possible, and a Holt/Bankhead type arrangement adopted
as an interim measure with a promise that the river association
is a target structure. The only thing that would need to be addressed
at that point would be the future position of the privatized PMA's
in river associations (e.g. percentage of shares, raising capital
by issuing preferential shares) because these have an ultimate
impact on the PMA market value. Immediately after the PMA's are
privatized, the federal government should begin transferring ownership
of the dams, using a river association approach. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The government must not slow down the privatization
of the PMA's while figuring out who should get the shares in the
river associations and how many. Removing the federal government
from the electricity business is the all important objective,
and it should not be delayed by arguments over the best way to
deal with the disposal of the non-power assets of the various
water projects. There will be time after we get the federal government
out of the electricity business to get the ownership and structure
of the dam operating agency correct. </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">EPILOGUE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">WHAT'S NEXT?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The privatization of the three PMA's analyzed
in this report is only the first, albeit important, step on the
road to remove the federal government from the electricity business.
It is the first step in cutting subsidies and leveling the playing
field for the emerging competitive market in electric energy.
The emphasis is on the word &quot;first.&quot; Aside from SEPA,
WAPA and SWPA, the federal government plays an active role in
the electricity business by owning and/or operating the Bonneville
Power Administration (BPA) and Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA).
It also influences the market by excluding municipal, co-operative
and other publicly-owned utilities from paying federal taxes and
by providing subsidized loans to rural electric co-operatives
through the Rural Electrification Administration: a trilobite
that somehow forgot to become extinct.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Among obsolete federal power programs, TVA
and BPA are certainly the largest: together they represent almost
80 percent of all federal power, and about 6.5 percent of all
power produced and marketed in the United States. However, it
is not their size alone that makes their privatization much more
complicated than SEPA, SWPA and WAPA. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">TVA's ambitious nuclear program has turned
out to be a classroom example of what &quot;stranded costs&quot;
look like in the real world - out of nine nuclear units built,
only two are currently operating, and TVA has been extremely reluctant
to write off the remaining seven. Deferred assets and construction
in progress total $15.7 billion, which is almost 50 percent of
TVA's total assets. On the other side of the balance sheet there
is another devil, $22.2 billion of long-term debt owed to bondholders.
Add to this a totally dominant position inside the &quot;fence&quot;
and you have one of the most complicated privatization projects
in the federal government. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">However, TVA is only one of the most complicated
privatization projects. Although BPA was somewhat more successful
in its participation in Washington Public Power Supply System
(WPPSS) nuclear program (one of three plants is currently operating),
it has a debt burden inherited from that program on the order
of $7 billion (or 44 percent of total assets). In addition to
that, BPA has become deeply involved in a salmon protection program,
which currently costs Northwest power consumers about $450 million
a year. This is a cost that will be difficult to recover in a
competitive marketplace, and it makes the real value of BPA much
lower than it may appear from its financial statements. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Because of various implicit subsidies and the
deferred recovery of some capital costs, TVA and BPA have been
able to keep their rates fairly low. This does not mean, however,
that we can simply extend our warrant plan to the &quot;big brothers&quot;
of federal power. Their enormous stranded costs and horrific financials
will make devising a workable privatization plan an even greater
political (and financial) challenge. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Despite future complications, we should move
now to take the first step. Privatizing the New Deal's Power Marketing
Administrations makes sense. Their original mission to help with
regional development was accomplished with the suburbanization
of America. Today, PMA's leave taxpayers with the bill to provide
subsidized power to the rich, distort and hinder competition and
productivity in the electric energy market, and are a large source
of frozen assets that could be used for federal deficit reduction.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Privatization can become politically viable
by using a method that creates direct benefits for stakeholders
in the PMA's. End-users of PMA power, worried about rate increases,
can be given the chance to earn actual monetary profits during
the sale of PMA's. Environmentalists, fishermen and boating companies,
worried about who controls the dams and reservoirs, can be given
that control themselves. It is time to replace the PMA's with
a new approach that empowers, and enriches, Americans. It is time
to turn the lights out on subsidized federal power.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">APPENDIX 1<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">AN ALTERNATIVE PROPOSAL FOR
CREATING POLITICAL SUPPORT<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Block-Shadegg privatization plan attempts
to generate political support for PMA privatization by creating
a strong interest group in its favor.  The plan does this by turning
potential opponents - those end users of PMA power who might see
rate increases after privatization - into supporters by ensuring
they obtain significant monetary benefits from the PMAs' sale.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The logic underlining this solution was <I>not</I>
recognition of &quot;property rights&quot; vested in federal subsidies;
we do not believe there is a legal entitlement to subsidized PMA
power.  We based our plan on an understanding of the political
decision making process.  Thus we recognized that groups which
perceive they will lose from policy are often able to stop change,
even if the change is produces net benefits for the country as
a whole.  For instance, concentrated special interests have been
able to get policies passed that produced net losses (i.e., farm
subsidies, electricity regulation, the minimum wage), leaving
dispersed and unorganized groups (i.e., general taxpayers, electricity
consumers, the unemployed) with the bill.  Those who would be
harmed by a policy do not always have the political organization
or clout to defend their interest. The challenge facing policymakers
now is to use the same mechanism for quite the opposite purpose:
Concentrate the benefits from a desirable policy change in the
hands of a well-defined interest group in order to make the desirable
change happen. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is possible that warrant plan we outline
may not be the best way to privatize the PMA's. It is possible
that interest groups other than warrant beneficiaries would be
even stronger supporters of privatization. Outlined below are
two alternative ways to politically approach privatization. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">One possibility would be for Congress to distribute
proportionally to all taxpayers warrants for all three PMA's,
implicitly giving them back &quot;their&quot; investment. Such
a plan may create political interest (and support among Members
of Congress) even in states without PMA's. As there are about
114 million taxpayers (warrants would be given only to those individuals
who filed personal income taxes in a given year), it would mean
a gain of about $47 for each taxpayer (strike price set at BG).
 Thus far more people would receive some direct financial benefit
under this plan than those 11 million end-users of PMA power.
 In addition, from the potential buyers' point of view, it actually
may be easier to contact 114 million people as a general public
instead of focusing on very specific group &quot;hidden&quot;
among others.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The disadvantage of distributing warrants equally
across all taxpayers is that the actual gain per taxpayer is not
very attractive.  Thus, it may be better to focus on residential
consumers of PMA power, bypassing the commercial, industrial and
public sector consumers. The warrants for a specific PMA would
be distributed equally among those households who ultimately consume
PMA through their municipal, cooperative or public utility.  If
the strike price remained at BG, the gains to each household would
be:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">$356 for SEPA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">$673 for SWPA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">$488 for WAPA<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This is a significant amount of money per household,
and would likely generate substantial political support for PMA
privatization.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">APPENDIX 2<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">METHODOLOGY <BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Estimating the Contribution of the
PMA's to the Budget<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The present value of the difference between
PMA receipts and appropriations should be equal to the net present
value of the debt, because the PMA's are required not to make
a profit. All money the PMA's contribute to the Treasury is simply
a repayment of their debt (with interest). Estimating the present
value of the repayment flow gives the estimate of the PMAs' value
to the Treasury.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The following assumptions were used to calculate
the present value of the debt repayment:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">No additional investments by the federal
government in the PMA's.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The entire unpaid federal investment (i.e.,
outstanding debt) repaid over 25 years in constant annual payments
(consisting of principal and interest payments)</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Interest rates charged on the debt equal
to the average interest rate for each PMA (4.6 percent for SEPA,
2.7 percent for SWPA and 4.45 percent for WAPA).</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Unpaid federal investment equal $1,007million for SEPA, $699 million for SWPA and $3,433 million for
WAPA.</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Interest paid on the portion of federal
debt used to finance investments in the PMA's is ignored</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">8.75 percent discount rate.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT></B>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Estimating the Increases in Average
Electricity Bills<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Although the EOP Group Study presented a great
deal of information concerning the impact of privatization on
muni and co-op residential customers, it did not contain the average
rate increase for end users. However, using the information EOP
provided we were able to estimate such an average.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The basic information provided in the EOP Group
Study was the percentage of all residential end users affected
by a rate increase of 0-5 percent, 5-10 percent, 10-20 percent,
and over 20 percent.  Assuming that bill increases are piece-wise
linear within these intervals, it is possible to estimate the
average bill increase as a weighted average of the mid-points
of these intervals (e.g, the increase for SEPA would be 2.5*0.94+7.5*0.06=2.8
percent). We refer to this estimate as a rough-interval estimate.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">TABLE A-1</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">ESTIMATE OF AVERAGE BILL INCREASE
FOR MUNI AND CO-OP RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMERS</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=5 WIDTH=346><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">% of Households Impacted by Bill Increases of:</FONT>
</TD><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=284></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=58></TD><TD WIDTH=68><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0-5%</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=72><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">5-10%</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=72><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">10-20%</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=76><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Over 20%</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=110><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Rough-Interval Estimate</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=100><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Fine-Interval Adjustment</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=74><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Final Estimate</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=58><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">SEPA</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=68><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">94%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">6%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=76><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=110><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">2.80%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=100><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.668</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=74><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">1.87%</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=58><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">SWPA</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=68><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">73%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">17%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">7%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=76><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">3%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=110><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">4.75%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=100><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.856</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=74><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">4.07%</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=58><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">WAPA</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=68><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">90%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">8%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">1.8%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=76><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.2%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=110><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">3.16%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=100><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.620</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=74><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">1.96%</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">However, the EOP study also included charts
that give the entire distribution of rate increases (percentage
of bill increase on the X-axis and percentage of customers on
the Y-axis) for some classes of preferential customers. Hence
these charts did not cover all end users (as opposed to the data
in Table A-1 which are reproduced from the study). It was obvious
to us from these charts that the distribution of bill increases
was not well approximated by our piece-wise linear estimate (see
Chart A-1 as an example). This means that the actual average rate
increase differs from the rough-interval estimate (the average
is higher for a concave distribution and lower for a convex distribution).
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CHART A-1<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><img SRC="img00008.gif"><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">To obtain a more accurate estimate, we read
the corresponding values from the charts, using 1 percent and
sometimes 0.5 percent intervals and calculated the average estimate
accordingly, assuming that the distribution was piece-wise linear
within these finer intervals. We then divided this average by
the rough estimate that was obtained by reading down the data
from the charts using 5 percent intervals. We refer to this ratio
as a fine-interval adjustment, indicating how much the more accurate
estimate differs from the simpler and rougher one. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As mentioned above, the charts did not cover
all end users, while the rate increases by 5 percent or 10 percent
intervals as presented in Table A-1 did. Thus the last step was
to extrapolate the difference between rough-interval and fine-interval
estimates as obtained from the charts on the rough-interval estimates
as calculated from Table A-1 data for all residential end users.
 Multiplying the rough-interval estimates with fine-interval adjustments
gives us the rate increase estimate used in the paper. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Estimate of End Users' Gains under
the Block-Shadegg Plan<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In order to estimate how much an average residential,
commercial, industrial and public customer of a particular muni,
co-op (or a public utility or an investor owned utility) is going
to gain under the Block-Shadegg privatization plan, we needed
information on the following variables:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">MV - the Market Value of PMA shares (see
text Table 5)</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">SPD - the Strike Price Discount (see text
Table 5)</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">R - total power revenues of a PMA in the
reference period (1993-1994 Annual Reports of SEPA, WAPA and SWPA)</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">P - the amount of electricity (measured
in dollars) that a particular muni or co-op purchased from a PMA
during the reference period (1993-1994 Annual Reports of SEPA,
WAPA and SWPA plus additional data provided by EOP Group on PMA
power purchases by those munies and co-ops who do not buy PMA
power directly but via another wholesale entity).</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">N(r,c,i,o) - number or residential, commercial,
industrial and other (predominantly public sector) end users served
by a particular muni or co-op (Electric Sales and Revenue 1993).</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">C(r,c,i,o) - total power consumption (measured
in dollars) of these customer classes during the reference period
(Electric Sales and Revenue 1993).</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The sequence of steps formula for calculating,
say, average residential end user's gains (in a specific muni
or coop service area) is the following:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">1) Total gains to all end users:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">TG = MV*SPD<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">2) Total gains accruing to all end users served
by a particular muni or coop: </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">TGA = TG * (P/R)<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">3) The sales to residential customers as a
percentage of total sales:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">S(r) = C(r/[C(r+C(c+C(i)+C(o)]<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">4) Total gains accruing to all residential
customers served by a particular muni or coop: </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">TGA(r) = TGA* S(r)<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">5) Average residential end user's gains:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">G(r) = TGA(r)/ N(r<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">These steps can be summarized in a single formula:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">G(r) = (MV*SPD) * (P/R) * {C(r/[C(r+C(c+C(i)+C(o)]}/N(r
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The methodology we used is probably best communicated
by a numerical example:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The total Market Value of WAPA is $5.182 billion,
and the Strike Price Discount is 0.481, which implies that $5.182*0.498
= $2.581 billion will be captured as gains (or value of warrants)
by end users. In 1993, the total WAPA revenues from power sales
were $606,319,000. In the same year, the City of Biggs, California,
purchased power from WAPA for $129,313. This means that 0.02133
percent (129,313/606,319,000) of all gains will accrue to the
residents and businesses in Biggs; in dollars, this represents
$2.581 billion * 0.02133 percent = $550,488.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In 1993, the power sales of the City of Biggs
to its customers, and average gains from selling warrants calculated
from the power sales were the following:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">TABLE A-2</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">POWER SALES OF CITY OF BIGGS
AND AVERAGE GAINS TO ITS CUSTOMERS</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Customer Class</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Residential </FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Commercial</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Industrial</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Other </FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Total</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">No. of Customers</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">575</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">45</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">1</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">624</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Power Consumption ($1,000)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">440</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">164</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">34</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">638</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Consumption as % of Total</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">68.97%</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">25.71%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">5.33%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.00%</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">100.00%</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Gains to a Customer Class ($)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">379,647</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">141,504</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">29,336</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">550,488</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">AVG Gains ($)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">660</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">3,144</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">29,336</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">882</FONT>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In some special cases, other adjustments were
necessary.  Specifically:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">In calculating the gains of TVA's end users
(TVA is one of SEPA's customers), only those end users who buy
power directly from TVA were counted as eligible for warrants.
Those who buy TVA (and consequently SEPA) power via their muni
or co-op were not included in our estimates. </FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Similarly, when calculating purchases of
PMA power by munies or co-ops (except those operating in TVA service
area), only direct purchases and purchases from wholesale public
or cooperative utilities were included. Thus, our calculation
does not include cases such as where a PMA sells to an IOU and
then the IOU sells to a muni that also buys directly from a PMA.
It is a policy question where to draw the bright line in calculating
warrant eligibility. We never go beyond one intermediate sale
in our calculations. </FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">For some co-ops, the only information available
to us was PMA power (measured in MWh) as a share of total power
needs.  To estimate how much power (measured in $) they actually
bought from the PMA's, we multiplied the physical share of PMA
power by their revenue from total sales to ultimate customers.
This would be an exact estimate if all munies and coops were buying
PMA power as well as other power for the same prices and if they
did not charge any markup on the purchase price. To adjust for
at least some of the inaccuracies of such an estimate, we multiplied
the estimated PMA power purchases of all co-ops for which we did
not have the exact data by a coefficient that transformed them
so that the sum of both directly available and estimated power
purchases was equal to total PMA sales. These numbers were then
used as an  input in the gains calculation. </FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">APPENDIX 3<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">MORE DETAILED INFORMATION
