<TITLE>FCC and the Telecommunications Act Endnotes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<center><h2>Endnotes For The FCC and the Telecommunications Act of 1996: Putting Competition on Hold?</h2>
</center><font size=2><br>Please use back to return to the document.
<p></font><hr>
* G.A. (Jay) Keyworth, II, is chairman of The Progress & Freedom Foundation. He served as Science Advisor to President Reagan, Director of the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, and as a member of the National Security Council.
<p>
Jeffrey A. Eisenach is president of The Progress & Freedom Foundation.
<p>
The views expressed are solely their own.<BR>
<p>
<hr>
<sup>1</sup> From the official title of the bill as introduced in the Senate.
<p>
<sup>2</sup> First Report and Order, Implementation of the Local Competition Provisions in the Telecommunications Act of 1996, FCC, August 8, 1996.
<p>
<sup>3</sup> Iowa Utilities Board v. FCC, Order Granting Stay Pending Judicial Review, U.S. Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit, October 15, 1996.
