<HTML>
<HEAD>


<TITLE>End Notes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<h6>Please use your browser's back 
option to return to the document.</h6><p>
<p><br>
<p><br>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">END NOTES<BR>
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<ol>

<P>
* Bruce Yandle, an Adjunct Fellow at The
Progress & Freedom Foundation, is Alumni Distinguished Professor
of Economics and Legal Studies at Clemson University and a Senior
Associate at the Political Economy Research Center. Andy H. Barnett is Associate Professor of Economics at Auburn University. Mark Brandly is a 
doctoral candidate at Auburn University. 
<p>
<li> There were earlier federal statutes
that addressed research and development and state cooperation,
but the 1970 statute was the first to establish federal controls.

<P>
<li> New car emissions of hydrocarbons
have fallen 97 percent since 1970, and California standards call
for the equivalent of a 99 percent reduction.  Between 1982 and
1991, ozone forming emissions decreased 13 percent and CO levels
declined, even with an increase in the number of vehicles and
miles driven.  (See U.S. Department of Energy, <U>Alternatives
to Traditional Transportation Fuels: An Overview</U>, Washington,
D.C., August 1994, p. 33.)
<P>
<li> The deepest criticism of the massive
efforts to deal with the ozone problem, to be discussed in this
report, relates to the 1988 data that forms the premise of the
problem.  The critics point out that 1988 was an outlier year
for drought and temperature, which contribute to higher ozone
readings.  Examination of a longer time series, before and after
1988, reduces significantly the ozone readings for the designated
ozone cities and regions.  (On this see, K.H. Jones and Jonathan
Adler, <U>Time to Reopen the Clean Air Act:  Clearing away the
Regulatory Smog</U>, Policy Analysis, No. 233, Washington, D.C.:
 Cato Institute, July 11, 1995, and Kenneth Chilton and Christopher
Boemer, <U>Smog in America:  The High Cost of Hysteria</U>, Policy
Study Number 128, St. Louis: Center for the Study of American
Business, January 1996.) <BR>

<P>
. See Peter Passell, &quot;Illinois
Is Looking To Market Forces to Help Reduce Its Smog,&quot;  <U>The</U>
<U>New York Times</U>, March 30, 1995. p. C1. Passell points out
that Chicago is establishing a market for VOCs.  Major corporate
polluters-Caterpillar, Abbott Labs, Amoco, Corn Products-are participating
in the planning phase.  The program involves six counties and
hundreds of polluters.  The 300 that emit more than 10 tons annually
will be obligated to participate. By 2007, total allowable emissions
will be reduced 60%. The program will also facilitate the purchase
and destruction of older, higher emission, cars.  Also, see Benjamin
A. Holden. &quot;Dirt in Hollywood?  Californians Have Pollution-Rights
Market Ready for It,&quot; <U>The Wall Street Journal</U>, April
12, 1995, p. B3. Holden describes the Regional Clean Air Incentive
Market or RECLAIM and reports that the Pacific Stock Exchange
has created an electronic trading system for Southern California
pollution credits called the SMOG exchange.  Some 24 companies
listed credits.  <BR>

<P>
<li> For a survey of alternative fuel
vehicle use across countries, see U.S. General Accounting Office,
<U>Alternative Fuels:  Experiences of Brazil, Canada, and New
Zealand Using Alternative Fuels</U>, GAO/RCED-92-119, Washington,
D.C., May 1992.
<P>
. Ibid.
<P>
<li> U.S. EPA, &quot;Clean Fuels:  An
Overview,&quot; EPA 400-F-92-008, Washington, D.C., August 1994.
<P>
<li> On issues related to the CAA, see
Robert H. Nelson, &quot;How Much is Enough?  An Overview of the
Benefits and Costs of Environmental Protection,&quot; Roger E.
Meiners and Bruce Yandle, eds., <U>Taking the Environment Seriously</U>,
Lanham, MD: Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers, 1993, pp. 1-23
<P>
<li> For background, see Lawrence J. White,
<U>The Regulation of Air Pollution Emissions from Motor Vehicles</U>,
Washington:  American Enterprise Institute, 1982, esp. ch. 3.
 Also, see Robert W. Crandall, et al., <U>Regulating the Automobile</U>,
Washington:  Brookings Institution, 1986, ch. 3.  For discussion
of more recent developments, see Tom Tietenberg, <U>Environmental
and Natural Resource Economics</U>, New York: Harper Collins Publishers,
1992, pp. 450-475.
<P>
<li> For useful nontechnical background,
see &quot;Ozone,&quot; <U>Automotive Engineering</U>, April 1995,
p. 57.<BR>

<P>
<li> See Kenneth Chilton and Christopher
Boemer, <U>Smog in America:  The High Cost of Hysteria</U>, St.
Louis:  The Center for the Study of American Business, January
1996, p. 12.<BR>

<P>
<li> Ibid.<BR>

<P>
<li> In making this point, Kenneth Chilton
and Christopher Boemer, op. cit., draw on National Research Council,
<U>Rethinking the Ozone Problem in Urban and Regional Air Pollution</U>,
Washington, D.C.: National Academy Press, Washington, D.C.: 1991.
 Quoting from the Council report, Chilton and Boemer state: &quot;On
days conducive to ozone formation, 'this VOC background should
be able to generate ozone concentrations that exceed the NAAQS
concentration of 0.12 ppm,' says the NRC.  Computer-generated
 simulations have shown that reactions between prevailing levels
of NOx and VOCs alone can generate ozone concentrations above
0.08 ppm in the Ohio River Valley and the entire Northeast corridor.&quot;
(Chilton and Boemer, ibid., p. 18.)<BR>

<P>
<li> Also, see Patrick Bedard, &quot;Still
Smoggy After All These Years,&quot; <U>Car and Driver</U>, April
1995, pp. 105-110.  Beard explains the situation this way: &quot;Control
of ozone is especially tricky because each city has its own air
chemistry, to which is added unburned hydrocarbons (HC) and oxides
of nitrogen (NOx) from cars.  Because the ratio is critical, locations
with excess HC-in Atlanta, for example, vegetation is a major
source of HC-are particularly sensitive to additional NOx and
insensitive to more HC.  The reverse is true in areas where coal-burning
power plants produce NOx.  Cars, however, are not tailored to
locations, except for statewide regulations specific to California.
 With cars, the regulators' plan is simply to eliminate as much
HC and NOx as possible and hope for the best.&quot; (Patrick Bedard,
ibid., p. 107.)  <BR>

<P>
<li> K. H. Jones and Jonathan Adler, <U>Time
to Reopen the Clean Air Act:  Clearing away the Regulatory Smog</U>,
Policy Analysis, No. 233, Washington, D.C.:  Cato Institute, July
11, 1995, p. 7.<BR>

<P>
<li> Similar findings are reported for
the northeastern states where 1988 data shows 39 nonattainment
areas, with 23 marginal, 6 moderate, 6 serious and 3 severe. 
Based on 1992-94 data, the total is 13, with 6 marginal and no
serious or severe. (Jones and Adler, op. cit, p. 7.)
<P>
<li> See U.S. Department of Energy, Energy
Information Agency, <U>Alternatives to Traditional Transportation
Fuels: An Overview</U>, Washington, D.C., August, 1994, pp. 99-100
and U.S. Department of Energy, <U>First Interim Report of the
Federal Fleet Conversion Task Force</U>, Washington, D.C., August
1993, appendix K.
<P>
<li> In addition to setting higher 1996
model year standards, the statute instructs EPA to review the
new standards and if necessary for achieving clean air goals to
cut allowable emissions by 50 percent beginning in 2004.  (See
U.S. EPA, &quot;Motor Vehicles and the 1990 Clean Air Act,&quot;
EPA 400-F-92-013, Washington, U.S. EPA, August 1994.)
<P>
<li> A comparison of these standards with
the 1970 standards indicates how far gasoline-fueled vehicles
have come in reducing emissions.  The 1970 standard called for
a maximum of 3.9 gpm for hydrocarbons, 33.3 gpm for carbon monoxide,
and no control of nitrogen oxides.  (See Robert H. Hahn, &quot;Choosing
Among Fuels and Technologies for Cleaning Up the Air,&quot; AEI
Discussion Paper, Washington, D.C.:  American Enterprise Institute,
December 1993, Table 1.)<BR>

<P>
<li> The California standards are far
more complex than indicated here.  The standards involve three
auto tiers-transitional low emission vehicles (TLEVs), which are
to meet the standard stated in the text, low emission vehicles
(LEVs), which are to meet a stricter standard, and ultra low emission
vehicles (ULEVs) that are to achieve a standard that is close
to zero.  Speaking in terms of a composite emission standard called
non-methane organic gases, a precursor for smog, the California
Air Resources Board estimates that <U>lifetime</U> emissions of
the three vehicle types will be 55 pounds, 33 pounds, and 18 pounds
respectively.  The Society of Automotive Engineers estimates that
improved gasoline engine vehicles could reduce emissions to the
level of the LEV vehicles.  (For discussion, see Robert W. Hahn,
&quot;Choosing Among Fuels and Technologies for Cleaning Up the
Air,&quot; AEI Discussion Paper, Washington, D.C.: American Enterprise
Institute, December 1993, pp. 2-4.)
<P>
. The nine cities are Los Angeles, Houston,
New York, Baltimore, Chicago, San Diego, Philadelphia, Milwaukee,
and Ventura. (See U.S. Department of Energy, Energy Information
Agency, <U>Alternatives to Traditional Transportation Fuels: 
An Overview</U>, Washington, D.C., June 1994, p. 35.)
<P>
<li> When the oxygen content is increased,
hydrocarbon and CO emissions can be reduced by 7.0 and 9.3 percent
respectively. (See Gilbert Sperling, &quot;Alternative Fuel Vehicles,&quot;
<U>Energy Law &amp; Transactions</U>, Release 5, Oakland, CA:
Matthew Bender &amp; Co., 1993, p. 74-9.) 
<P>
<li> According to DOE estimates, the total
reformulated fuel requirements for these urban markets and others
that may choose to require the same fuel will quickly reach 60
percent of all gasoline sold in the U.S. (U.S. Department of Energy,
Energy Information Agency, <U>Alternatives to Traditional Transportation
Fuels:  An Overview</U>, Washington, D.C., June 1994, pp. 23-24.)
<BR>

<P>
<li> Section 244 of the CAA, which specifies
the fleet program, requires clean-fuel vehicles to be used in
serious, severe and extreme ozone nonattainment areas.  Examples
might be taxi, school bus, and delivery vans that refuel at a
common location.  The CAA envisions a goal of 250,000 clean-fuel
vehicles.  (See Henry A. Waxman, Gregory S. Weststone, and Philip
S. Barnett, &quot;Cars, Fuels, and Clean Air:  A Review of Title
II of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990,&quot; <U>Environmental
Law</U>, Vol. 21, 1991, pp. 1947-2019, at 2001.)
<P>
<li> For discussion, see Gilbert Sperling,
&quot;Alternative Fuel Vehicles,&quot; <U>Energy Law and Transactions</U>,
Release 5, Oakland, CA: Matthew Bender &amp; Co., 1993, pp. 74-37
to 74-39.
<P>
<li> The CAA contains sanctions for nonattainment
regions classified as severe that fail to meet ozone reduction
deadlines. All along, new stationary emission sources must obtain
offsets from existing sources, and the emission offset ratio rises
with a lack of progress.  If progress continues to fall short,
then even those ozone nonattainment areas not classified as severe
may be designated severe unless the state organizes an emission
trading system.  Put simply, the statute is market-forcing at
certain margins.  (See Penny Mintz, &quot;Transportation Alternatives
within the Clean Air Act:  A History of Congressional Failure
to Effectuate and Recommendations for the Future,&quot; <U>New
York University Environmental Law Journal</U>, Vol. 3, 1994, pp.
1-18, at 14.)
<P>
<li> The states include Connecticut, Delaware,
Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New
York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and the consolidated
metropolitan statistical area of Washington, D.C., which includes
part of Virginia.  The CAA allows for creation of other such regions,
when EPA deems necessary. (For discussion, see Daniel B. Trinkle,
&quot;Cars, Congress, and Clean Air for the Northeast:  A Separation
of Powers Analysis of the Ozone Transport Commission,&quot; <U>Environmental
Affairs</U>, Vol. 23, 1995, pp. 169-199.)<BR>

<P>
<li> See Michael Bradley, &quot;Addressing
the Environmental Needs of the Northeast:  A Look at the Future
of Alternative Fuels,&quot; <U>California Western Law Review</U>,
Vol. 28, 1991, pp. 59-63.
<P>
<li> Virginia joined the auto industry
suit. On this, see Daniel B. Trinkle, &quot;Cars, Congress, and
Clean Air for the Northeast:  A Separation of Powers Analysis
of the Ozone Transport Commission,&quot; <U>Environmental Affairs</U>,
Vol. 23, 1995, p. 179.<BR>

<P>
<li> The new cleaner vehicles, which would
reduce ozone-related emissions by 50 percent, relative to the
standard set for the national fleet, would be introduced in the
Northeastern and Mid-Atlantic states beginning in 1996.  These
NLEVs will be introduced nationally in 2001. NLEV tailpipe emissions
are to be limited to 0.2 g/mile for nitrogen oxide and 0.075 g/mile
for hydrocarbons, the two pollutants that produce ozone.  Those
caps would be 50 percent and 70 percent below current limits,
respectively. (See &quot;Cloudy Prospects for NGVs May Soon Find
Clear Air,&quot; <U>Natural Gas Week</U>, Jan. 8, 1996, pp. 6-7.)
<BR>

<P>
<li> In addition to EPACT, the Alternative
Motor Fuels Act of 1988 encouraged the development, production
and use of AFVs.  Funding of $18.5 million was provided for 1990-93.
 (See U.S. General Accounting Agency, &quot;Alternative Fuels:
 Increasing Federal Procurement of Alternative-Fueled Vehicles,&quot;
GAO/RCED-91-169, May 1991.  Also, the Intermodal Surface Transportation
Act of 1991, which focuses primarily on transportation planning
and related federal programs, addresses AFVs.)
<P>
<li> The 1990 Kuwait invasion, still fresh
in the memories of most Americans, led to a daily curtailment
of seven percent. The Iranian revolution of 1978-79 and the Arab
Embargo of 1973-1974 had smaller daily impacts on the flow of
oil but lasted far longer than the Kuwait disruptions.  To put
the disruptions in perspective, the daily reductions during the
1978 revolution was equal to roughly 5.5 percent of world daily
consumption.(<U>Statement of Jay Hakes, Administrator</U>, Energy
Information Administration, Department of Energy, before the Subcommittee
on Energy and Environment of the Committee on Science, U.S. House
of Representatives, March 14, 1996, p. 35.)<BR>

<P>
<li> See, The National Defense Council
Foundation, <U>Natural Gas Vehicles:  Helping Ensure America's
Energy Security</U>, Washington, D.C., October 1995, p. i, <U>Statement
of Joseph Romm</U>, Acting Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary,
Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy, U.S. Department
of Energy, before the Subcommittee on Energy and Environment of
the Committee on Science, U.S. House of Representatives, March
14, 1996, p. 4 and <U>U.S. Energy Outlook and Implications for
Energy R&amp;D</U>, Hearings of the Subcommittee on Energy and
Environment, Committee on Science, U.S. House of Representatives,
March 14, 1996.
<P>
<li> U.S. Department of Energy, <U>EPACT
Initiatives for Alternative Fuel Vehicles</U>, Washington, D.C.,
March 1995, p. 3.
<P>
<li> We note that President Carter issued
Executive Order 12261 in 1981 requiring federal agencies to use
gasohol where it was feasible to do so. The experience under the
order was similar to that under EPACT.  There were supply problems,
unanticipated expenses, and competing regulations.  (On this see,
U.S. General Accounting Office, &quot;Gasohol:  Federal Agencies'
Use of Gasohol,&quot; GAO/T-RCED-92-73, June 24, 1992.)
<P>
<li> The U.S. General Accounting Office
provided a 1994 report on progress and problems associated with
the federal fleet purchases.  At the end of 1993, some 7,800 AFVs,
about two percent of the total, were in the federal fleet.  Problems
encountered involved higher than anticipated vehicle costs problems
encountered involved higher than anticipated vehicle costs, insufficient
refueling facilities, and mismatch of vehicles with infrastructure.
 For example, 118 methanol vehicles were sent to Atlanta, which
had no methanol refueling capability.  In addition, the GAO was
unable to obtain any meaningful estimate of the effects of the
AFVs on air quality goals.  (See U.S. General Accounting Office,
<U>Alternative-Fueled Vehicles:  Progress Made in Accelerating
Federal Purchases, but Benefits and Costs Remain Uncertain</U>,
GAO/RCED-94-161, July 1994.)
<P>
<li> This discussion is based on U.S.
General Accounting Office, <U>Alternative-Fueled Vehicles:  Progress
Made in Accelerating Federal Purchases, but Benefits and Costs
Remain Uncertain</U>, GAO/RCED-94-161, July 1994.
<P>
<li> Ibid. p. 30.
<P>
<li> For discussion, see Robert W. Crandall
and John D. Graham, &quot;The Effect of Fuel Economy Standards
on Auto Safety,&quot; <U>Journal of Law &amp; Economics</U>, Vol.
32, April 1989, pp. 97-118.
<P>
<li> Ibid.
<P>
<li> For example, the per-mile injury
rate for CNG vehicles is 37 percent lower than for gasoline fleet
vehicles and 34 percent lower than all gasoline vehicles.  (See
A. D. Koen, &quot;U.S. Natural Gas Industry Aims to Bolster Role
in Transportation,&quot; <U>Oil and Gas Journal</U>, Vol. 92,
August 8, 1994, pp. 19-23.)
<P>
<li> U.S. Department of Energy,  <U>Alternative
Fueled Vehicles for State Government and Fuel Provider Fleets,
A Guide</U>, Washington, D.C., March, 1996.
<P>
<li> In addition to these programs for
stimulating demand for AFVs, EPACT specifically requires DOE to
engage in research and development activities that focus on the
development of improved technologies for using natural gas and
other alternative fuels.<BR>

<P>
<li> U.S. Department of Energy, <U>Alternatives
