<head>
<title>  Where Limited Government Meets Family Values:  Parental Rights and The Third Wave -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Where Limited Government Meets Family Values:<br>
Parental Rights and The Third Wave</h2>
<p>
By Jeffrey Bell
</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
As the Third Wave ushers in an unprecedented era of government devolution and rapid 
change in the social fabric, the role of private institutions is becoming increasingly highlighted.  
This is a welcome development, for while rejection of the centralized, bureaucratic model of 
government may seem as inevitable as it is desirable, "limited government" is only half of the 
equation.  If a consensus is reached that government will no longer be responsible for carrying 
out certain basic functions, we then face the perhaps more interesting task of reassigning the 
responsibility for these functions.  As predictable as the motions of a seesaw, if government's 
role is to decrease, the role of spontaneous, private institutions must increase.  
<p>
Harsh words for Big Government's incompetence are not enough.  Pessimism about the 
competence of the centralized state must be balanced by an optimism in the ability of families 
and local communities to meet the challenges of devolution.  And when it comes to society's 
most essential task -- the care and raising of children -- America's parents are ready, willing and 
able to step up to the plate.  
<p>
To enable parents to carry out their enormous responsibilities, the law must respect their 
rights.  The importance of the parent-child relationship deserves explicit recognition and 
protection from government.  For too long, America's families have been micro-managed by 
agents of the "nanny state" exhibiting a "we know what's best for your children" mentality.  
<p>
The futility of bureaucrats substituting their judgment for that of parents is perhaps most 
evident in public schools.  Some elements of the growing parental rights movement are 
motivated by the fact that values taught in school often contradict values taught at home; others 
are more concerned with the "dumbing down" of academic standards.  Both problems result from 
a lack of accountability to parents, who are, after all, the true owners of the school.  
<p>
The Third Wave is demonstrating that decentralization tends to increase the 
quality of products produced.   We ought to apply this principle to education reform.  Today's 
children need to learn the skills that will help them adapt to tomorrow's fast-changing work 
environments.  We must place our faith in parents as the natural party to demand the kind of 
accountability and quality from our schools necessary to meet this goal.  
<p>
More firmly establishing the parental rights principle also anticipates that with the Third 
Wave will come new models for educating our children.  Consider, for example, the Noah 
Webster Academy, a network of Michigan homeschooling families which will soon be linked by 
a computer network to facilitate curriculum development and implementation through text 
transmission, video lectures and assignments.  A team of 14 licensed educators is available at a 
central location to provide assistance via toll-free helplines.  The Noah Webster Academy is 
applying for state funding under the innovative Michigan charter school legislation.  It is difficult 
to predict how our notions of "school" may change during the Information Age, but Noah 
Webster provides a glimpse of things to come.  
<p>
The parental rights principle accounts for the fact that centralized engineering and design 
have given way to spontaneous "unauthorized" problem-solving.  It provides the tool families 
need to navigate uncharted waters while expressing optimism that in the vast majority of cases, 
parents' choices for their children will be far superior to those made by agents of the state 
advocating a one-size-fits-all solution.<p>
<p>
The Third Wave is providing families with new opportunities as well as new challenges.  
While new technologies are making it easier for parents to work at home, the barrage of images 
and ideas that children are be exposed to is increasing exponentially.  We ought to ensure that 
parents have greater input into government programs and public school policies that too often 
contradict values taught at home.  Parents struggling to monitor their children's exposure to 
controversial messages in pop culture have a right as taxpayers to demand that their government 
not contribute to this problem.
<p>
In this era of rapid change and transition, it is not always easy to see which aspects of the 
current social fabric are passing away and which are foundational to that which is to come.  This 
uncertainty makes it all the more necessary to make explicit those values, those bonds between 
persons, that won't change, and shouldn't change, even if we had the choice.  The parent-child 
relationship is surely worth preserving, protecting and strengthening in order to prepare for the 
rigors of the future.
<p>
Government played a critical role in the transition from the Agricultural Age to the 
Industrial Age by providing a solid currency and protecting rights to land, capital and trade 
routes.  As we increased our power over our physical environment, government lent stability to 
the process, curbed excesses and helped make possible unprecedented economic expansion.  Our 
current transition into the Information Age coincides with a renewed appreciation for the family 
as the critical building block of a healthy society.  As our ability to manipulate, control and 
magnify our intellectual capital increases, government can again play a critical role by protecting 
the right of parents to direct the upbringing and education of their children.  Keeping our 
foundation of strong families intact will help ensure a smooth transition to limited government 
and a Third Wave social fabric. 
<p>
<p>
Jeffrey Bell is Chairman of Of the People Foundation, a non-partisan education and research organization engaged in the study of the emerging parental rights movement.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/i-ac0795.html">July Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
