<head>
<title>The Competitive Advantage of the Inner City -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>The Competitive Advantage of the Inner City</h2>
<p>
By Michael E. Porter
</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The economic distress of America's inner cities is one of the most pressing issues facing the nation.  The lack of businesses, investment and, most importantly, jobs in these disadvantaged urban areas not only perpetuates a crushing poverty, but fuels other social problems such as crime and drug abuse.  As the inner cities continue to deteriorate, the debate on how to aid them grows increasingly divisive and bitter.
<p>
Underscoring the current state of affairs is a sad reality: the numerous efforts to revitalize inner cities over the past few decades have clearly failed.  Despite the investment of substantial resources and good faith efforts of many in the minority as well as in the majority communities, the creation of a sustainable economic base in inner cities, and with it employment opportunities, wealth creation, role models and improved infrastructure, still eludes us.
<p>
We believe that past efforts have been based on the wrong model.  Assistance to inner cities has largely taken the form of relief programs such as income assistance, housing subsidies and food stamps with the intent of addressing highly visible social needs.
<p>
Genuine economic development initiatives aimed at building businesses in the inner city have been fragmented and ineffective.  These limited efforts at economic development have taken the form of either outright subsidies and preferences for companies, or efforts to stimulate economic activity in tangential fields such as housing and neighborhood development.  These approaches have largely failed.  Without economically viable companies and jobs, social programs only grow larger.
<p>
<h3>A New Approach</h3>
<p>
We need a new model for inner city economic development. It must be based on an economic rather than a social perspective.  It must be centered on the private sector, not government or social service organizations.  It must address companies directly, rather than attempting to stimulate economic development indirectly through investments in housing and community infrastructure.  It must be focused on creating inner city businesses that are profitable in their own right, rather than presupposing the need for subsidies, incentives or unprofitable actions mandated by government.
<p>
The new model should view the inner city as a distinct but integral part of the regional and national economy, not as an island unto itself.  The new model must be trade and "export" oriented, rather than focused solely on businesses that serve the local community.  The goal should be to create regional, national and even international companies, not just small local businesses.
<p>
The cornerstone of the new model is to reveal the profit potential of the inner city by identifying the unique potential competitive advantages of inner city-based companies which provide the basis for sustainable market positions.  Inner city businesses need locational advantages which allow them to compete with firms based elsewhere and to occupy a specialized position that adds value within the regional and national economy.
<p>
If companies are to prosper and put down roots in the inner city, they must be driven by more than subsidies or social conscience.  Inner city investments will fail in the long run unless they stand on their own merits.
<p>
The new model must link the inner city to the regional economy rather than further isolate it.  This means networking with and harnessing the capabilities of companies in the surrounding region.  It also will require improved infrastructure to unclog the physical flow of goods and services into and out of inner city areas.
<p>
The new model must not only address inner city residents, but also encourage skilled and experienced individuals who live and work elsewhere, especially minorities, to turn their attention to the inner city.  These leaders must transfer their skills and participate in new business formation alongside entrepreneurs within the community, motivated by the creation of wealth, not social service or activism.
<p>
The new model must engage mainstream supporting institutions such as banks, universities, and training providers, instead of relying on fragmented and poorly equipped social service institutions.  The emphasis should be on encouraging private sector/mainstream entities to serve the community profitably, rather than creating even more overlapping government or quasi-government organizations.
<p>
The new model must address the high costs of doing business in the inner city directly, rather than employing subsidies in an attempt to offset them directly.
<p>
The role of government itself must change markedly.  The new model must be built around incentives for private sector entities instead of relying on the government to directly deliver financing or services.  Government should concentrate on improving the business environment, not taking leadership in business development.
<p>
Finally, real estate and community development must fit into a broader strategy based on these principles, instead of being seen as a strategy in its own right.
<p>
<h3>Physical location</h3>
<p>
Inner city areas are in what should be economically valuable locations.  They sit near congested, high-rent areas, major business centers, and astride transportation and communications nodes.
<p>
Inner city locations thus offer potential advantages for those businesses that benefit from proximity to downtown business districts, logistical infrastructure, entertainment and tourist destinations, and concentrations of other companies.  This creates opportunities for relocating activities such as warehousing, data processing, food preparation, and others that can be de-coupled from downtown headquarters, or other company locations, but yet still benefit from proximity. 
<p>
<h3>Demand Conditions</h3>
<p>
The second potential competitive advantage of the inner city lies in demand conditions.  The most obvious opportunity is in serving the immense inner city market.  Even though average incomes are relatively low, high population density translates into substantial purchasing power and a large market.
<p>
Our Boston study area, for example, has an estimated total family income of 3.4 billion dollars.  Despite a 21 percent lower average household income level than the rest of Boston, spending power per acre is 5.6 percent higher than the rest of Boston and much higher than in surrounding suburbs.
<p>
The inner city market is not only large, but young and rapidly growing, due in part to immigration and relatively high birth rates.  Minority consumers represent the major growth market of the future.
<p>
Local demand in the inner city has already triggered the creation of some businesses, but there is potential for many more.  Strong unmet demand for housing, for example, has led to the formation of a substantial real estate cluster in inner-city Boston and elsewhere.  Indeed, the inner city has spawned the creation of hundreds of social service organizations.  Boston has a group of inner city-based security guard companies who got started based on local demand but who are beginning to "export."
<p>
<h3>Access to regional clusters</h3>
<p>
A third potential advantage of the inner city is the ability to leverage access to competitive nearby regional clusters.
<p>
In Boston, for example, the inner city is next door to world-class financial services and health care clusters.  South Central Los Angeles is close to the huge entertainment cluster and a large logistical services and wholesaling complex.
<p>
These competitive clusters in the surrounding area create two types of potential advantages.  The first is for business formation.  Proximity to highly competitive nearby industries can be a major competitive advantage in providing supplies, components and supporting services to multiple nearby customers.
<p>
Inner city firms can also draw on the presence of competitive firms in their region to compete in downstream products and services.  For example, Massachusetts' strength in financial services should provide an opportunity for minority firms to provide financial services tailored to minority businesses and individual needs, such as secured credit cards, factoring, and mutual funds, both within and outside the inner city in Boston and elsewhere in the country.
<p>
<h3>Human resources</h3>
<p>
The fourth potential advantage of the inner city, not based on location per se, is in the area of human resources.  An abundant supply of low-cost labor is not in and of itself an advantage, because lower-cost labor is available in rural and foreign locations.  However, human resource advantages do arise today in the inner city in several forms.
<p>
First, inner city workers are often more motivated and more loyal in fields where there is high turnover in other locations.  A good example is a bakery in the heart of Boston's inner city, which bakes and decorates cakes sold to supermarkets throughout the region.
<p>
It can attract and retain residents from the areas at seven to eight dollars per hour, plus contributions to pensions and health insurance, and has almost 100 local employees.  Coupled with the logistical advantage of the inner city location, this labor pool has allowed the company to thrive.  These sorts of jobs represent a starting point in building a sustainable economy.
<p>
Second, our research in Boston and elsewhere has revealed a real capacity in inner cities for entrepreneurship.  Some of this entrepreneurial energy has been directed at building businesses.  Most legitimate inner city entrepreneurship, however, has been directed at community activism and the provision of social services.
<p>
In Boston's inner city, for example, there are a truly remarkable number of social service providers as well as social, fraternal, and religious organizations.  The density of such organizations is far higher in the inner city than in Boston as a whole.  (Forty percent of the city's employment in social service and membership organizations was in our study area in 1990, compared to 11 percent of the city's total employment).
<p>
Behind the creation and building of these organizations is a whole cadre of minority entrepreneurs who have responded to intense local demand for social services and funding opportunities provided by government, foundations, and private sector sponsors.  The challenge is to redirect some of this talent and energy towards building for-profit businesses and creating wealth.
<p>
In order to unleash this economic potential of inner cities, one must confront a series of significant disadvantages.  Businesses operating in the inner city face more obstacles than those based elsewhere.  Unless these disadvantages can be addressed directly, instead of indirectly through subsidies or mandates, the locational advantages of inner cities will continue to be nullified and eroded.  To do so, however, it will be necessary to reexamine and discard many old approaches.
<p>
<p>
Michael E. Porter is a professor at Harvard Business School.  This article is an excerpt of a longer study with the same name.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/i-ac0795.html">July Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
