<html>
<head>
<title>Term Limits: Restoring Faith in Our Government -- PFF</title>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Term Limits: Restoring Faith in Out Government</h2>
<p>
By John Boehner
</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<blockquote>
<i>"To restore accountability to Congress.  To end its cycle of scandal and disgrace.  To make us all proud again of the way free people govern themselves..."</i></blockquote>
<p>
These words from the preamble of the <i>Contract with America</i> are at the very heart of the new Congressional majority's effort to rebuild citizens' faith in their government.  Although the <i>Contract </i>was an important collection of long-overdue reforms to our federal government, the concept of a "contract" as a whole was greater than the sum of its parts.  That restoration of faith, long battered by an out-of-touch and scandal-plagued crop of entrenched politicians, was the true aim of this <i>Contract.</i>
<p>
No other issue better captures the spirit of this effort than term limits.
<p>
One of the people's great frustrations with government is politicians who ignore their wishes and openly flout the public policy demands of the American people.  It has been argued that the former Democratic leadership's treatment of the issue of term limits led not only to the general voter discontent with Congress felt during last November's election, but contributed directly to the unprecedented defeat of the Speaker of the House himself.  Former Speaker Foley not only opposed term limits, he used the power of his office to prevent an open and honest debate of the issue on the House floor.  And when his very own constituents voted at the ballot box to impose term limits, he took them to court in order to stop their initiative.  Is it any wonder that Speaker Foley was the poster child of the term limits movement last year?
<p>
The <i>Contract with America </i>stands in contrast to this arrogance.  It is that kind of "I-know-better-than-you" conceit that led to the very creation of a Contract and the election of a new majority committed to allowing issues such as term limits to be debated before the people's representatives.
<p>
It is very important that the great issues of the day be deliberated and acted upon.  That is why, even though I had until this year had voiced opposition to them, I fought last summer to make sure term limits were included in our<i> Contract. </i> Their absence would have been an act of disdain on our part.  While I have doubts about term limits, I have greater doubts about Congress' ability to govern without greater confidence from the public -- and that is at the heart of our efforts to reform government and renew America.  
<p>
The people of this country, in state after state and in district after district,  have made it clear that they want term limits.  And they do so not just through opinion polls and letters and protests, but at the ballot box.  Of the twenty-three states which have passed term limits, all but one are the result of citizen initiated ballot referendum.
<p>
I am proud that it is a Republican Congress that has brought this matter to the House floor for vote and debate for the first time in our nation's history -- fulfilling the promise we made in our <i>Contract with America. </i> The new majority proved to all Americans that we were willing to let the people decide whether or not they wished to amend our great charter of government, as is their inalienable right.
<p>
Although we had a full and honest debate on the issue, we were ultimately unsuccessful in obtaining the necessary two-thirds majority required to approve such an amendment.  
<p>
Just two years ago you could have had a meeting of congressional term limits supporters in a phone booth.  When the dust settled after the March vote more than 80 percent of House Republicans voted for a term limits constitutional amendment -- exceeding the 72 percent support term limits receives from the public at large.  
<p>
In order to approve the amendment, House Republicans would have required the support of just half the Democrats in the House.  Sadly, fewer than 20 percent of them voted for term limits -- ensuring defeat of the amendment.
<p>
But the story doesn't end there.  All of the great legislative reform battles in our nation's history have taken time, time to have the voters at the ballot box visit their wrath upon the elected officials who opposed their wishes.  That is why the House leadership is committed to making this an issue in 1996 and have pledged to make a constitutional amendment on term limits House Resolution number 1 in the next Congress.   
<p>
As a practical matter, term limits may for better -- or may for worse -- fundamentally change our government.  As a governing idea, they deserve a national, constitutional debate.  This debate is not just about limiting the terms for Representatives.  No, the debate is about whether or not we are willing to respect the judgment of those who elected us.
<p>
This is an issue much larger than budgets and programs and bureaucrats and all else that makes up what is known as our federal government.  This debate is about politicians in Washington thwarting the people's right to alter their form of government.  I believe this is exactly the type of debate that our Founding Fathers envisioned when they established the process whereby our nation's citizens exercise their power as "we the people."  
<p>
As a member of the new majority, I want us to rely on our performance and not our words to change the public's contempt for this great institution.  But as a Republican, I am also willing to step up and admit that the calls for term limits are not directed at any one party.  Congress' performance over the last several years has forced this call for change.  Wasteful spending, bounced checks, out of balance budgets, bloated bureaucracies, a reliance on special interest campaign funds.  Clearly, both major parties must admit responsibility in having failed the people.  We now have the opportunity to correct that failure.
<p>
While our failure to pass term limits (this time) may have disappointed many, the American people are clearly pleased with the progress the <i>Contract </i>and the new majority in Congress have made so far.  Politicians who do what they said they would do; a Congress that is working harder and more successful than any since 1933; and, a fundamental change in the way Washington does business have all helped renew America's faith in this institution.  In fact, an April <i>Wall Street Journal</i>/NBC News poll indicates for the first time a majority of those responding -- 47 percent to 40 percent -- said they approved of the job Congress is doing.   
<p>
The fact remains, however, that whenever contempt is openly displayed by politicians towards the public and their desires for reform, it severely lessens our moral authority and practical ability to govern.  Our commitment to debate and ultimately pass a term limits amendment is the first step on the long road toward restoring this institution's credibility with, and accountability to, the American people.  Nothing less will do.
<p>
<p>
John Boehner is a Member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Ohio chairman of the Republican Conference.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>
