HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 11:39:06 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:18 GMT
Content-length: 8950
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>A People's Budget -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a><br> 
<center>
<h2>A People's Budget</h2>
</center>
<ul><blockquote>
<p>
<p>
<p>
What would the budget of the United States government look like if policymakers in Washington followed the instructions voters set last November?  It would be the most complete transformation of the government in Washington at least since the Great Society:
<p>
<ul>
<li>
The responsibility for running and paying for state and local programs would be returned to the states and localities, where it belongs -- and where people can hold elected officials more accountable for producing results.
<li>
The government in Washington would be nearly one-third smaller, as a percentage of GDP, than it is today.  At 15.7 percent of GDP, it would be the smallest it has been since 1951.
<li>
Most Federal excise taxes would be eliminated, and the income tax cut by 22 percent, giving people the funds to take care of themselves and their families, and giving states and localities the tax base they would need to take on their new responsibilities.
<li>
Medicare would begin the transformation from a 1960s "command and control" bureaucracy to a 1990s system of consumer choice.
<li>
Corporate welfare and subsidies for the privileged, powerful and elite would be eliminated.
<li>
The Federal budget would be balanced, and the debt would begin to shrink rapidly relative to the size of the economy.  With Medicare saved from bankruptcy and the budget deficit finally eliminated, the foundation would have been created to deal with the looming crisis in Social Security.
</ul>
<p>
That, at least, is the answer contained in <b>The People's Budget: A Common Sense Plan for Shrinking the Government in Washington</b>, crafted by some of the nation's foremost thinkers on the future of America, including:  Ed Dale, <i>New York Times </i>reporter on the budget for 20 years; Jeff Eisenach, President of the Progress and Freedom Foundation; Frank Luntz, 1992 Perot Presidential Campaign and 1994 Contract with America Pollster; Tim Muris, former budget official in the Reagan Administration; and, William Schnieder, defense expert currently at the Hudson Institute.
<p>
Designed not for Washington, D.C. policy experts but for the American people, <b>The People's Budget</b> will be sold in bookstores nationally beginning June 1. (It will be available May 15th by mail; order at 1-800-955-5493.) Unlike other pundits who asked how much the budget needed to be cut to be in balance, the authors of <b>The People's Budget</b> asked what type of government do people want in Washington, and then made the budget accordingly.
<p>
And the type of government people want was made loud and clear on November 8, 1994, when the American people voted for Big Change.  Nearly 73 percent said on the day after the polls closed that the Federal Government was too big. 27 percent said it should be cut between 21 and 41 percent, while a stunning 33 percent of Americans said the Federal Government should be cut between 41 and 60 percent.
<p>
Indeed, when examined by the standards of what makes sense to the American people, all kinds of seemingly sacrosanct Washington government activities do not make sense and are ripe for change -- even though many of them had a worthy purpose when they began. 
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Do paid bureaucrats in Washington, DC know better than the citizens of individual cities, towns and counties how to provide help to the poor?  Common sense says they do not.  But in Washington, the idea of turning welfare back to the states is "radical."
<li>	
Should the defense establishment continue using a procurement process that leads to billions of dollars in waste?  Common sense says the Department of Defense ought to operate more like a modern business than a 1930's bureaucracy; but in Washington it's a "radical" idea.
<li>	
Should special interest groups -- from corporations to labor unions, farmers to artists -- receive billions of dollars solely because they possess the political power to demand and get them?  Common sense says no; but in Washington, it is considered "radical" to go against the special interests.
<li>
Should programs that have been tried for twenty years or more in such areas as job training and education and have a record of failure be allowed to continue?  Common sense says no, but in Washington it is "radical" to terminate any program that sounds like it is intended to help children or the poor.
<li>	
Should Medicare be allowed to race towards bankruptcy, when we know how to modernize and transform the system to provide more choice for senior citizens at a lower cost to everyone?  Common sense says no; but by Washington standards, real changes in Medicare are considered "radical."
<li>	
Should a bureaucratic government designed in the 1930s, a government Americans rate as the biggest single threat to the country's future progress, which intrudes increasingly on the freedoms Americans so cherish, which levies taxes so heavy that they kill opportunity and destroy jobs and runs a deficit so high it squeezes out private sector investment -- should such a government be allowed to continue?
</ul>
<p>
Washington's answer is that fundamental change is "too radical."  The people's answer, say the authors of <b>The People's Budget</b>, is that fundamental change is nothing more than common sense.
<p>
In essence, the Federal Government people want is one that stops taking money from people, localities and states to do things that ought to be done, and mostly still are, by people, localities and states.  It is a Federal Government that stops taking on functions which  it performs badly. It is a Federal Government that gets back to the basics: national security; social insurance (Social Security and Medicare); paying interest and paying down the national debt; and, a few other core functions (Treasury, Justice and State Departments).
<p>
The basis for this desire springs from the belief of the American people that the Government in Washington is not in a better position to tell someone in their home town and state how to build roads, educate their children or house their poor. And if the Government in Washington is going to cede control over these activities to their rightful locale, then it makes no sense for the Federal Government to tax people, bring the money to Washington and then send it back -- with or without strings.
<p>
Exactly what do people get from this plan?  They get a Federal Government nearly one-third smaller than today -- the smallest since 1951.  They get the elimination of nearly all Federal excise taxes and a 22 percent cut in income taxes.  They get a government down from today's 22 percent of GDP to 15 percent -- which frees resources to empower communities and the private sector. And, they get a balanced budget by the year 2002.
<p>
But most importantly of all, the American people will restore the American dream.  <b>The People's Budget</b> aims to create a legacy for our children by stopping a financially and morally bankrupt government in Washington from mortgaging our generation and our children's future.
<p>
That is what the five authors propose in the first full-fledged budget of US government ever produced by an independent think tank. It is a "People's Budget" both because the people last November signaled their conviction that the role of Washington should be sharply changed and reduced, and because the plan will bring decision making closer to the people themselves -- to individuals, families, neighborhoods, local governments and state governments, in that order.  The authors emphasized that what they are offering is not merely a list of proposed spending cuts; it is more, even, than a series of proposals.  What the authors have done is develop a full- fledged budget for the United States government:  A complete blueprint for downsizing and transforming the government in Washington into a smaller, more modern, less intrusive, more effective, and much less expensive institution.  The numbers and the economic assumptions add up -- they just add up to less money for the government and more money for the people.
<p>
<p>
<i>In <b>The Strange Death of Liberal England</b> by George Dangerfield, the editors found the following quote describing British Prime Minister Asquith: "In composing his 1909 Budget he was faced with an enormous deficit....The Budget he then contrived came to be known as the "People's Budget," because it aimed a rude blow at the rich, and more especially the Lords."</i>
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>
