</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Privatizing Social Security: Lessons from Chile -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Privatizing Social Security: Lessons from Chile</h2>
<P>
By Mark Klugmann
</center>
<p>
<p>
<P>
 As Americans increasingly question the long-term health of the
Social Security system, they may want to examine how other countries
dealt with problems in their national pension systems. For instance,
in 1980, the government of Chile replaced a bankrupt, government-funded
pension system with a revolutionary innovation:  a privately administered,
national system of mandatory retirement savings.
<P>
 Even before privatizing its steel, electric power, airline, and
telephone companies, this developing South American country had
already transferred its pension system to the private sector.
<P>
 That landmark reform, realized by then-Minister of Labor and
Social Welfare Dr. Jose Pinera, established a model for an increasingly
important global trend:  the private delivery of government-mandated
social services.
<P>
<b>A Private System, Publicly-Regulated</b>
<P>
 Under the Chilean system, the typical worker pays no social security
tax to the state.  Nor, once he retires, does he collect a government-funded
pension.  Instead, during his working life, he automatically deposits
10 percent of his wages each month in an individual investment
account.  This account bears the worker's name, is his property,
and will be used to pay his retirement pension.
<P>
 A worker chooses one of the private Pension Fund Administration
companies (AFP's) to invest his savings.  These companies can
engage in no other activities and are subject to strict government
regulation to guarantee a diversified and low-risk portfolio,
and to prevent theft, fraud or mismanagement.  A separate government
entity was created to provide this oversight. 
<P>
 Unlike most other countries, workers' savings do not enter the
government treasury, nor are they paid out in pensions to already
retired workers (as occurs, for example, in the pay-as-you-go
U.S. Social Security system).  Under the AFP system, the government
does guarantee a minimum pension and does serve as the insurer
of last resort, but those guarantees are funded out of general
revenues, not worker savings.
<P>
 <b>The AFP Company</b>
<P>
 Each AFP operates the equivalent of a mutual fund that invests
in stocks, bonds and government debt.  Although investment decisions
are made by the AFP, government regulation determines which debt
and equity issues are approved for investment and sets maximum
percentage limits both for specific types of instruments and for
the overall mix of the portfolio.  
<P>
 Workers are free to change from one AFP company to another. 
For this reason, there is competition among the companies to provide
a higher return on investment, better customer service or a lower
commission.
<P>
 A worker may contribute up to an additional 10 percent of his
wages to his account each month, as a form of voluntary savings.
 (The first 10 percent of withholding is obligatory on up to U.S.
$20,000 of annual income.) In the branch offices of many AFP's,
there are simplified computer terminals that permit the worker
to calculate his future pension, based on the money in his individual
investment account and the date at which he hopes to retire. The
computer will calcutate how much he must deposit each month to
achieve his retirement income goal and calculate the age at which
he may retire.
<P>
 Worker contributions are free of taxes, as is the AFP investment
account.  Upon retirement, when funds are withdrawn, taxes are
paid, usually at a lower rate.
<P>
 The mandatory savings levels are designed so that the typical
worker will have sufficient money in his AFP account to fund a
pension equal to 70 percent of his final salary, plus survivor's
benefits.
<P>
<P>
<b>Additional Economic Advantages</b>
<P>
 The AFP system solves the typical problem of labor demographics:
 in an aging population the number of workers per retiree decreases.
 With the AFP system of individual retirement accounts, the working
population does not subsidize the retired population.  Thus, in
contrast with the pay-as-you-go system, the potential for inter-generational
conflict is avoided.
<P>
 The problem that many countries face, of unfunded pension liabilities,
does not exist under the AFP system, and instead the economy benefits
from an ever-larger pool of retirement savings available for investment.
<P>
 The system also has the benefit of being fully portable -- the
retirement account is tied to the worker, not the company -- permitting
worker mobility.
<P>
<b>The Results of the AFP System in Chile</b>
<P>
 The Chilean Private Pension System, as of September 1994, managed
an investment fund of U.S. $20,000 million, an unusually large
pool of internally-generated capital for a developing country
of 13 million people and a GDP of U.S. $44,000 million.
<P>
 This long-term investment capital has not only helped fund economic
growth, but also spurred the development of efficient financial
markets and institutions.  The availability of AFP investment
capital made it easier to finance the privatizations of state-owned
enterprises.  In large part due to the effects of the AFP system,
the capitalization of the stock market in Chile equals the GDP,
an extraordinary phenomenon in Latin America.
<P>
 Since the system began to operate on May 1, 1981, the average
return on investment has been 14% per year.  Largely because of
this high return, more than half of new retirees choose to take
early retirement.  At present, six out of seven workers who reach
retirement age have AFP savings that yield pensions in excess
of the government-subsidized minimum.
<P>
 Although pension levels are determined only by contribution levels
and investment performance, pensions under the AFP system have
been significantly higher than under the old, state-administered
system, which required a payroll tax of 25 percent.
<P>
<b>A World Model</b>
<P>
 The success of the Chilean AFP system has been noted by its South
American neighbors, and the system has in the last year been directly
adapted and implemented in Argentina, Peru and Colombia.  (A somewhat
different version is being attempted in Mexico.)  Chilean AFP
companies have entered these markets, linking their knowledge
in joint ventures with local partners and also, in some cases,
with transnational financial companies. 
<P>
 At the level of public policy discussion, the AFP system has
also been advocated in Italy and Spain, and been favorably reviewed
in the economic press in the United States. 
<P>
 Politically, the AFP system has proved popular and has helped
promote social and economic stability.  Workers have a direct
and visible stake in the economy -- they are investors. When the
AFP was inaugurated in Chile in 1981, workers were given the choice
of entering the new AFP system or remaining in the old system.
 Most chose the AFP system, with 500,000 (one fourth of the workforce)
joining in just the first month -- far more than the 50,000 that
had been expected.  Today, more than 90 percent of the workers
who had been under the old system have individually and voluntarily
transferred to the AFP system.
<P>
 As the state pension system disappears, politicians will no longer
decide whether pension checks need be increased, and in what amount,
for which groups.  Thus, pensions are no longer a key source of
political conflict and election-time demagoguery, as they once
were.  A person's retirement income will depend on his own work
and on the success of the economy, not on the government or on
the pressure brought by special interest groups.
<P>
<p>
Mark Klugmann in director of The International Center for Pension
Reform.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
