<html>
<head>
<title>The Moderate Republican Austerity Trap -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>The Moderate Republican Austerity Trap</h2>
<p>
By Pete du Pont
</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The new majority in Congress had a good 100 days.  More importantly, so did the American people with the passage in the House of tax cuts, the line item veto, the balanced budget amendment and real Congressional reform.
<p>
But one of the Republicans' greatest contributions to the future prosperity of the country went largely unnoticed -- the defeat of the disastrous proposal to irrevocably link tax cuts to deficit reduction. Avoiding this moderate Republican austerity trap did more to ensure future prosperity than the tax cuts themselves.
<p>
Understand exactly what the moderates proposed:  that the tax cuts of the Contract With America be suspended -- in effect, repealed -- in any year between now and "2002 and thereafter" (my emphasis) in which deficit targets were not met. 
<p>
The targets were neatly laid out in a statutory table -- $150 billion in 1996, $125 billion in 1997, scaling down to a balanced budget by 2002.  If President Clinton's Office of Management and Budget (OMB) did not annually certify that each of these targets had been met, tax cuts would be repealed and tax rates would jump back up to the 1995 level.  Adding the word "thereafter" ensures that, from here to eternity, no taxes could ever be reduced in a year in which the budget was not in balance to the penny.
<p>
Such an austerity trap is paralyzing, both economically and politically. 
 <p>
First, it removes from the policy debate the idea of tax cuts to stimulate economic growth, a concept used successfully by Presidents from Kennedy to Reagan.  Even liberal economists 
agree that tax reductions can stimulate growth, and most will admit that annual economic growth in the United States -- averaging an anemic 2.1 percent  over  the last 6 years --  is far below the country's potential.  But the moderates' proposal would prohibit using this fiscal tool at all until another fiscal tool -- spending cuts -- has been totally successful.
<p>
Second, it mandates that economic growth is a lesser goal than deficit reduction.  The experience of the 1980s and the foundation of the huge Republican electoral victories of 1980 and 1994 were based on exactly the opposite principle -- that economic growth and job creation are (after sound currency, of course) the first economic priority.
<p>
Third, it assumes that the current federal tax burden -- about 25 percent of the earnings of the average working family -- is appropriate and should be left in place until the administration says otherwise. But as one House Leader said in closing the tax debate in the House, "won't a little less money for the government and a little more money for... families be a good thing?"
<p>
Fourth, the idea of allowing a few faceless economists at OMB to decide the growth rate of the economy, and thus the number of jobs that will be lost or created, is deeply flawed.  Turning the future prosperity of the country over to basement bureaucrats who have the ability to cook the numbers, and are hostile to tax cuts in the first place, is sheer folly.  The collapse of the 70-year Soviet experiment with this philosophy, and the rejection of socialist central planning around the world, should long ago have consigned this idea to the dustbin of history.
<p>
Finally, the idea is wholly impractical.  How can individuals or small business owners  plan for the coming year, not knowing until several months into the year whether their tax obligation will  go up or down?  They can't, because the answer depends upon how much spending the Congress cuts, and then upon whether some bureaucrats agree they have cut enough.
<p>
Politically, the tax cut-deficit reduction linkage is catastrophic.  It is a return to the 
"me-too" liberal Republicanism of the '60s and '70s in which Republicans agreed in bipartisan goodfellowship with Democratic policies in principle (in this case deficit reduction as the primary economic policy), but at slightly less cost  (in this case tax cuts if the deficit is reduced).   It was a politically disastrous formula, dooming Republicans to permanent minority status in the legislative branch of government.  Returning to it now would abandon the Reagan-Gingrich-Contract With America philosophy of economic growth that won the only victories the Republicans have enjoyed in a political lifetime.
<p>
Adoption of this moderate Republican austerity trap would be a dead-end street.  It was beat back during the first 100 days, but the battle is not over.  Liberal Republican Senators lie in wait, hostile to tax reductions and friendly to bigger government.  Whether Republicans drive a stake through the heart of this vampire before it rises again to suck the lifeblood from the economy and the Republicans' 1994 victory will largely tell the tale of the conservative revolution.
<p>
<p>
Pete du Pont, a former Governor of Delaware, is policy chairman of the National Center for Policy Analysis.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>

