<head>
<title>Religion, Politics and Society -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>Religion, Politics and Society</h2></center>
<center>An Interview with Ralph Reed</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<blockquote><center>
<font size= "-1">American Civilization speaks with Ralph Reed, Executive Director of the Christian Coalition, about the broadening public policy interests of evangelicals, about the characterization and reality of evangelicals, and about their goals over the next several years. </center></blockquote></Font>
<p>
<b>AMCIV:</b> Are you worried that by engaging the Christian Coalition in support of the Contract with America or tax issues that you risk being characterized as just another special interest group, no different than business groups or teachers unions who are more interested in economic issues than moral issues?
<p>
<b>REED:</b> Well, I think that there is often a close distinction between what constitutes an economic and what constitutes a moral issue.  I mean, certainly whether or not we're going to continue to run up a national debt that we have no intention of ever paying and saddling our children and grandchildren with 
that debt, is clearly a fiscal issue. But it is a fiscal issue with a moral component. 	Welfare reform ultimately is a cultural and moral issue because it deals with whether or not we're going to subsidize out of wedlock births while discouraging and punishing marriage, work and family.
<p>
I think the issue of tax policy is ultimately a values issue because it reflects the priorities of a society.  If you tax job creation and you tax family formation while subsidizing illegitimacy and subsidizing other forms of social propriety, you are making a values statement as well as a fiscal statement.  
<p>
So I have always felt that the false dichotomy between the moral and cultural agenda on the hand and the fiscal and economic agenda on the other hand was something created by our critics and our foes to marginalize our movement and to confine us to a very narrow band of issues.
<p>
The Christian activists of previous eras never confined themselves to one or two issues.  The Christian progressive of the late 19th and early 20th centuries worked on issues like temperance and integration, and also worked on issues like the progressive income tax and a need for social welfare programs in the inner cities.
<p>
So I believe we have a broad-based agenda.  That broad-based agenda does not mean that we are the holier subsidiary of any political party.  The Contract with America, I believe, is an ultimately bipartisan document.
<p>
And the high level of support of it is enjoyed among the Democratic caucus, I think, 
demonstrates that. 
<p>
<b>AMCIV:</b>  The Christian Coalition is often portrayed by media as having a narrowly defined agenda with one true goal, which is trying to legislate the nation's morals.  How do you respond to that characterization?  Is it accurate, and if not, can you give us an accurate portrait of evangelicals who are active politically?
<p>
<b>REED:</b> Our agenda is to persuade and not to impose.  It is to include and not to exclude.  It is to bring more people into the political process and not reduce the number of people in the political process.  
<p>
We don't want to dominate, but we do want to participate.  We don't want to exclude the minority voice or the women's voice or the union voice or the business voice.  But we do think that those voices need to be enriched by the religious voice and by the moral voice.
<p>	
I don't see that as a left/right issue.  I think whether it's the Children's Defense Fund quoting Old Testament prophets to talk about caring for the least among us, or Martin Luther King invoking his religious beliefs to condemn segregation, or the Christian Coalition bringing its values to bear on issues that concern it, these are all part of a long and cherished history of religion being one of the brightest tapestries in the texture of American politics.
<p>
<b>AMCIV:</b> The dominant political motto in our society currently is that pro-active government help isn't going to work, that government has failed to solve our nation’s problems and even maybe exacerbating them. Many people are turning elsewhere for solutions, including religion and religious organizations.  What role do you see for religion or religious revival or a searching for spiritualism to help address some of the problems America faces? 
<p>
<b>REED:</b>  Well, I think the ultimate answer to what ails America is going to be spiritual and cultural renewal and not government policies.  We should not try to replace the social engineering of the left over the last 30 years with the social engineering of religious conservatives.  What we ought to be trying to do is not impose our values or Bill Clinton's values.
<p>	
Try to get the federal government out of our lives and out of our pockets and out of our 
homes, so that we can begin to live our own values that we cherish and celebrate in our homes, churches and synagogues.  
<p>
So I think politics ultimately is a relatively small part of the total picture.
<p>
<b>AMCIV:</b> The 100 days of the Contract with America is almost up.  Looking at the longer term, the next 1,000 days or the next several years, what more needs to be done in the political arena to allow the faithful to truly live free lives? 
<p>
<b>REED:</b>  I think after the 100 days we need to more dramatically reduce the role of government.  We need to look at taking entire Cabinet departments and their bureaucracies that are centered in Washington and ship them back to communities, and take the tax dollars that are then saved and apply them to the deficit.  
<p>	
I think the second thing we have to do is we have to secure religious liberty and freedom of conscience for every American, not only for school children desiring to pray in public schools, but also for communities that want to honor and celebrate their religious beliefs in their communities -- nativity scenes on courthouse lawns.  
<p>	
I think we also need to more dramatically reduce the role of the welfare state in our lives.  I think clearly reforming Aid to Families with Dependent Children is a step in the right direction, but we need to look at the full range of entitlement programs, and ask ourselves at every turn whether these needs couldn't be better met by families, by private charities and by churches and synagogues in the faith community.
<p>	
I think we are prepared at the Christian Coalition to issue a challenge to the faith community, that it isn't just a question of these needs being met more efficiently by private individuals.  It is our moral duty and obligation to meet those needs and not turn them over to a government bureaucracy.
<p>	
It is a symptom of our own failure as a faith community that the government has assumed these responsibilities that we should have been carrying all along.  
<p>
<b>AMCIV:</b> If we agree that the federal government should get out of welfare and turn it over to local community groups, private organizations, church organizations, what do you do with the church/state issue?  Because a lot of people are going to say well, these church groups are going to try and help people in their community, but they can't preach, which in a sense, guts those programs of their effectiveness.
<p>
<b>REED:</b>  No, I think that we certainly should not create a situation where the government is subsidizing the propagation of a particular theology.  On the other hand, if a government program provides that a voucher for an individual religion need can be redeemed at a private charity that does not have a religious or theological foundation, it seems to me that that same voucher could be redeemed at a church or a synagogue without violating the historical distinction between church and state.
<p>
We allow people under the GI Bill to go to state universities or to institutions that are church-related.  It seems to me that doing this through the welfare program would be no different.  The aid should be to the individual, the voucher or the aid, and then they go to whatever institution best meets their needs.
 <p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>

