<html>
<head>
<title>If We Believe in the Declaration, We’ve Got to Transform our Culture -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>If We Believe in the Declaration, We've Got to Transform our Culture</h2></center>
<center>By Newt Gingrich</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Americans can no longer escape the reality that three decades of social welfare 
policies have failed, condemning too many of our fellow citizens to lives of despair.  Most Americans want a more compassionate society that will help the truly needy. They want to replace the current welfare system not just to save money, but to create a system that really helps people.
<p>
To accomplish this end will require replacing the culture of poverty and violence 
with a culture of productivity and safety. It is not just helping the poor or focusing on the 
inner cities, but the replacement of one culture with another.
<p>
Efforts to repair or improve the current welfare system are doomed to fail because 
they misunderstand the holistic nature of the problem. In a holistic model, everything 
within the model has to be taken into account.  But in a reductionist model, you attempt to break a problem down into a series of building blocks, deciding which piece you want to 
deal with first.  There’s a very big difference between the two; in the holistic model, every 
piece depends on the other pieces -- if you don’t deal with the totality, it does not work.
<p>
Piecemeal efforts to repair our system and its culture of poverty and violence are 
irrelevant and doomed to fail.  Every time we say, "Well, let’s do a specific small piece, 
because at least we will make progress," we are wrong. You will have no impact at all, or virtually no impact.  The culture of poverty and violence is so powerful that if you try to change one piece of it, the whole rest of it will thwart your efforts.
<p>
We say, "why don’t you go to work?"  And you say, "Fine."  And so we find out 
that if you go to work, you lose Medicaid. One of your children gets sick, you promptly 
lose all the money you just worked for. What we have is an interlocking system, in which 
to change any one piece without thinking through the change of the whole doesn’t get you 
anywhere.
<p>
To replace the whole culture of violence and poverty, we must address four key 
realities which define any solution to the problems.
<p>
<b>New Beliefs for New Behavior</b>
<p>
The first reality is that when individuals are caught within a dysfunctional culture, 
they must transfer their loyalties, beliefs and behaviors to another culture to truly change their behavior.  For instance, Alcoholics Anonymous is a conversion experience.  They say, yesterday, I was an active alcoholic.  Today, I am a recovering alcoholic.  Yesterday, when I felt anxiety-ridden, I took a drink.  Today, when I feel anxiety-ridden, I go to my AA meeting and talk to my friends, or I pray -- but there is a conscious effort to rebuildthe entire person and to recognize that the transition to this system from another system is a decisive moment. If you don’t have a support structure, if you don’t have something which helps you when you start to slide back, you’re going to break down.
<p>
<b>Without Money But Not Poor</b>
<p>
Samuel Goldwyn wrote a book about growing up in a low-income community in 
which two different cultures exist side by side in the same neighborhood among people of the same income level.  It is not a circumstance of money.  Being without money and being poor are two different things.
<p>
This is the core problem we’re faced with because we have confused these two 
distinctions.  This is what Samuel Goldwyn wrote about his childhood:
<p>
"Where else on earth among the poorest people did you see in every home a blue 
and white box where you were supposed to drop your pennies? Once a week, an old 
woman would come around and empty it, and off it would go somewhere overseas.  The poorest of the poor helping still poorer ones across the Atlantic somewhere. Hundreds of sweat shop employees, men and women who sat at machines for nine and 10 hours a day, came home, washed up, had supper, and went to the lodge hall or settlement houses to learn English or to listen to a fellow read poetry to them. I saw workers, welfare workers, scribes, teachers, philosophers, all hoping and striving for one goal, to break away.  And they did too.  America gave them all hope in life, and they repaid America."  
<p>
Goldwyn is talking about people who worked all day and then took a couple of 
pennies, maybe an hour’s work, to go and pay the poet reader at the community center to give them part of their soul as well as food.  This was the real world.  
<p>
This is not mythical.  This is not some theory.  This was America at the turn of the century.  
<p>
This description begins to make vivid the healthy world of being without money 
which led to two generations of strength, versus the unhealthy world of being without 
money which has led to two generations of disaster.
<p>
<b>One Person at a Time</b>
<p>
<p>Part of the reason it is hard for us to really change things is that we underestimate 
the second reality: cultural change is very hard.  It requires tremendous persistence over time, and can often only be achieved one person at a time.  I think part of what happens tous is we say, "Okay, I’m willing to do this for up to a year and a half."  That’s a little bit like a farmer who says, "I’ll grow corn as long as it makes it in three weeks. If it doesn’t make it in three weeks, I’m throwing that sucker out and replanting."
<p>
To break through in a culture and to get people to start dramatically changing their 
behavior means getting to enough individuals by starting with one person, and then two and then three, and then gradually beginning to peel away the whole culture.
<p>
<b>Government’s Role</b>
<p>
The third reality is that this kind of cultural change is best done outside 
government.  And I would argue that with the exception of the military’s boot camps, 
there is virtually no government program that gets the level of cultural change you need inside government for the very reason that governments are poor agencies of 
acculturation.
<p>
Americans should be furious when some bureaucrat tries to acculturate them.  You 
should say, wait a second, I pay taxes.  Who are you to tell me whether I ought to be in 
the circle or the square?  Are you nuts?  You work for me.  I don’t work for you.  And so you would have a very hard time ever getting an agreement for cultural change delivered by government.
<p>
The kind of cultural change we are talking about requires missionaries.  It requires 
the person who will sit there at 3:00 o’clock in the morning holding the hand of the person who is about to commit suicide.  Yes, there are some wonderful government employees.  You find people who are individually fabulous, but you can’t recruit to a bureaucracy on 
the premise you’ll stay there as long as they need you.  You can recruit to a volunteer 
organization on that premise.  Very different models.  And so we sometimes get mad at the bureaucracy, because we ask it to do things it can’t do, instead of being more careful about what government can do well and what other parts of society can do better.
<p>	
I would argue that government and politicians have found the first three realities of 
cultural replacement unacceptable.  They have, therefore, tried to find piecemeal short-
term improvements that at least meet their political needs and the public’s desire to get something done. Thus for 30 years they’ve engaged in a series of underfinanced, short-sighted, small efforts that have failed.
<p>
<b>A New Way of Life</b>
<p>
To truly make a difference, we must move people out of this culture of violence 
and poverty and into a better culture.  This is the fourth reality, that the cultural change 
must be from one way of life to another.  Individual changes within the old culture are 
often overwhelmed by other aspects of the culture. We must make clear that a culture of poverty and violence is not acceptable.  There are millions of Americans who live in that culture right now. What we are saying to them is, look, it is better to work than to be dependent.  It is better to be safe than to be in danger.
<p>
Now, the word "better" is very argumentative.  Some argue that, who are we to 
start imposing what would once have been called middle-class, bourgeois virtues on 
others? The only good answer is, we have already tried a technique of dealing with 
violence and poverty, and we can’t stand the result that we see on television.  We cannot stand the pain we’re inflicting on the children.  We cannot stand the 4-year-old being thrown off the tenement house balcony. 
<p>
People are becoming susceptible to what I call "compassion exhaustion."  Their system, despite their best efforts, has never quite worked. Now they’re terribly disappointed.  They ought to be optimistic. The reason is that in America, very powerful reform movements can emerge very quickly and can have a very powerful impact. 
<p>
We went from the Montgomery Boycott of buses in 1955 to the Civil Rights Acts 
of 1964 and 1965 in 10 years.  You can quickly get to a catalytic moment.  We can 
suddenly begin to have real change very fast. You see this by looking back at American History.  The great American reform movements starting with the Great Awakening of the 
1730’s, the Revolutionary Generation, the Jeffersonians, the Jacksonians, the 
Abolitionists, the founding of the Republican Party, and the Progressive Movement were almost all in a 5 to 10- year cycle from beginning, to the process of speeding, to 
consolidation.  In the more modern era, you had the New Deal, which did most of its best work in about five years.
<p>
<b>The Pursuit of Happiness</b>
<p>
Although we may be on the cusp of a great movement to replace our culture of 
violence and poverty, we’ve got to be very cautious, because this is not a simple thing; it is very hard.  We have failed at it so far because we keep trying to reduce it to a level of simplicity that will make it easy.  It isn’t, and it won’t be.  
<p>
Let me also suggest that the vision we want to establish is that every American is 
endowed by their creator with certain inalienable rights, among which are life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness.  If we actually mean that sentence as our vision, we must add a second sentence: "We owe it to every American citizen to grow-up in a culture and system which ensures their God-given rights and responsibilities as full citizens."  The key here is "every American."  We all sort of say it.  But are we really determined to live it out?  Are we really determined to say every child born in 1995 should absolutely grow up in that kind of framework?  That is a big order.
<p>
To accomplish this goal, we need three really simple principles, visionary 
principles. Every citizen is an American. Every neighborhood is part of America. Every 
child is an American child. The moment we accept that, we have to say to ourselves:  This is a big challenge. We cannot avoid it.  Because every time a child dies for lack of prenatal care or a child gets killed in a drive-by shooting or a child ends up in a room where they are not going to learn anything, we have failed at our vision-level commitment that every American has the right to pursue happiness.
<p>
What we have done is basically cut a deal with the poor.  We said, starting in the 
late 1960’s, we’ll maintain you.  We’ll send you money.  Perhaps being selfish middle-
class people, we never sent enough money, but the theory was, we’ll send you money.  
We will not demand you change your behavior.  You want to have your kids born in total ignorance?  It would be inappropriate for us to interfere.  You want to go to a local school that doesn’t work?  Well, at least it’s not a school we send our kids to.  So we’ll give lip service to changing it, but the truth is, we won’t change it.  We’ll just have study commissions that will say, yes, they should do better. What we have all allowed to happen over a 30-year period is people who do not have what the Declaration of Independence guarantees them. To do that, you’ve got to, for example, reestablish safety.  Any American who’s physically threatened is being cheated of the constitutional provision to provide for the common security.  Because danger is domestic as well as foreign.
<p>
This is, again, one of the things we keep kidding ourselves about.  If we truly want 
healthy inner cities, if we truly want healthy Indian reservations, and if we truly want 
healthy West Virginia Appalachian poor neighborhoods, we are talking about a big 
change.  This is not a small change.  This is one of the largest changes in American 
history.  And we just don’t take it seriously.  We pay lip service to it. We walk off and 
when a kid gets killed we say, "That’s sad."  And what I am suggesting is, if we take that child seriously as an American and we take the Declaration and the Constitution seriously, then we must decide in our generation that we are fed up with it and we’re  going to actually shoulder our responsibility as a country. All of us, including the poor, are making this transition, we are taking on a big challenge.  Maybe in some ways as big as the Cold War.  It’s not going to be a small challenge and it’s not going to happen overnight. 
<p>
<p>
Newt Gingrich is Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
