</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>America’s Manufacturing Revolution: The New Economy -- PFF</title>
</head>
<center><h2>America's Manufacturing Revolution:  The New Economy</h2></center>
<center>By Jerry Jasinowski</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Picture in your mind’s eye two different scenes. The first is America in 1985. 
America was on the defensive on the economic front. Industry after industry, company after company, was losing global market share. Foreign products were pouring into America. The quality of American products was scoffed at.  "Made in Japan" had gone from a joke in the 1960s to being the standard in the 1980s. It seemed clear -- America was losing the battle in global competition.  The second scene is America in 1995. America is on the offensive on the economic front.  Industry after industry, company after company, have been gaining global market share. A record amount of American products are being sold abroad. The high quality of American products is widely recognized.  "Made in America" is becoming the new standard. It is clear -- America is now on the road to winning the battle in global competition.
<p>
That is a startling difference in just one decade. How could the situation change so 
dramatically and so quickly?  In particular, what did companies in America do to generate this turnaround and comeback?  
<p>	
The answers to these questions center on the biggest economic transformation taking 
place in America today:   the manufacturing revolution. I use the term "revolution"  because over the past ten years manufacturing companies across America have been undergoing a transformation on a scale not seen since the Industrial Revolution of the 1800s.
<p>
Instead of declining, as some pundits predicted, American manufacturing has, by a broad collection of measures, become #1. 
<p>
America is #1 in exports. Our double digit rate of export growth exceeds our competitors and we have expanded our world market share.  America is #1 in productivity. A Brookings Institution study found that productivity in German manufacturing was 86 percent of that in the United States while Japanese productivity was an even lower 78 percent.  Finally, America is #1 in many key industrial sectors that are among the most important to long term growth, such as 
computer systems and computer software.
<p>		
The intriguing question is:  How did America regain the overall number one 
ranking in competitiveness and all these other number one positions?
<p>
Certainly, government policies contributed to the competitive comeback, particularly the move to more competitive exchange rates, monetary and fiscal policy, and the strong commitment to open trade policies that expand global exports. But positive government policies are only a modest part of the story. In most cases,  government policies have done more to harm American competitiveness than to help it. Witness the damaging impact of crushing regulatory and legal burdens. 
<p>		
To understand America’s economic comeback, you must understand the bold and 
innovative changes taking place in the private sector; you must understand America’s 
manufacturing revolution.
<p>
<b>Manufacturing Revolution</b>
<p>
Let me begin by sharing with you my first hand exposure to the inside story of this 
revolution. For two years, economic consultant Robert Hamrin and I went searching for the best success stories among American manufacturers of all shapes and sizes. After examining over 200 such stories, it became clear that something major was occurring - that all the success stories pointed to a manufacturing revolution that goes far beyond incremental and isolated corporate changes. We wrote a book about the revolution, "Making It in America", which identifies ten Paths to Success that these pacesetter companies are following. 
<p>	
This revolution is as profound as the original industrial revolution of the last century, but its different in nature. The industrial  Revolution was about doing everything on a bigger and bigger scale -- more resources, more capital and labor, lager scale production -- these were the elements that drove growth. Today, we are looking at a productivity-led revolution where growth is achieved primarily by greater technological advance and doing more with less. This historic departure radically changes how products are made and the economy operates. 
<p>
Let me highlight six of the ten paths to success that we uncovered in our research:  
leadership in managing change; total quality management; investment and use of information technologies; employee empowerment; innovation in product development and service; and, going global.
<p>
<b>Leadership in Managing Change</b>
<p>
I  begin with leadership in managing change because that is where significant corporate transformation almost always begins:  with true leaders  who have a vision and passion. The vision makes clear where the company should go and what its focus should be. The passion makes certain that the vision is achieved. 
<p>	
One such leader in America is Jack Welch, the Chairman of GE. Listen to how this leader thinks:  "If your change isn’t big enough, revolutionary enough, the bureaucracy can beat you. When you get leaders who confuse popularity with leadership, who just nibble away at things, nothing changes."
<p>
The bedrock of America’s manufacturing renaissance involves corporate leaders 
recognizing and acting on a fundamental truth:  there must be a balance between business basics and embracing constant innovation to manage change. That dynamic tension between two powerful forces is a tough one to balance. But the truly successful company will, over the long run,  build upon a foundation of basic values, such as understanding what business you are in, while at the same time being boldly innovative and entrepreneurial.
<p>
<b>Total Quality Management</b>
<p>
The focus on cutting costs led to a renewed emphasis on all aspects of quality ... quality of products first, and quality of the company second. Concepts like Total Quality Control with its 
stress on the customers and doing things right the first time was the first step companies took to 
become competitive. This led to a more revolutionary  way of thinking, called Total Quality 
Management, or TQM, which forced a whole new way of doing business by striving to eliminate 
all waste in corporations and striving for continuous improvement.
<p>	
Motorola is of course the classic corporate example of applying TQM techniques. Their 
excellent implementation produced cost savings of at least $5 billion for the period 1987-1993.
<p>
<b>Investment and Use of Information Technologies</b>
<p>  
The third revolutionary path to success is investment and use of information technologies. 
The investment figures tell the story. Nearly half of business spending on equipment is for 
computers and other information technologies. And that doesn’t even include the billions of 
dollars that companies spend on software and programmers each year. This investment has helped 
to greatly boost company productivity and create whole new systems of manufacturing.
<p>
The deployment of  these technologies has transformed the American factory. Many 
factories now possess unprecedented  speed in the production process, which has greatly 
improved products. At the same time these factories can now engage in agile manufacturing 
which gives them the flexibility  they need to meet customers’ rapid and ever changing demands.
<p>	
Some manufacturers are already moving beyond agile manufacturing to mass 
customization. This is the ability to customize products literally in quantities as small as one while 
producing them at mass production speeds. The ultimate outcome, fast approaching, is 
simultaneous manufacturing, where even as the customer is giving the order, the product starts to 
be made. The trend is clear:  the mass production paradigm of the Industrial Age is being replaced 
by the mass customization paradigm of the Information Age.
<p>
<b>Employee Empowerment</b>
<p>
The fourth path to success is employee empowerment. Many companies have been smart 
enough to recognize that people -- their workers --  are their most valuable resource. That is why 
they have unleashed the full power of their workers, under such names as employee involvement, 
participative management, and employee empowerment. 
<p>
When you think of employee empowerment, you should think of the three "T" words:  
trust, teams and training.  Employee empowerment requires trust.  It is built around trust - trust 
that is two way:  bosses trusting employees and employees trusting bosses.  Teams are among the 
renaissance’s most widespread and powerful elements.  In 1980, virtually all manufacturing 
employees worked on their own.  Today, millions of workers are working together in teams.  
Teams are so effective because they boost employee morale and teamed employees more readily 
take it upon themselves to focus on customer satisfaction and product quality.  Training of 
workers is increasingly being recognized as an investment for the future, not a cost.
<p>
<b>Innovation in Product Development and Service</b>
<p>
The fifth path that successful companies stress is innovation in all aspects of 
manufacturing, but particularly in new product development and service. Since a top quality 
product has become a "given", the real challenge today is product innovation. If you want to 
grow, speed and creativity in new product development is the most effective way to get there.
<p>
But even developing new products is often not enough. American manufacturers have 
discovered the critical importance of product delivery and service to their customers. Customer 
satisfaction is no longer enough. Rather, a company must "delight", or "please", or "surprise" its 
customers. They are doing this through getting to know their customers in great detail, providing 
them with superior service, and getting them involved in their product development decisions.
<p>
<b>Going Global</b>
<p>
Finally, for companies interested in growth, they have to go out and find new customers in new markets. The main way American companies have done this in the last decade is by going 
global. 
<p>
Even small companies, for the first time ever, are well represented among exporters:  over 
half of U.S. companies with revenues less than $100 million exported products in 1993, up 
sharply from 30 percent in 1990. American companies are also investing abroad quite heavily. 
<p>
The results are clear. Companies that have gone global in a serious manner find that it is a 
driving force behind corporate growth, with foreign sales accounting for 40 percent to 90 percent 
of their total revenues.
<p>
<b>Meeting Today’s Challenges </b>
<p>
The first requirement is a healthy dose of humility. We got into trouble in the past by being 
arrogant. In today’s rapidly changing, highly competitive world, that’s more risky than ever. At 
the very least, in both government and the private sector, we have to be prepared to engage 
ourselves in improving each day.
<p>
So what should be our top priority?  It’s clear that our top economic priority must be 
maintaining and expanding economic growth, providing employment and improving standards of living. If we want innovative, market economies to succeed we must provide economic 
prosperity.
<p>
On the international front, this means that the main responsibility of national governments 
must be an ongoing commitment to open trade. They must work hard to get the newly established World Trade Organization off to a good start and to effectively implement the many changes established in the latest Uruguay Round. They must also act to reduce barriers to trade that still exist and develop a stronger investment code. Most importantly, the business community needs to educate their workers and the public that expanding trade produces jobs.
<p>
On the domestic economic front, we need national governments initiating revolutions in the way government is run. They should look to key lessons learned from the manufacturing revolution that has taken place in America. The goal should be to make government as efficient and effective as possible. Following corporate examples, they should first listen to their customers 
about what they want, and what they think of the quality of their current products.  But the main action will, and should, take place in companies in the private sector. They are the basic engines of growth. Business leaders around the world, many of them gathered in this 
assembly, will face two fundamental challenges:   to continually improve and to nurture our 
people.
<p>
In the future, the key to maintaining good corporate performance will be to never rest on 
success. Companies in the past would set goals, either performance goals or specific action goals, and when they were obtained they would rest. Many would become complacent. Relentless global competition will not allow such resting in the future. As Andy Grove, CEO of Intel, has said: "only the paranoid survive."
<p>
Companies focused on continuous improvement will also recognize that they cannot rest 
on just efficient operations and strong productivity growth. Rather, they must turn their attention 
to growth. This will involve focusing on exciting new product development, discovering new 
markets, and going global, both through increased exports and direct investment overseas.
<p>
The second challenge -- nurturing people -- flows from the Information Revolution that is 
rapidly shaping a knowledge society in many countries around the world. Here, the one 
fundamental fact that must always be borne in mind is that most of the value in a business is 
generated by the energy from peoples intellect and creativity. The best companies of the 21st 
century will stay ahead by freeing their workers from the command and control organization of 
the past, investing in their expanding learning and regarding good performance with incentives 
and profit sharing. 
<p>
Continually improving and constantly nurturing people. These two corporate mandates 
will not be easy ones to implement. They will take many business leaders and  companies well out of their comfort zones. But they are the absolute imperatives for success in today’s global economy. 
<p>
<p>
Jerry Jasinowski is President of the National Association of Manufacturers, his most recent book, with Robert Hamrin, is Making It in America:  Proven Paths to Success from 50 Top Companies.
 <p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
