<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Intro (Drugs & Biologics)-- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<P><br>
<h3><FONT >DRUGS AND BIOLOGICS</FONT></h3>
<P>
<FONT >The goal of the proposal is to speed the delivery
of safe and effective new drugs and biologics to patients who
need them.  To achieve this goal requires changes in the regulatory
system that will facilitate early clinical research, increase
the efficiency of drug development and its regulatory oversight,
and reduce the overall time and cost required for a new drug to
reach the market. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There has been broad consensus for nearly three
decades that reforms of the current system are necessary.  Numerous
official panels and inquiries have proposed remedies, but they
have not been implemented expeditiously or widely.  The present
proposal embodies the most important and consistently repeated
of these recommendations:  management and structural reforms that
transfer tasks currently performed internally by FDA to outside
experts and organizations.  While FDA has at one time or another
delegated most of its review and evaluation functions to outside
experts or entities, this delegation has been piecemeal and disorganized;
partial privatization has never been integrated in a way that
could create an efficient overall system.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Other reforms recommended repeatedly by blue
ribbon panels have included a lesser role for FDA in the scrutiny
of early-phase clinical investigations and the wider use of accelerated
approvals coupled with continued post-market surveillance.  The
proposal adopts these recommendations, explicitly or implicitly.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The proposal rationalizes and enhances the
efficiency of the process for developing, reviewing and approving
new drugs and biologics by assigning principal review responsibilities
to government-certified <I>Drug Certification Bodies</I> (DCBs).
 At the same time, <I>the proposal maintains the existing legal
requirement for pre-market demonstration of safety and effectiveness</I>.
 Preserved as well are FDA's oversight, enforcement powers and
the agency's authority to issue the final sign-off approval for
product marketing.  Key elements in the process are outlined below
and in Figure 1.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>


<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >KEY PROPOSALS FOR DRUGS AND BIOLOGICS
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI><FONT >The primary responsibility for managing
the Investigational New Drug (IND) filing, oversight of the clinical
program, and New Drug Application (NDA)/Product License Application
(PLA) review will be transferred from the FDA to nongovernmental
Drug Certification Bodies (DCBs).</FONT>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><FONT >The DCBs, which can be profit-making or
non-profit organizations, will be subject to FDA certification
and staffed -- as required by the language of the Food, Drug,
and Cosmetic Act -- by the necessary &quot;experts qualified by
scientific training and experience.&quot;  </FONT>
</UL>
<UL>
<LI><FONT >The sponsor will submit NDAs (or PLAs)
to the DCB, not to FDA.  After evaluating the NDA, the DCB will
submit a summary of the results of its review (if favorable) to
FDA.  The FDA Commissioner then has a designated period of time
to accept the DCB's recommendation for approval (which, legally,
is a &quot;rebuttable presumption&quot;) or to deny approval.</FONT>
</UL>
<UL>
<LI><FONT >If approval is denied, then at the discretion
of the sponsor and the DCB, a review by an independent Medical
Review Board, reporting to the Secretary of Health and Human Services,
may be undertaken.  All parties, including the FDA, are expected
to accept the decision of the Secretary.</FONT>
</UL>
<UL>
<LI><FONT >FDA will continue to administer the present
national system of pharmacovigilance, above the level of the DCB.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00001.GIF"><FONT >The plan reforms will
stimulate competition to supply drug-development oversight and
review services;  that is, DCBs will compete for sponsor-clients.
 This competition will encourage DCBs to identify and solve problems
early and rapidly, perform reviews in a timely manner, and manage
the oversight and review efficiently.  The system will favor DCBs
that offer the greatest expertise, the best service and a reputation
for integrity.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The crafting of drug development and approval
strategies will benefit from competitive pressures on DCBs, because
there is much room for innovation:  the choice of factors such
as clinical endpoints, indications for approval, and regimes of
pre-clinical and clinical testing, ultimately drives the size,
time and cost of development programs; and, there is large potential
for savings in these areas.  Subject to the law's standards of
effectiveness and safety, DCBs will be free - and competitive
pressures will encourage them - to devise new and more efficient
ways of developing drugs and meeting the approval standards. 
This strategic competition and synergy between sponsors and DCBs
will transform the drug development and approval process and will
reverse the relentless spiral of rising time and costs. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
