</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Intro (Devices)-- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<P>
<P>
<h3>MEDICAL DEVICES</h3>
<P>
<FONT >The plan for medical devices will in large
part follow the European Union's medical device regulatory system,
which is characterized by reliance on clear and objective standards
that are largely implemented by private, non-governmental organizations.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Under the EU system, all medical devices are
classified, using objective criteria, into one of four classes
(I, IIa, IIb, and III) representing increasing levels of risk
and complexity.  Devices may be marketed only if they conform
with a comprehensive series of <I>essential requirements</I>.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >As is the case in the EU, implementation of
the proposed system will involve the interaction of three groups:
 manufacturers, who bear the ultimate responsibility for their
products; private Device Certifying Bodies (DCBs), engaged by
manufacturers to provide independent certification of critical
manufacturing processes and products; and, the federal authority
(FDA), which maintains responsibility for public safety by ensuring
the competence of the DCBs, enforcing compliance with law and
maintaining a universal system of postmarketing surveillance.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Review under the new system should be expeditious
because competitive forces will only tolerate DCBs that are responsive
to the market.  The current system has been characterized by such
slow approvals that important products are not available.  Domestically,
venture capital has become scarce and manufacturers have been
forced to relocate critical operations offshore.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Because device innovation is often characterized
by many small incremental changes, a method of rapid certification
of new products is needed in order for U.S. Manufacturers not
to fall further and further behind.  For Class I devices, the
new proposal permits manufacturers to self-certify conformance
with the essential requirements.  In addition, manufacturers who
maintain a total quality assurance system may self-certify new
Class IIa and IIb products between the periodic audits by their
DCB.  Key elements of the proposal are summarized  below and in
Figures 2 and 3.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >KEY PROPOSALS FOR DEVICES<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI><FONT >Manufacturers can ensure conformance with
the essential requirements by adhering to relevant internationally
agreed upon objective standards.  The manufacturer generally will
have a choice of methods, and will be able to either demonstrate
conformance of its<I> quality assurance systems</I> or conformance
of the <I>product</I> itself.  Combinations of these two routes
are permitted. </FONT>
<LI><FONT >For all classes of devices except Class
I, a DCB must audit the manufacturer periodically to confirm such
conformance.  The stringency of the audit and the number of areas
audited depend on the class.  The FDA's current auditing of manufacturers
for Good Manufacturing Practices will be replaced by the DCB's
certification of the manufacturer's quality assurance systems.
 Such certification will often exceed FDA standards as it could
include certification of design quality assurance.  It will also
be performed far more frequently than current FDA inspections.</FONT>
<LI><FONT >Class III products always require premarketing
<I>design approval</I> by a DCB.  Although not part of the EU
system, the proposal presented here also requires the FDA to be
notified 90 days prior to marketing a Class III product, to allow
time for the FDA to elect to review the appropriateness of the
certification process.</FONT>
<LI><FONT >All manufacturers will be required to have
a system for monitoring and acting upon reports of a device malfunction
after sale.  In addition, the FDA will act as a central repository
of such information when it involves a threat to patient safety,
as it is in a position to monitor the investigation of such events,
especially when they involve similar situations arising with several
manufacturers.  The FDA may, for cause, require that a device
be withdrawn from the market if the manufacturer has not ensured
that it meets the essential requirements or if the DCB has not
acted competently.  In addition, criminal charges may be brought
in the case of fraud or criminal negligence.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00002.GIF"><IMG SRC="IMG00003.GIF">
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >THE MEDICAL REVIEW BOARD</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Current FDA procedures do not provide an adequate
independent forum in which to appeal agency decisions.  Our proposal
remedies this deficiency by establishing an independent, standing
committee of experts within Health and Human Services - the Medical
Review Board (MRB) - to advise the HHS Secretary when FDA disagrees
with a DCB's product approval recommendation.  The MRB will have
approximately 10- to-15 members representing a wide spectrum of
scientific, medical and regulatory expertise.  It will hear appeals
of FDA decisions to overturn a DCB recommendation, and will advise
the Secretary.  All parties, including FDA, will be expected to
accept the decision of the Secretary.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >LIABILITY<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I><B><FONT >DCB Liability</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT >The proposed system will provide the Drug and
Device Certifying Bodies with strong incentives to operate carefully
and responsibly.  DCBs will be subject to FDA oversight and the
possibility of losing their certification if they do not follow
applicable regulatory guidelines.  They also will be subject to
tort liability for negligence in carrying out their obligations.
 Finally, DCBs will be subject to lawsuits from manufacturers
for breaking contractual obligations.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The DCBs should not, however, be liable for
factors beyond their control.  It is, therefore, important to
formalize the current recognition by the courts that such certification
bodies not be subject to strict liability to third parties injured
by products.  Otherwise, particularly in the context of joint
and several liability, many responsible institutions will be reluctant
to enter the certification market for fear that their very existence
will be threatened by tort liability suits that might be completely
unrelated to the manner in which they carried out their obligations.
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT >Manufacturer Liability</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT >Our plan also addresses the tort liability
status of pharmaceuticals and medical devices firms more generally.
 Liability costs have disproportionately burdened these industries,
largely because their products are intrinsically involved in life
and death situations.  In fact, major lines of litigation, such
as those involving DES and the Dalkon Shield, have come to be
almost synonymous with the liability crisis.  The potential liability
exposure faced by these industries has discouraged new product
innovation, particularly for products related to pregnancy and
childbirth.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >At the current time, there is insufficient
recognition by the courts of the extensive role played by government
regulation in ensuring efficient levels of safety for pharmaceuticals
and medical devices.  To the extent that the current FDA regulations
do achieve socially efficient control of risk, superimposing tort
liability in addition to regulation is harmful, by deterring introduction
of beneficial new products.  Therefore, the proposal includes
a regulatory compliance defense for all product liability, not
simply a defense against punitive damages.<B><sup><a href="foot.html">|</a></sup> <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The regulatory compliance defense simply recognizes
that, by negotiating the regulatory process, the manufacturer
has fulfilled its requirements with respect to the provision of
products that provide an appropriate level of safety, and that
the government has certified this fact.  Juries should not be
second guessing decisions regarding product safety that have already
been recognized by government agencies as having achieved appropriate
levels of safety.  The plan for reforming the FDA drug and device
approval processes would not limit the applicability of this defense,
because there would continue to be a regulatory mechanism to ensure
that an appropriate level of product safety is provided to consumers.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >OFF-LABEL USE<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The slowness of the FDA process for approving
new uses for products already on the market deprives patients
and their doctors of critically important information for long
periods of time - long after the scientific evidence is available
that a treatment may be beneficial for a particular condition.
 The proposal will make the &quot;off-label&quot; issue less salient,
by lowering the costs and increasing the benefits for manufacturers
who obtain supplementary approvals for their products.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Currently, the FDA does not give supplementary
applications a high priority and sponsors have a limited incentive
to submit them.  Under the proposed system, DCBs will have the
incentive and the resources to process supplementals efficiently
and in a timely manner.  Supplemental approvals for devices will
particularly be facilitated, because manufacturers with the requisite
quality assurance certification will be able to self-certify label
changes (subject to the usual monitoring by the DCB).  Another
major incentive to submit applications for supplemental approvals
will be provided by the regulatory compliance tort liability defense,
which will be available only to products used in approved ways.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >INTERNATIONAL HARMONIZATION<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >A major premise of the proposal is that the
current system for bringing drugs and medical devices to market
suffers because the FDA represents the only route to market. 
Therefore, permitting alternative routes is healthy for the entire
system, and one way to do this is to encourage &quot;jurisdictional
competition&quot; from foreign approval systems.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This can most easily be done by permitting
products approved in jurisdictions whose standards are similar
to those in the United States - for example, the Great Britain
or the European Union - to have the same status as a product approved
by a DCB in the United States.  Where applicable (i.e., for drugs
and Class III devices), products with foreign approvals could
be submitted to the FDA for U.S. marketing approval under the
same procedures and with the same presumptive approvability as
a DCB-approved product.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Because it is based on standards and procedures
virtually identical to those of the European Union, adoption of
the proposed device system would, by itself,  substantially further
the goal of regulatory harmonization.  This system would make
it possible for a manufacturer to obtain both American and European
approval using the same documentation and inspections, and the
services of a single organization that could be certified both
as an American DCB and a European &quot;notified body.&quot; 
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >TRANSITION<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >A transition period of at least several years
will be needed to establish procedures to accredit DCBs and to
permit drugs and devices currently under review to be approved
under the existing system, if the manufacture should so elect.
 Once DCBs are available, any sponsor with an active application
before the FDA could withdraw that application and submit it to
a DCB.  At the end of the transition period, the FDA would cease
to perform review process functions.  Because of the European
Union device experience and the fact that (European) notified
bodies with U.S. affiliates and branches are already operational,
it is likely that the transition period for devices can be shorter
than for drugs. <BR>

