<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation:Institutional Alternatives -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<h2>I. Institutional Alternatives for the Regulation of Drugs and Medical Devices</h2>
by Robert D. Tollison
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >EXECUTIVE SUMMARY<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >This paper presents an economic and institutional
analysis of the various organizational alternatives which might
be adopted to reform the Food and Drug Administration (FDA). 
The present FDA system is described as a government monopoly over
the introduction of new drugs and devices.  While this system
has served the public well in some respects, in recent years it
has proceeded with so much excessive caution against mistakes
that it has substantially slowed downed the introduction of beneficial
new drugs and devices. Thus the issue is, how can the present
system be reformed so as to speed up the introduction of beneficial
new products, while maintaining the existing legal standards of
safety and efficacy?<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >At one extreme from the present government
monopoly is <I>laissez faire,</I> meaning allowing private decisions
to be made by drug and device manufacturers with respect to the
marketing of their products.  Although this system has some merits,
it is generally found to be wanting in several respects due to
problems related to information and incentives in such an environment.
 For example, some firms may take unwarranted risks in the marketing
of new products where there is no government oversight.  Therefore
complete reliance on the goodwill and reputational capital of
firms is ruled out on such grounds.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Various other organizational arrangements involving
degrees of FDA oversight and degrees of privatization of the certification
process are considered here.  These include:  the removal of FDA
veto power over new products, a private monopoly organization
(laboratory) to review and certify new products subject to FDA
oversight, the contracting out to private entities of many of
the functions presently performed by the FDA, and competing private
firms as suppliers of certification services under FDA oversight.
 Indeed, the example of the Underwriters Laboratory as a private
certifier and standard-setter for a large variety of products
and commodities is discussed in some detail as an example of how
a private entity might work.  Also considered are issues of competing
jurisdictions and the international linkage of drug approval processes.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >All told, the analysis concludes that competing
private bodies under FDA oversight represent the best bet for
institutional reform.  In many respects, this system derives from
the &quot;European&quot; system presently in place for medical
devices.  The general point is that such a system offers the opportunity
for the United States to achieve greater benefits from the speedier
approval of beneficial new drugs and devices, while at the same
time maintaining the important legal standards for safety and
efficacy under the aegis of the FDA.  Moreover, allowing internationally
recognized drug review bodies in other countries, such as Great
Britain, to act as private entities in competition with U.S. private
entities would further insure that safe and effective products
would reach U.S. markets at the same time that they reach the
market in other advanced, industrial countries.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT > Introduction<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >There are a variety of alternative institutional
arrangements which could be called upon to regulate and monitor
the safety and effectiveness of the nation's supply of new drugs
and medical devices. These range from the present system, which
can be classified as a government monopoly on drug and device
certification, to a free market system in which government would
have no regulatory role at all. In between these two extremes
are a number of institutional alternatives which combine more
or less government oversight with more or less private involvement.
 There are costs and benefits of each system, and it is through
a careful consideration of these costs and benefits that one can
proceed to choose a system that provides the most  net benefits
 to medical consumers. In this regard it should be acknowledged
that the present system of government monopoly, as embodied in
the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and its accompanying legislation,
has undoubtedly provided substantial benefits over time to medical
consumers. This is not the issue. The point is to explore whether
the present process can be improved and strengthened so as to
continue to serve medical consumers into the next century. To
this end this paper examines the major institutional alternatives
for regulating drugs and medical devices, starting with the existing
system as presently administered by the FDA. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Government Monopoly<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The prevailing institutional arrangement under
which the FDA operates may be described as a government monopoly.
The oversight of new drugs, medical devices, and biologics is
centralized under FDA control. The hallmark of the FDA as a government
monopoly is the fact that producers have no alternative route
to the oversight of clinical research and the review and certification
of new drugs and devices other than through the FDA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The existing literature on government monopoly
bureaus dates from William Niskanen's pioneering microanalytic
study of bureaucracy (Niskanen 1971). Niskanen modeled a bureau
as an agent which bargained with an oversight committee for funding.
Due to its comparative advantage in information, the bureau always
won in the bargaining process. Indeed, Niskanen postulated a theory
in which the bureau was in a position to win all-or-none bargains
with the oversight committee, thereby expanding its budgetary
base or policy mandate well beyond the &quot;optimal&quot; level
(i.e., the level required for the competitive provision of the
good or service). The primary implication of Niskanen's theory
was therefore that government agencies and budgets were overlarge,
bloated or overreaching because of the bargaining power of individual
bureaus.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The effect of the oversight process on bureau
policy choices was taken up by Weingast and Moran (1983) in their
study of the Federal Trade Commission (FTC). These authors argued
that a bureau is the agent of its oversight committee when it
comes to policy choices. Indeed, they argued that bureaus are
perfect agents of the interest groups represented by oversight
committee members<sup><a href="foot.html">1</a></sup>.  Whatever the prevailing tradeoffs in policies
are (e.g., between consumers and producers, as deciphered, for
example, from the last election), the oversight committee imposes
these trade-offs on the bureau leadership. Reluctant or unreliable
bureau managers are replaced in a relentless drive to establish
the preferred political equilibrium. Weingast and Moran tested
their theory by showing how changing composition of the relevant
oversight committees led to a change in FTC behavior (i.e., case
selection). Their principal-agent approach is now the predominate
method for analyzing bureaucratic behavior in the literature.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There are two major implications from the literature
with respect to the FDA. Niskanen's work suggests that the FDA,
like other government bureaus, has more resources at its disposal
than are necessary to carry out its legislative mandate, and,
moreover, the FDA will seek to act beyond its Congressional mandate
in policy matters. Weingast and Moran's analytical framework suggests
a more subtle issue to confront, namely, that the FDA is doing
what its congressional sponsors (and the interest groups who support
them, including drug manufacturers) want it to do. If the latter
implication is, in fact, the case, this suggests that the idea
of &quot;reforming&quot; the FDA will be a difficult task indeed,
because the agency may be doing what the relevant interest groups
want it to do. Simply adopting an alternative institutional arrangement
(e.g., contracting out), while maintaining FDA veto authority
over new products, will not necessarily improve FDA behavior.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Given that the FDA is a government monopoly
that determines whether new medical products are safe and effective,
standard microeconomic theory predicts a higher FDA &quot;price&quot;
of approval and a lower quantity of approvals. And the property
rights structure of the FDA reinforces this bias. The FDA is not
the residual claimant for any additional gains realized from earlier
approval; manufacturers receive such gains. Yet if problems arise
from earlier approval, the FDA bears the costs in the form of
a public outcry or a backlash from congressional overseers.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The essential critique of FDA monopoly behavior
is that it spends inordinate resources to police unsafe drugs
and devices so that useful products are delayed in reaching patients.
The historical basis of this behavior is well documented, and
the political model that underlies it is clear. The consequences
of allowing an unsafe product on the market are obvious and politically
disastrous for the agency and its overseers. The consequences
of delaying an otherwise effective and safe drug or device (e.g.,
the lives saved as a result) are much less obvious and less politically
costly (although they may exact used higher &quot;costs&quot;
in terms of needless suffering or death.) The FDA therefore responds
to existing incentives and behaves in a predictable fashion. 
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Moreover, the personification of the consequences
of an unwise decision onto the leadership of the FDA and the relevant
members of Congress intensifies the problem. Voters may prefer
a more expeditious approval process, yet the fact that FDA administrators
face the consequences of toxicity directly implies that they will
prefer more &quot;insurance&quot; than the average voter would
&quot;buy&quot; in such a situation. Bureaucratic incentives thus
compound the problem, making the review process work more conservatively
than individuals in general would prefer. This type of argument
applies to all types of government programs whose outputs involve
risk and uncertainty (e.g., national defense). Thus, in general,
the FDA bureaucracy probably deploys more resources to the prevention
of harm from drugs and devices, at the expense of new drug and
device approval, than the average voter would prefer.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >What are the effects on the drug and medical
device industries of a politicized, risk-averse monopoly in charge
of approval? The expectation is what the empirical record reveals.
The return to innovation has fallen and become more uncertain
and research and development has moved offshore, so there is less
domestic innovation. One observes &quot;approval arbitrage,&quot;
whereby companies concentrate their R&amp;D efforts overseas where
the regulatory burden is not so onerous. More subtly perhaps,
the type of innovative activity may have changed. Owing to the
high costs and uncertain outcome of seeking government approval,
research may tend to focus on lower risk research projects which
manufacturers are confident will pass scrutiny and make money.
The high costs of approval, coupled with an imperfect capital
market, may also act to keep potential entrants out of the industry,
suggesting that the FDA has been &quot;captured&quot; by existing
manufacturers who are quite comfortable with the present system.
The increased uncertainty also raises the cost of capital for
drug and device firms, and acts to reduce the pool of capital
available for funding new research.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >One alternative to the current regime would
be to establish a clear description of  the requirements a new
drug or device must satisfy to be approved, thereby reducing some
of the arbitrariness in the approval process. This is one of the
proposals put forward by former Vice President Quayle's Council
on Competitiveness. This seemingly minor reform would have a number
of beneficial effects. Notably, it would remove much of the variance
in the returns to innovation. A more certain return would allow
firms to fund R&amp;D at lower cost of capital, perhaps spurring
innovation. Investments would no longer have to be certain winners,
and much important work that might have gone undone could be funded.
Fixed rules would also lower the cost of seeking approval by reducing
unanticipated and costly delays arising from requests for more
information. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Such reforms are not a panacea. The FDA is
a governmentally sanctioned monopoly without a profit motive,
and it will bear political costs if drugs and devices are approved
too quickly. To minimize this risk, the FDA will lobby hard to
adopt extremely stringent rules, perhaps to the point of further
reducing the number of approvals.   Even fixed rules will suffer
from &quot;mission creep,&quot; wherein annual revisions gradually
add to the total regulatory burden as the FDA seeks more and more
insurance against a drug or device failure and consumer advocacy
groups trumpet every perceived error by the agency. The FDA's
incentive will continue to revolve around security and budget.
As a government monopoly, there will be no outside competitive
verification that the rules of safe testing are the most efficient
and least costly set of rules that achieves the desired levels
of safety and effectiveness. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There are a galaxy of potential institutional
reforms that could be applied to the FDA, but there are large
problems which any meaningful reform must address. Chief among
these is the position of the FDA as a premarket monopolist. Given
the monopoly position of the FDA and its accompanying legal authority,
there is a lack of competitive structure in the U.S. drug oversight
and review process, so that service to new-drug sponsors is predictably
at levels that are extremely low and intolerable in other contexts.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The FDA, however, does not exist in a vacuum.
And here the experience of comparable agencies in other countries
may hold the key to understanding how the FDA process could be
improved. There is ample evidence from European countries such
as Great Britain and Germany and the evolving policies in the
European Union (EU) to suggest that the. United States has fallen
into an inefficient approval process. This evidence generally
suggests that European countries are able to bring new products
to the market faster than the United States, while maintaining
substantially equivalent safety and effectiveness results. This
suggests that the institutions of drug and device review and approval
in these countries have attained a better trade-off between protection
and progress than U.S. institutions have. That is, for an equivalent
amount of consumer protection they are able to bring products
to market faster. This competitive discrepancy in U.S. policy
has been apparent for decades, suggesting the need for fundamental
reform of the FDA.  Moreover, some linkage between the United
States and European systems might be in order so as to introduce
a competitive element into the U.S. system.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The present system in the United States works,
but it does not work as well as it could. This is the basic point.
The point is not to scrap the present system, but to make it at
least as effective and efficient as comparable drug and device
review systems around the world.  Recently, there has been a shift
in the preferences of oversight committees, a fact which suggests
(from the literature already reviewed) that the agency will have
to change and that the door is open to reform.  More importantly,
the example of Europe cannot be ignored or denied. These countries
have established faster and equally safe review processes at a
lower level of total expenditure. It is thus imperative that we
learn from the European experience, and explore linking U.S. policy
to European policy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT >A Simple Model of a Monopoly FDA<sup><a href="foot.html">2</a></sup><BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT >The cost of drugs or medical devices can be
characterized using a simple model (as shown in Figure 1) in which
the cost of precaution is traded-off against the cost of remedial
measures in the event of post-approval problems with a drug. Costs
of precaution are shown rising to the right as the level of precautionary
care is increased. These costs represent the effort by the FDA
to keep potentially harmful or useless products off the market.
Costs of remediation are shown declining from left to right based
on the assumption of declining marginal returns from increased
expenditures on precaution. These costs are the effort by the
FDA and manufacturers to engage in post-marketing surveillance
of problems with previously approved products and by manufacturers
to pay for damages their drugs have caused. Theoretically, the
&quot;optimum&quot; level of precautionary measures is at the
point of lowest total cost, and if all these costs are internalized,
this should be the expected level of precautionary care exercised
by manufacturers. On the surface a level of care set by the FDA
at this &quot;minimum&quot; level of total social cost should
guarantee the most efficient market for drug and device use.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >If the FDA could accurately determine the optimum
level of precaution, the government monopoly system might be efficient.
The problem is that it cannot. Regulatory standards are therefore
set according to some &quot;risk&quot; standard that satisfies
the internal requirements of the regulators. Regulators have no
incentive to choose a level of precaution less than the optimum,
so the &quot;optimum&quot; level of care becomes the lower bound
of the standard.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Current FDA standards are positioned somewhere
above the lower bound -- arguably, toward the higher end of the
scale -- resulting in an inefficiently high proportion of resources
put into prevention and a higher total cost than necessary. The
solution to this problem lies in providing better incentives for
firms to internalize the costs of precaution and remediation.
The rest of the paper explores several alternatives in this regard.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Self-Certification?<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >Self-certification of new drugs and devices
would be the functional equivalent of <I>laissez-faire</I> in
this area of public policy. Firms would be responsible for their
own testing and certification procedures for safety and effectiveness
(which could include the use of third-party certifiers), and would
stand to gain or lose in the marketplace depending upon the reliability
of their products. There are numerous layers of questions with
respect to self-certification. How would it work? How would it
work relative to alternative processes involving government oversight<sup><a href="foot.html">3</a></sup>?The
standard economic analysis of self-certification is related to
Akerlof's (1970) classic paper on &quot;lemons.&quot; He analyzed
a market situation in which sellers have perfect information about
product quality and buyers have limited (prepurchase) information.
In this case bad products come to be overvalued and good products
undervalued, and a sort of Gresham's Law prevails -- bad products
drive good products from the market. Bad products are the only
products that continue to be sold, if the market continues to
exist at all. There is thus an inefficiency in markets with asymmetric
information -- quality levels are too low, and firms have no incentive
to introduce higher quality products because they do not capture
the full benefits from their introduction. A market failure is
said to exist in such cases.<sup><a href="foot.html">4</a></sup>
<p>
This failure does not necessarily
imply that government intervention is the solution to the problem.
The market fails to provide the correct amount of quality relative
to a case where buyers have perfect information. However, since
government cannot provide perfect information either, the issue
becomes how the private sector might respond to such an issue
in conjunction with some form of government oversight.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There are a variety of ways that firms and
government might respond to the problem of asymmetric information,
some relevant to drugs and medical devices and some not. Firms
can offer guarantees and warranties, factors which would not seem
to apply in the case of drugs and devices. Firms can appeal to
third-party certification organizations such as medical laboratories
and set up a system of industry standards. This approach is directly
applicable to the case of drugs and devices, as will be discussed
below. An alternative approach, which is consistent with relying
upon a <I>laissez-faire</I> version of self-certification, consists
in relying upon firm investments in reputational capital to signal
the presence of high-quality products.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Klein and Leffler (1981) and others have shown
that under certain conditions, where firms have a comparative
advantage in producing and disseminating information about product
quality and where consumers have difficulty in deciphering product
claims before they actually consume the product, markets will
respond by making it worthwhile for firms to invest in brandname
capital (BNC). The concept is simple. Firms have incentives to
invest in BNC as a means of posting a bond with consumers. So
long as a firm produces products that are safe, reliable, and
trustworthy, consumers are willing to pay a premium for such products.
This premium constitutes a flow of payments that are capitalized
into BNC, and the premium represents a quality-assurance payment
by consumers. So long as firms deliver on promises of quality
and credibility, consumers will reward firms with premium payments
for brandnames. In equilibrium the premiums should just offset
the costs to firms of providing quality-assurance services to
consumers. If the firm makes a mistake or chooses to renege upon
its investment in BNC, it will be punished in the marketplace
as consumers will no longer pay a premium for the branded product.
And, indeed, there is ample evidence that drug firms are punished
substantially in this way (Jarrell and Peltzman 1985).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This is really a point about private contracting.
Klein and Leffler analyzed the role of implicit contracts when
explicit government-enforced contracts are incomplete or too costly
to establish. One form of an implicit enforcement mechanism is
for the potential defector to make an investment in a firm-specific,
nonsalvageable asset. This investment acts as an implicit guarantee
that the firm will not cheat the customer because cheating will
result in forfeiture of the investment. That is, the firm will
lose future business, and the investment in the nonsalvageable
asset will be lost. The purchase of a non-salvageable asset is
equivalent to posting a bond that assures non-cheating behavior.
For their part, customers pay a price premium for the product
to induce the firm not to cheat. In equilibrium the value of the
investment in the nonsalvageable asset just dissipates the &quot;protection
money&quot; offered by buyers so that the firm earns a normal
rate of return on its investment in quality-assurance and provides
a higher-quality product in exchange.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Looking at the argument more closely, one could
argue that asymmetrically distributed information frequently creates
markets. As information costs increase, the probability of informational
entrepreneurship increases, and this probability increases as
demand elasticities decrease. The price component of price elasticities
does not solely reflect the actual price charged for a good, but
the search costs consumers incur prior to paying the price as
well. To the consumer both the search costs and the price paid
for the good represent the cost of consumption. Hence, consumers
with inelastic demands will incur higher search costs, as well
as higher prices, with relatively little change in quantity-demanded.
Also, according to the Alchian and Allen theorem (Alchian and
Allen 1972), high fixed costs generate higher expenditures, (as
long as a couple must hire a baby-sitter when they go out, they
will treat themselves to a nicer dinner.)  High prices, high search
costs, and the opportunity cost of misinformation apply to the
drug and device markets, and a consumer will rationally spend
more on information collection upon incurring these costs. The
consumers' willingness to pay for information, and the high costs
of doing so on their own, create an opportunity for an informational
entrepreneur, who, by specializing in evaluating drugs and devices,
realizes scale economies due to the indivisible nature of information
(upon obtaining the information, his average cost drops as he
distributes the information). These medical products markets will
thus tend to develop informational entrepreneurs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In medical markets physicians and pharmacists
engage in informational intermediation. For instance, a Doctor's
diagnosis is informational intermediation: the patient has rationally
decided to pay for the doctor's specialization rather than invest
in the human and physical capital required to diagnose himself.
In prescribing a medicine the doctor reduces the patient's transaction
costs. The patient also invests in the additional safeguard of
a pharmacist who specializes in evaluating drugs. If a new medicine
which the pharmacist rates as more effective than as the prescribed
medicine exists, or if the patient's current medicinal regimen
conflicts with the prescription, the pharmacist consults with
the physician to change the prescription (if the applicable state
laws allow). This relationship existed prior to the advent of
the FDA, and in today's more advanced medical industry, it would
surely continue in the absence of the FDA. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >What prevents medical professionals from underinvesting
in medical information? Markets, of course, provide patients with
their first line of defense. A fly-by-night drug firm may invest
little or nothing in some placebo, rendering the credibility of
drug firms suspect. Patients, however, can quite easily inform
themselves about doctors and pharmacists. First, patients observe
the professionals' credible commitments; after years of training
the professionals have invested heavily in human capital and are
unlikely to underinvest in obtaining returns from the investment.
Moreover, doctors and pharmacists operate in a competitive market,
and their fees and volume of business will consequently reflect
their abilities. Lastly, health-care contracts, like all others,
are subject to fraud and liability law. If medical professionals
behave in an uninformed manner, they risk the assets they sunk
in their training and potential legal damages. Rationally, doctors
and pharmacists will require evidence regarding the effectiveness
and safety of a drug or device prior to prescribing or dispensing
it.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Cures for many health maladies occur within
a rather narrow band; only one basic biochemical structure may
effectively vaccinate individuals against the mumps, for instance.
The first firm to discover, patent, and market this structure
obtains a monopoly. A competitive market for medical innovation
exists in pursuit of these monopoly profits. Advocates of government
intervention often cite these factors as creating a &quot;race
for the bottom,&quot; in which firms, rushing their products to
the market, underinvest in both development and testing, leading
to a lowest common denominator market. Justice Brandeis's famous
phrase, however, is as incorrectly applied here as it was when
he coined it for the market for corporate charters. It is the
very existence and pursuit of monopoly profits which assures that
adequate research and testing would occur in the absence of government
intervention.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Without the ability to monopolize markets,
medical innovation would essentially cease. Medical research entails
investments of hundreds of millions of dollars to discover a potential
drug, and such costs are fixed. If, after incurring such massive
expenses and risks, competitive market conditions prevailed and
price was equated to marginal cost, the innovating firm would
not recover its research and development costs, but just the costs
associated with the production of the drug. Obviously, as the
probability of such an event increases, investments in discovery
will decrease. For a firm to invest in research and development
it must expect a downward-sloping demand curve.<sup><a href="foot.html">5</a></sup>
<p>
This, of course,
is a theory of the competitive provision of quality-assurance
by private firms. And it works in a general way in the economy
at large. Firms undertake investments in BNC, and markets punish
firms that renege on such investments. Informational entrepreneurship
does take place. Put another way, one does not tend to observe
pervasive &quot;lemons&quot; problems in modern economies. One
can go across the spectrum of the economy, and find firms behaving
in the manner predicted by the BNC theory. So there is little
doubt that self-certification plays a large role in providing
safe and effective products to consumers.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Would such a system work with drugs or medical
devices? Such a system is certainly an effective alternative to
the present regime of government monopoly. Nonetheless, there
are problematical aspects of a complete self-certification system.
The primary drawback would be that small, undercapitalized firms
might take risks in such an environment which would ultimately
be costly to consumers. The time required for drug development
(15 years) means that incentives might be distorted for small
firms. Such firms, which do not have enough resources to sustain
liability judgments, might very well provide less than optimal
amounts of testing so that consumer harm would result from such
a self-certification system. In other words, small firms might
simply &quot;roll the dice,&quot; hoping to come up with a winning
new product and not be able to sustain a liability judgment if
they are wrong and the product is not safe and effective and causes
harm to consumers. Such considerations dictate some type of government
oversight of drug and device testing.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Perhaps a more telling point about self-certification
is that it is analogous to refereeing your own paper as a academic
specialist. Peer review serves a valuable scientific service in
bringing to bear a more objective evaluation of the contribution
of a scientific paper or result. In addition, peer review generally
leads to an improvement in the quality of scientific papers. Government
oversight of drug and device testing may perform a similar service
for consumers that a self-certification process cannot. Peer review
processes, however, in general show the same kind of bias that
the FDA shows.  (i.e., peer review puts heavy emphasis on culling
out unusual but perhaps path-breaking papers.)<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It is thus an open question whether self-certification
in practice would lead to an effective system of drug and device
review and testing. And keep in mind that self-certification simply
means that firms can employ any feasible means to test and review
products. Market reactions would reward those firms who provided
the most cost-effective and reliable means of testing and certification.
The problem of small, fly-by-night firms attempting to limit testing
procedures or to mislead consumers would also be disciplined by
market reactions. Nonetheless, there would seem to be some role
for government in overseeing the medical product review process.
In laying out the standards or protocols for product testing,
for example, government could effectively forestall the small,
undercapitalized firm problem. The problem with government oversight
is how to delimit such a function so that innovation and new product
introduction are not stifled as a result. As the experience in
Europe has shown, there are areas, such as low-risk medical devices,
where firms can be allowed to self-certify medical products, subject
to meeting pre-specified government standards. This is not complete
<I>laissez-faire</I>, but it is a way to allow the market to work
with minimal government oversight. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Remove the FDA Veto Power?<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >A basic conundrum underlies the institutional
analysis of the FDA. If, in fact, the FDA is simply carrying out
the mandate of its legislative overseers, as Weingast and Moran's
(1983) analysis suggests, any institutional arrangement that maintains
the current government monopoly of oversight responsibility will
embody the same incentives as the current system, and will represent
only a marginal improvement over the status quo. This is why some
observers have advocated removing the FDA's veto power over new
drugs and devices (Kazman 1990).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This is an interesting proposal. In essence,
it represents a full-scale version of <I>laissez-faire</I> in
drug and device certification. In such a regime firms could approach
the market in any way they chose. They could self-certify, use
private third-party certifiers, or use the FDA, which would be
reconstituted as part of an overall competitive certification
process. Such a system has intriguing possibilities in that it
would undoubtedly foster innovation in the certification and testing
process, and the FDA would have to be responsive to such pressures
in this regard. And, over time, consumers would come to rely upon
those certification procedures that worked best. So if one were
to support a <I>laissez-faire</I> approach to certification, letting
the FDA compete in this process might be a good idea.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Such a system is not without problems, however.
In general, it would suffer from the same basic problem that completely
privatized certification suffers; namely, there would likely be
informational failures and asymmetries such that higher quality
products are driven from the market. For example, in a combined
public-private review process without a government veto, small,
undercapitalized firms would have the option to take excessive
risks in the form of introducing incompletely tested products
into the marketplace. In the event of subsequent problems consumer
welfare would suffer.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >So the issue of removing the FDA veto is another
version of the issue of whether <I>laissez-faire</I> will work
as a certification process. Such a system would undoubtedly be
an improvement over some alternative institutional arrangements,
but it seems apparent that some form of government oversight is
necessary to insure that the certification process works in the
interest of consumers. The key is to be able to design an oversight
mechanism that will foster the use of private, competitive testing
procedures and that will speed approval and hasten innovation
in both products and testing procedures while maintaining a core
of essential government oversight over the process. Indeed, limited
government oversight would probably work better than a system
with a vetoless FDA. The presence of a vetoless FDA alongside
alternative private certification institutions would undoubtedly
inhibit the emergence of a robust private certification process
for a variety of fairly obvious reasons, such as the problem that
private firms would have in competing against a government-subsidized
FDA. And for that matter, in the present environment of product
liability lawsuits, companies may not have any choice except to
use the FDA for product approvals.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Direct Government Involvement in
Certification: The Case of the FAA<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >This particular institutional setting involves
emphasis on self-certification by manufacturers with the direct
involvement of government in the process. In fact, in this case
one does not have to rely upon a hypothetical discussion. The
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) currently implements such
a system for airplane development.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In aviation the key approval required for a
new aircraft comes in the form of a type certification.<sup><a href="foot.html">6</a></sup>All
aircraft flown in the National Airspace System must have a current
airworthiness certificate which implies that a type certification
was granted to the original manufacturer<sup><a href="foot.html">7</a></sup>. This certification requires
that all parts and processes used in the manufacture of the airplane
and that the flying characteristics pass government requirements.
As with drug and device approvals, this certification can be expensive
to obtain.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The basic process is shown below. Manufacturers
begin the design of a new aircraft with certification requirements
in mind. Firms tend to use many existing parts and subassemblies
that have previously been certified as well as certified production
techniques. Before they begin to build the first components, most
manufacturers submit an application of the new design to the FAA.
The FAA responds by putting together a certification team. The
size of this team depends on the complexity and size of the new
aircraft. A small, single-engine aircraft for general aviation
may only involve a few people while a large commercial airliner
may involve a team of hundreds of members. The certification team
meets and reviews the new design. Based on the newness and the
degree of innovation, they inform the manufacturer of certification
requirements after obtaining the manufacturer's input.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Initial Design Concept  Firm Submits Concept
to FAA  FAA Organizes Certification Team   Firm Builds and Tests
Aircraft  FAA Reviews Firm's Test  Final Approval<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The FAA provides inspectors and oversight of
the new aircraft's development and production. Some of these FAA
personnel essentially work full time at the larger plants overseeing
the development and production process. They supervise the testing
of components and manufacturing procedures and verify adherence
to FAA regulations. Thus, the function of independent testing
is performed concurrently with development and production by a
team composed of FAA and company personnel.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This method provides for incremental approval
due to the continuous certification process. The theory is that
if all components are certified as safe, the full aircraft has
a higher probability of being safe. The FAA requires extensive
flight testing with special emphasis on key flight regimes. This
means that not only does the plane have to have predictable flight
characteristics for its intended functions, but the requirements
are continually updated based on past accidents and problems.
At the end of these tests the FAA awards an air worthiness certificate
that allows the sale and use of the aircraft for commercial and
private purposes. The FAA may also require additional testing
as the result of subsequent accidents, maintenance data, or general
safety concerns after the aircraft has entered service. However,
the bulk of the tests required for recertification will be done
by the manufacturer and submitted to the FAA for approval.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There are several important features of this
type of certification procedure. First, unlike the FDA procedure,
it gives the manufacturer considerable control over the time required
for certification. Firms can invest heavily in testing in order
to get a product to market more quickly. Part of this is accomplished
by careful planning and coordination with the FAA in the initial
meetings. The rest can be accomplished by investing in flight
test facilities or services. Second, firms are less under the
control of government schedules and bureaucracies. Third, the
self-certification system provides a slightly weaker liability
position for the firms. The firm has only itself and a few government
inspectors to uncover all problems. Thus, it is possible that
this shorter approval process has a higher cost in the form of
greater liability exposure.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Indeed, the element of self-certification involved
in the production of aircraft has contributed to the liability
problems of the industry, and there is still the &quot;refereeing
your own paper&quot; type of problem with self-certification systems.
And even with a great deal of government oversight, it seems unlikely
that drug firms would do their own certifying. Independent certification
provides a form of quality-assurance to consumers that self-certification
cannot. For such reasons the FAA system does not seem amenable
to the drug review process, and in some respects would probably
come to represent a bureaucratic nightmare for the industry. Nonetheless,
elements of this model are applicable to some medical devices.<sup><a href="foot.html">8</a></sup>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Private Monopoly with Government
Oversight<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >This alternative consists in establishing a
single national laboratory or certified body which would conduct
the oversight and review of drug and device development programs
and applications for marketing approval under the supervision
of the FDA. The primary benefit of such a system would be that,
relative to the present system, a private body would have an incentive
to operate efficiently and to innovate in the review process to
a degree that the present system does not. This presumes, of course,
that some of the gains from innovation could be retained by the
private body. The primary disadvantage of this process is that
the continuation of government veto power would leave the present
system little changed. For example, the private monopoly right
could be revoked by the FDA if the monopolist deviated substantially
from the preferences of the bureaucracy which runs the present
system. So, at best, private monopoly with government oversight
would represent  only a modest improvement over the present system.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Moreover, such a system brings with it a host
of problems familiar to students of public utility regulation.
How would the private monopoly be chartered? How would it set
prices for its services?  If simply left to its own devices, the
private monopoly laboratory would charge monopoly prices for its
services where &quot;price&quot; is construed to be some combination
of money cost and waiting time for certification services.  Such
monopolistic behavior would retard the review process relative
to a more competitive arrangement for the provision of testing
services.  Any attempt to regulate the private monopoly would
rest upon issues similar to those raised in public utility regulation.
Would the monopoly right be rebid, say, every ten years? Would
there be extensive and detailed price regulation? What regulatory
biases and gamesmanship would result? <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This morass of regulatory issues can be avoided
by having more than one certified body to which firms can turn
for services. And unless some sort of economic justification,
such as economies of scale, can be found, there is no compelling
reason to have a single monopoly laboratory with government oversight.
Such a system would be cumbersome, and while perhaps exhibiting
better behavior than the present system of government monopoly
in terms of innovation and cost control, there would not likely
be that much difference between the two in practice.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >A simple model of a monopoly laboratory is
presented in the appendix. The moral of this analysis is simply
that the regulation of a private monopoly certification service
with respect to the provision of safety services, even assuming
a benign overseer with a sole interest in consumer welfare, would
be quite complicated. And while there are examples of such systems
in the private sector (the Institute of Nuclear Power Operations),
it is not easy to see how such a scheme could be applied to the
case of medical products. Regulation of a private monopoly is
difficult and problematical in any event, so that there is no
reason to expect the case of drugs and devices to be any different.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Government Monopoly with Contracting
Out<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >This system of institutional review would maintain
FDA pre-market approval for new drugs and devices, but contract
out the actual certification programs. This is roughly equivalent
to what has been done to date by the FDA from time to time at
every level of the system except final approval.  It is also equivalent
to other government procurement programs under which specified
products or services are purchased from qualified contractors.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Contracting out is quite different from the
system described below as government oversight with competing
private laboratories. In the case of contracting out, private
contractors would bid to the FDA for business, while in a private
competing laboratories model, product sponsors would solicit the
services of private laboratories directly. In either case, the
FDA would regulate the private contractors or the private competing
laboratories.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The distinction between the two systems is
important. Undoubtedly, there are benefits to the contracting
out system relative to the present government monopoly with in-house
certification by the FDA. Private contractors could be expected
to be more efficient and innovative than government in-house reviewers.
Such incentives could reside, for example, in the concept of a
&quot;regulatory lag.&quot; Where equally reliable testing and
review procedures can be performed at lower cost, profits on a
given contract will improve. There are thus persistent incentives
to improve the design and review of product development programs
under contracting out that do not exist under the present system.
Over time, contracting costs will fall as firms pass along the
savings in bids for future work. Contracting out would also increase
the speed of the review process (as it could be done concomitantly),
and more drugs and devices could be reviewed at any point in time,
with consequent beneficial feedback for firms' investments in
research and development.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The other side of the coin, however, is that
government contracting carries with it a host of incentive and
other problems which have been studied in detail in the literature
(see Scherer 1964; McCall 1970; and Baron, 1972). It is not always
clear, for example, that competitive bidding yields the least-cost
supplier of services. Moreover, there have been a host of problems
associated with cost overruns. Also, the bureaucracy created by
delegating to the outside, and then reintegrating the results
into a review process that has always been beyond the agency's
managerial ability to control, simply increases complexity and
plays to FDA's weaknesses. For such reasons it is more likely
that the benefits of government contracting can be obtained without
the associated costs by adoption of a system of private laboratories
which would compete directly for the business of drug and device
firms. Such a system is closely akin to certain models in the
EU and several European countries, and is discussed in more detail
in the next  two sections.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Competing Private Firms with Government
Oversight<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >This institutional arrangement would consist
of maintaining a final governmental review over new drugs and
high-risk devices, while relying upon competing private firms
for  sponsor oversight and certification services.  These private
certification firms would do a lot more than simply issue certificates.
They could perform a range of functions, currently performed by
the FDA, that are needed in order to be able to certify.  This
procedure is seen in the present European system for medical device
certification, so that examples of how such a system would work
can be drawn from the European experience. This model is also
analogous to the way in which the Underwriter's Laboratory works
in the United States; a discussion of the Underwriter's Laboratory
is thus also in order.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The European medical device system embodies
a set of standards which devices must meet. Although only a small
fraction of devices need to be regulated as drugs are regulated
(i.e., need to have a pre-market approval), it nevertheless is
instructive to examine how European device regulation works for
the entire range of devices.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In order to meet the required standards, manufacturers
are allowed a great deal of flexibility. For some low-risk devices,
manufacturers are allowed to self-certify that their products
meet the necessary standards. This &quot;light-touch&quot; regulation
requires only that the manufacturers, in addition to meeting strict
manufacturing and quality-control standards, maintain records
as to the reliability of a device and be available for questioning
should a problem develop.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >For higher-risk products manufacturers must
seek certification from third-parties, the so-called &quot;notified
bodies.&quot; Examples of such bodies, or private laboratories,
are BSI in Great Britain, TUVs in Germany, and KEMA in the Netherlands.
 Notified bodies supply certification services to firms, based
on analyses and oversight that they do in the form of testing
products and inspecting manufacturing systems. Approval of a product
by a notified body is tantamount to government approval:  the
product can then be marketed.  The notified bodies themselves
are subject to regulation by government with respect to their
operations as certifiers. In addition, as in the United States,
there is post-introduction reporting of adverse incidents. Such
incidents must be reported by manufacturers and users, and in
cooperation with national government authorities the manufacturer
makes an appropriate decision with respect to correcting problems
or taking the product off the market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Thus, the European system relies upon elements
of self-certification for low-risk devices, third-party certification
for higher-risk devices, and post-market surveillance of adverse
incidents. The role of government in this process is limited to
standard-setting, regulation of the third-party certifying agencies,
scrutiny of the clinical development program, and dealing with
adverse incident problems once products are in the marketplace.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The effects of this system have been salutary.
Approval times are considerably faster in Europe -- 250 days as
compared to 820 days for a PMA review in the U.S. (Wilkerson Group,
1995.)  And there is no evidence that the European system produces
less safe outcomes than the United States system. It is therefore
possible that a system based on the elements of self-certification
(subject to government standards) and third-party certification
can produce a marked improvement over the government monopoly
system presently in place in the U.S. Indeed, the FDA has proposed
a trial of the use of third-party certification for low-risk devices.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It is not a great leap to extend the European
system from devices to drugs. The U.S. requires a cumbersome IND
filing before first human testing while the U.K., for example,
does not.  At the market-approval stage, the review authority
in the U.K. gives more responsibility to a committee of independent
medical experts who have a consulting relationship to the agency.
 Moreover, the FDA, being the only regulator in the U.S. drug
market, necessarily acts differently than regulatory agencies
in, say, the U.K. and Germany. In the case of the EC's decentralized
 registration procedures, each national authority must compete
with 11 other national regulatory agencies in the EU, each agency
being concerned with the price of medicinal products in its domestic
market due to their respective government's role in the provision
of health care services.  It is also worth emphasizing that the
European agencies are fee-based. They thus have a meaningful profit
motive which arguably drives them to provide speedier and more
efficient reviews of new drugs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT >The Underwriter's Laboratory<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT >There is a certification system in the United
States for various products and equipment which operates in a
fashion  similar to some aspects of the European system for medical
device review. This system is typified by the activities of the
Underwriter's Laboratory (UL), and is worth considering in some
detail.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL is a large, not-for-profit organization
that certifies over 14,000 types of products using over 650 standards
(a &quot;standard&quot; is a detailed specification for a product
class that may run to many pages).  In addition to electrical
appliances and equipment, the UL also certifies automotive and
mechanical products, fire-resistant building materials, bullet-resistant
glass, and OSHA-designated &quot;hazardous location&quot; products,
among many others.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL tests and certifies products which present
inherent potential hazards to life and property. Except in special
cases, the UL does not offer an effectiveness mandate, but is
only concerned with safety issues. The exceptions are life-safety
products such as fire extinguishers and smoke detectors. In these
cases performance issues are also considered. The UL has never
underwritten any risk of the products that they certify. The business
of the UL is information; they are solely a testing and certifying
body.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL is completely private and independent.
There is no statutory or court-ordered requirement that forces
manufacturers to seek UL approval. Such activity is a purely voluntary
act on the part of manufacturers. The UL holds no <I>de facto</I>
or <I>de jure</I> monopoly on safety certification. In the United
States there are several competing standard-setting laboratories.
Not all laboratories use the UL's standards, but there is a high
degree of similarity among the competing standards. The UL is
much larger and older than any of its competitors and holds the
dominant position in the market. The primary regulator of the
UL and its competitors is the Occupational Safety and Health Administration
(OSHA).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >As noted above, the UL publishes over 650 standards
(the guidelines under which they test and approve products). These
standards are known to manufacturers in advance and cover specific
end-products. New standards are written according to the evolution
of market demand. As the demand for UL certification increases,
the UL formulates initial guidelines outlining their testing procedure
and the criteria products will have to meet to receive certification.
This information is distributed to interested bodies, such as
councils of manufacturers, insurers, and consumers. The UL asks
for comments and criticisms from these organizations, amending
their approach as necessary. This process results in a &quot;proposed
standard&quot; which undergoes the same scrutiny as the preliminary
information. The process evolves into &quot;published standards&quot;
which are made available to manufacturers. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >UL approval is not equivalent to governmental
approval. Ultimately, the use of products is still governed by
law, frequently under the jurisdiction of local inspectors, such
as the Fairfax County Fire or Building Inspector. In theory, and
perhaps in practice, local codes can ban a UL-approved product
or order its removal. In practice, such actions are extremely
rare.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >No form of legal mandate requires a product
to display a UL approval mark. However, many retailers are reluctant
to carry products lacking UL approval, and, occasionally, insurers
may deny liability coverage for unapproved products. As in the
textbook case of an investment in a non-salvageable asset, all
concerned parties benefit from the transaction, and firms, insurers,
and the UL all have incentives to maintain high quality standards.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The certification process begins when a manufacturer
delivers a batch of product to the UL. The UL informs the firm
of the standard under which they will test the product. If the
manufacturer agrees to continue, the UL prepares a safety report
and offers a &quot;procedure&quot; to be kept by the manufacturer
at his facility. The procedure lists the specific building materials
of the sample batch, as well as the manufacturing procedure, and
so on. The firm cannot deviate from the procedure, or they will
lose UL approval. The UL has field inspectors who visit manufacturers'
facilities to insure that the procedure is being followed.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The fee that the UL charges for its services
is based on a cost-of-testing approach, and depends on the testing
required by the particular published standard that covers the
good in question. Cost is also affected by the manufacturer's
choice of materials used in the product. If it is manufactured
using mostly UL approved materials, testing is less costly than
otherwise. The UL charges a flat fee for its field inspection
service and charges for its inspectors by the hour.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Notwithstanding all the discussion of the UL's
independence and the discipline imposed on the UL by the market,
it faces a specific regulatory burden. In fact, the UL is an actual,
working example of a competing laboratory with government regulation.
The UL and its direct competitors are certified by OSHA as &quot;nationally
recognized testing laboratories&quot; (NRTL), in accordance with
specific statutory guidelines. OSHA offers certification to any
laboratory that can meet its standards. The standards are not
arbitrary, and are available from OSHA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL's direct competitors are also NRTLs.
Not all NRTLs are standard-setting bodies. Many use the UL's standards
directly, and offer some compensating differential in cost or
ancillary services to attract business. Some set their own standards
and testing protocols, independent of the actions of the UL, though
there do not seem to be great differences among the competing
standards. Typically, the UL's direct competitors are smaller,
newer, and for-profit enterprises. The UL's not-for-profit status
is likely the result of its curious history and inception. Since
its beginning, the UL's stated mission has been &quot;testing
for public safety.&quot; Though the UL has received revenue to
defray the costs of testing, its activities were always deemed
to be a public service. The UL maintains this position (over the
complaints of its competitors), and this history motivated the
UL to change its status to a not-for-profit organization.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >No other country uses UL standards, but most
foreign countries have their own certifying bodies, testing laboratories,
and standards. There is no set of bilateral or unilateral reciprocal
agreements with respect to UL standards. However, there are &quot;memoranda
of understanding&quot; between the UL and many of its foreign
counterparts. Though these agreements do not call for accepting
the certification of an overseas laboratory, they are reciprocal
on many levels, and in many instances the standards are similar
across national boundaries.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL's relationship with Canada goes beyond
a memorandum of understanding. The UL is certified by the National
Standards Council of Canada to test products for use in Canada
under standards specifically written for Canada. All products
approved for Canadian consumption bear the UL mark. The UL's Canadian
standards are similar but not identical to the UL's U.S. standards.
The UL is currently involved in writing common standards for the
United States and Canada.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL has not been exposed to excessive liability
concerns. There have been few lawsuits brought against the UL,
and these have been considered to be weak. The UL is occasionally
subpoenaed in connection with a lawsuit brought against a manufacturer,
but it provides no expert witnesses or any trial support. The
fact that the UL, as an independent third party, has certified
a product does not make the UL jointly liable for that product's
performance in the field. Neither does UL certification attach
the UL to manufacturer negligence. Basically, the UL answers two
questions: one, has the manufacturer taken the appropriate safeguards;
and two, was the product batch sent to the UL for testing found
to be safe? The UL mark signifies that the sample sent for testing
was found to be safe under a published standard, and the UL expects
that further products manufactured in the same manner using similar
materials are also likely to be safe. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The UL model, of course, is not a perfect fit
for the purposes of new drug and device review and certification.
 More is involved in drug and device approval than simply testing
a batch of products according to some manufacturer's standard.
 This is obvious.  Nonetheless, given the legal right to do so,
it is possible then the UL could seek to expand its capabilities
to be able to perform these functions.  This could involve the
retention of qualified experts to make judgments according to
the necessary standards.  In other words, both the UL and the
FDA can test a product according to specifications, but neither
the UL nor the FDA can test a drug's efficacy and safety.  Rather,
they would have to evaluate the evidence  by first checking that
it was obtained correctly and that it is accurate and truthful,
 and then that it has been interpreted correctly and satisfies
the law.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Both the European system for devices and the
UL illustrate the potential gains from applying a private certification
system in the United States to new devices and drugs. When coupled
with careful regulation of the certification industry and its
incentives, the private supply of testing services can potentially
provide as much  or more safety and effectiveness as the present
system, while speeding the flow of new drugs and devices into
the medical marketplace.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >These private bodies could do a great deal
more than simply certify new products.  They would perform a scientific
review function to ensure the accuracy and truthfulness and interpretation
of results such that the existing law is satisfied.  Privatizing
this function and devolving it from the FDA has many advantages,
not the least of which is to afford the opportunity to bring the
very best scientists into the process of evaluating the safety
and effectiveness of new medical products. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Moreover, as discussed earlier in the analysis
of self-certification systems, there is little basis to expect
a &quot;race for the bottom&quot; out of this system. The FDA
would have regulatory oversight over the private laboratories
and certifiers, as well as review authority over their recommendations.
Such factors, as well as market incentives to maintain reputational
capital as a competent testing organization, would insure a healthy
evolution of private certification laboratories.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Competing Jurisdictions<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >One way to look at the problem of institutional
reform of the FDA, building upon the example of the EU, is to
suggest th
<h2>I. Istitutional Alternatives for the Regulatio
evolution of EU institutions and their faster approval times may
reflect the reality that the individual country processes for
drug and device review must compete with one another, and such
competition has beneficial effects.  In the decentralized drug
review procedure of the EU system, sponsors can choose the national
agency to which they submit first.  This has resulted in intense
competition among the national agencies.  Indeed, Great Britain's
agency has done a marketing tour of the United States touting
its fast response time and its competitive cost.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The FDA monopoly in the United States. is not
in a similar position to the European agencies. So linking the
U.S. process to those in other countries might well make the issue
of institutional reform moot. Countries could choose review institutions
as they saw fit, and jurisdictional competition would mold these
institutions over time to comply with constituent interests. Jurisdictions
and firms which were effective would receive more revenue from
drug approvals, and so on. Obviously, jurisdictional competition
involves both costs and benefits, and it is a big leap to imagine
that the United States would be willing to enter a simple international
agreement under which products approved in other countries could
be marketed in the United States But some such linkage may be
desirable to support genuine institutional reform in the United
States<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Indeed, the European model provides at least
two implications for the United States  First, Europe's national
interagency competition within the EU is a model of how competition
between private certifiers could work in the United States  Second,
Europe's governmental certifying bodies can be set up in competition
with the FDA by appropriate international recognition agreements.
 Some further analysis of this latter type of action would be
useful.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The textbook case for jurisdictional competition
is the example of corporate law in the United States Each state
has evolved an individualized chartering system for corporations,
and have competed for corporate chartering revenues for more than
100 years. Over this time Delaware has become a preferred jurisdiction
in which to incorporate, but firms can incorporate in any state.
The issues, then, are why does this system of corporate chartering
work so well and could it be extended by analogy to the process
of drug and device review?<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The definition of a corporation is simple --
it is a business entity characterized by share ownership and limited
liability. The first component simply constitutes a contract between
a firm and its equity suppliers, and how a state governs this
relationship does not affect any other state's relations with
the firm. Jurisdictional reciprocity, therefore, is contingent
upon each jurisdiction recognizing limited liability as desirable.
Consequently, reciprocity does not require agreement on any other
issues, and jurisdictions are free to experiment with various
forms of corporate governance and judge their efficiency by how
the market reacts. States subsequently become responsive to the
changing needs of business, and as long as they do not respond
with severe alterations of the limited-liability principle, they
can change virtually any other component of corporate governance
without affecting the reciprocity agreement.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Defining a corporation is possibly easier than
defining what constitutes a &quot;safe and effective&quot; drug.
In agreeing to reciprocity, jurisdictions would state that they
accept the definitions of other jurisdictions, and in the case
of drugs and devices, that they approve of the testing methods
employed. A reciprocity agreement, therefore, would inevitably
require some minimum standards for membership. These standards,
however, constrain the ability of jurisdictions to differentiate
their processes, and thereby allow the political market to signal
its preferences. While jurisdictions in the market for corporate
charters differentiate their products through the governance components,
a market in drug and device certification has no margins upon
which to operate except for an agreed-upon concept of the definition
of  safety and effectiveness and the methods for testing.  Changes
in this definition necessarily alter the nature of reciprocity.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Moreover, rather than the continuous and infinite
relationship between corporations and their domiciles, drug and
device approvals entail discrete transactions. Firms do not evaluate
where they should submit all of their products, but consider each
case individually. If a jurisdiction changes its process, firms
can submit future products to other jurisdictions. In a worst-case
scenario a race for the bottom could occur as each jurisdiction
simply rushed to approve the products manufactured within its
borders and export them to other markets. Nonetheless, this is
not what appears to have happened among European countries. To
the contrary, competition among countries has led to the evolution
of outstanding agencies for drug and device review and approval;
there has not been a race to the bottom.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >International agreements are, of course, not
easy to negotiate, and reciprocity in drug and device approval
would be no exception to this rule. Most, if not all, of the benefits
of jurisdictional competition, however, could probably be obtained
by adopting a system with competing certifiers in the United States
Indeed, a rigorous private certification industry in the United
States would likely strengthen the prospects for linkage with
the systems of other countries, as such a change in policy would
put our system on par with the structure of the emerging European
systems.</FONT><sup><a href="foot.html">9</a></sup>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Conclusion</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The weight of the evidence presented here suggests
that improvements are clearly possible in the drug and medical
device certification processes as they currently operate in the
United States The evidence that certain European systems perform
better than the FDA process is compelling. The model of government
oversight with private certifiers has several advantages. It would
bring state of the art scientists and scientific methods into
the process of drug and device certification. It would foster
innovation in drug and device evolution, oversight, and certification
procedures, leading to lower costs, faster approval rates, and
enhanced safety and effectiveness. It would cut down on bureaucratic
red tape and delay. It would not require any changes in the existing
legal standards applied by the FDA. For these and various other
reasons, movement to a system of competitive certification performed
by private laboratories and testing groups commends itself for
the consideration of policymakers.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
